<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    Friday, Jan. 7, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bush, McCain Clash at Debate
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WEST COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Sen. John McCain
clashed sharply over tax cuts in the second Republican campaign debate. McCain
said it was fiscally irresponsible to promise a huge tax cut that is based on a
surplus the U.S. might not have. Bush retorted that his plan was more generous
than McCain's for lower income taxpayers and added firmly: "There is enough
money to take care of Social Security. There is enough money to take care of the
basic services of government, and there is enough money to give the people a
substantial tax cut. And that's what I intend to do."
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Cubans Rally for Elian's Return
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   MIAMI (AP) -- CARDENAS, Cuba (AP) -- Tens of thousands of people from Elian
Gonzalez's hometown rallied in a seaside plaza Friday night to demand his return
from Miami. The rally matched the emotional content of angry demonstrations by
Cuban exiles in Miami who fiercely oppose a U.S. government decision to return
Elian to his father's home here. Elian's great-uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez of Miami,
has temporary custody of the boy and want to keep him permanently in the United
States. He says he can give Elian a better life off the communist island. The
U.S. government has ruled that Elian and his father should be reunited by next
Friday, Jan. 14.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mexican Students Reject Offer
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Striking Mexican students rejected university officials'
offer Friday to meet some of their demands to end an eight-month strike that has
shut down the nation's largest public school. The strikers, who seized the
campus of the National Autonomous University of Mexico on April 20, said the
offer did not go far enough. The students said they are now demanding the
release of several students arrested after launching bottle rockets at the U.S.
Embassy during a December demonstration. While there are 268,000 students at the
university, the strikers represent a few thousand.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
China Sentences Teen-Age Dissident
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   BEIJING (AP) -- A 19-year-old dissident in eastern China's Jiangsu province
has been sentenced to three years in prison on subversion charges, a human
rights group reported Saturday. Family members who recently visited Wang were
told he had been refusing food, the fifth time he has staged a hunger strike
since he was arrested last February, the center said. Wang is believed to have
been convicted for writing an open letter to President Jiang Zemin urging the
Communist Party to eradicate rampant corruption, the Information Center said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Speculation Looms in Shipyard Killings
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   SEATTLE (AP) -- A fired shipyard employee gunned down two men in a
deliberate act of revenge that was elaborately plotted, prosecutors alleged in
filing murder charges Friday. Kevin William Cruz, 30, was charged with two
counts of aggravated first-degree murder and two counts of attempted murder in
the Nov. 3 attack. Cruz was fired from the Northlake Shipyard in January 1999.
Prosecutors believe he harbored a grudge because he was fired soon after the
company's insurance company cut off his benefits for a work-related injury,
saying he wasn't really hurt. Cruz was arrested Tuesday and was being held on $4
million bail.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Rapper Puff Daddy Faces Shooting Lawsuit
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Rap star Sean "Puffy" Combs was hit with a $50 million
lawsuit Friday by a man who was shot in a Times Square-area nightclub last week.
Robert Thompson, 38, of Danbury, Conn., alleges he was shot in the right
shoulder by Combs protege Jamal Barrow during a dispute in Club NY on Dec. 27.
Kenneth Nolan, Thompson's lawyer, said Combs was sued because it is unclear
whether the rapper encouraged Barrow to fire and whether Combs had a gun in the
club. Nolan said that if he learns that Combs did nothing illegal, he will amend
the complaint.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Soars to Record High
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Investors brushed off signs of inflationary pressure as the
Dow Jones industrials soared into record territory Friday. The Nasdaq composite,
which tumbled earlier this week, recorded its best day in history rising 155.45
to 3,882.58. The Dow rose 269.30 to close at 11,522.56, topping its Dec. 31
closing record. Fueled by consumer goods stocks, the rally wiped out the last
remnants of Tuesday's 359-point tumble.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Knicks Beat Magic 94-86
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- Allan Houston scored 23 points and Latrell Sprewell
had 19 Friday night as the New York Knicks held off the Orlando Magic 94-86 for
their third straight win. The victory was the 10th in 13 games for the Knicks,
who improved to 9-3 since Patrick Ewing returned to the lineup after being on
the injured list for the first six weeks of the season. Ewing had 18 points,
nine rebounds and three blocks, while reserve Kurt Thomas finished with 10
points and nine rebounds. Darrell Armstrong led Orlando with 16 points. Corey
Maggette had 14 points, while reserve Chris Gatling added 11 points and 10
rebounds.
</P>
</TEXT>
