<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 00:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pataki: let welfare families keep more child support money  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Child advocates are praising Gov. George Pataki for
his proposal to let welfare families keep more of the child support payments
they are receiving from non-custodial parents.
<P>
	   Included in Pataki's 2000-2001 state budget plan to be presented to the
Legislature on Tuesday will be a provision doubling the limit from $50 to $100 a
month in support payments that families on welfare can receive.
</P>
<P>
	   Pataki will make his sixth budget proposal to the state Legislature in
Albany on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   The child advocates said Friday that if any families need the extra money,
it's those on public assistance.
</P>
<P>
	   "It has always been an issue with us for those lucky enough to be getting
child support that they and their children should see the benefits of that
support," said Elie Ward, executive director of Statewide Youth Advocacy. "The
money is supposed to be for the kids."
</P>
<P>
	   The amount of child support that people on welfare can receive is limited so
taxpayers can be reimbursed for the cost of the public benefits their families
are taking in.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1999, the Pataki administration reported that about $1 billion in child
support payments were made in New York. Of that, about $190 million was
forwarded to the state so state, county and federal taxpayers could be
reimbursed for the cost of welfare payments.
</P>
<P>
	   Ward said that for some families on welfare, getting an extra $50 or $75 a
month could even take them off public assistance.
</P>
<P>
	   Christine McKenna, associate director of another youth advocacy group,
SENSES, said increasing the pass through can be an incentive for the custodial
parent to cooperate in finding the missing parent who owes child care and to
make that missing parent more willing to pay up.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's really frustrating if they are socked for $120 or $150 and their child
is only seeing $50," McKenna said.
</P>
<P>
	   Other child-related initiatives the governor said would be in his next
budget included:
</P>
<P>
	   -Increasing from 159,000 to 178,000 the number of child care slots available
for the children of working poor families.
</P>
<P>
	   -Increasing the state's child care block grant from $626 million in the
current fiscal year to $711 million in 2000-01. In addition to providing more
day care, the increase would also expand oversight and monitoring of child care
facilities, improve services for the children of migrant workers and provide for
the fingerprinting of all regulated child care providers, Pataki said.
</P>
<P>
	   -Expanding the state's "celebrating fatherhood" campaign to encourage males
to voluntarily take part in their children's lives.
</P>
<P>
	   -Expanding efforts to determine whether parents paying child support have
health care programs which could also cover those children. If the children are
now on welfare, their health care is paid by taxpayers through Medicaid.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
