<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Another $12 million put toward farm land easements  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - The highest amount ever - $12 million - will be
funneled this year into a state program designed to keep crucial tracts of
farmland out of developers' hands.
<P>
	   Fifteen communities will get the latest state grants under the Farmland
Protection Program. They bring to $30 million the amount allocated since 1996
under the farm preservation program.
</P>
<P>
	   "By investing now, we're helping to ensure that the heritage of farm
families and the bucolic landscapes of our state will survive well into the next
century," Pataki said.
</P>
<P>
	   The grants are awarded to town or county farmland protection boards and are
designed to fund up to 75 percent of the projects. Municipalities must
contribute the other 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   No farmland is actually bought as a result of the program. Rather, easements
on the land are purchased which will prevent the property in the future from
being developed. That guarantees that farms will remain farms, even if the land
passes into other hands or is willed to relatives.
</P>
<P>
	   For farmers, the selling of easements can provide them with cash that could
allow some of them to stay in business.
</P>
<P>
	   To qualify, farms must be active, ongoing agricultural concerns situated on
scenic, well-tended properties. Ideally, the farms should also be adjacent to
other environmentally sensitive lands or to parcels on which easements have
previously been secured under the Farmland Protection Program.
</P>
<P>
	   New York is making "great strides" in preserving farmland through the
program, said Jerry Cosgrove of the American Farmland Trust.
</P>
<P>
	   "The result is that farmers can pass their farms on to their children and
reinvest in their communities' economic and environmental quality of life,"
Cosgrove said.
</P>
<P>
	   Cosgrove's group helps identify the most valuable and vulnerable pieces of
farmland and gives localities and farmers technical help in negotiating the
Farmland Protection Program.
</P>
<P>
	   This year's $12 million in state funding is comprised of $7.5 million from
the 1996 state environmental bond act and $4.5 million from the state's
Environmental Protection Fund.
</P>
<P>
	   The latest projects qualifying under the program, their location, the amount
of land involved and the cost to the state are:
</P>
<P>
	   -Macedon, Wayne County; more than 834 acres; $748,465.
</P>
<P>
	   -Montgomery, Orange County; about 481 acres; $1.3 million.
</P>
<P>
	   -Southampton, Suffolk County; 30.5 acres; $828,965.
</P>
<P>
	   -Southold, Riverhead, Brookhaven, Southampton and East Hampton, all in
Suffolk County; undetermined number out of 47 parcels encompassing 2,469 acres;
$2.5 million.
</P>
<P>
	   -Elbridge, Onondaga County; 567 acres; $865,000.
</P>
<P>
	   -Preble, Cortland County; 359 acres; $1.1 million.
</P>
<P>
	   -Marilla, Erie County; undetermined number out of 59 parcels encompassing
2,817 acres; $375,000.
</P>
<P>
	   -East Fishkill, Dutchess County; 164 acres; $890,000.
</P>
<P>
	   -Clintondale, Ulster County; 621 acres; $1.3 million.
</P>
<P>
	   -Southold, Suffolk County; undetermined number out of six farms encompassing
180 acres; $495,479.
</P>
<P>
	   -Riverhead, Suffolk County; undetermined number out of five farms
encompassing 217 acres; $490,000.
</P>
<P>
	   -White Creek, Washington County; 221.5 acres; $225,962.
</P>
<P>
	   -Westport, Essex County; 293 acres; $140,334.
</P>
<P>
	   -Warwick, Orange County; 92 acres; $350,000.
</P>
<P>
	   -Amherst, Erie County; 1,044 acres: $100,000.
</P>
