<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 17 former utility workers harmed by asbestos settle for $2 million  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) - Fourteen retired utility workers and the heirs of
three others stricken with asbestos-related diseases have accepted $2 million to
settle a lawsuit against a group of asbestos companies.
<P>
	   The men, ranging in age from 56 to 75, were exposed to asbestos insulation
products while working at Rochester Gas &AMP; Electric Corp. as far back as the late
1950s, their attorney, Dennis Herron, said Friday. Most of them retired in the
early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
	   Three of the men who sued for damages in 1997 have since died of lung, colon
and throat cancers. Their share of the award goes to their families. The
wrongful death and injury lawsuit had gotten to the first day of jury selection
Thursday before being settled.
</P>
<P>
	   As part of the settlement, the identities of the 21 defendants - asbestos
manufacturers, suppliers and distributors - were kept confidential. The utility
was not sued because New York employers are protected from claims under a
workers' compensation law.
</P>
<P>
	   The men were employed at a variety of power stations in the Rochester
region, including the Ginna nuclear plant on Lake Ontario's southern shore.
Power plants use great amounts of insulation for high-pressure steam pipes.
</P>
<P>
	   The federal government banned the use of asbestos at industrial work places
in 1972. Exposure to asbestos can result in illness anywhere from 10 to 40 years
later, Herron said.
</P>
<P>
	   "The interesting thing with a lot of these 17 guys is they didn't work
directly with these products," he said. "They were doing their job next to a guy
who was replacing asbestos pipe covering ... and were exposed as a bystander."
</P>
<P>
	   All of the men were eventually stricken with illnesses linked to asbestos
exposure, from various cancers and asbestosis, a scarring of the lungs, to
pleural plaques, a thickening of membranes lining the lungs. Effects range from
labored breathing to death.
</P>
<P>
	   It was at least the fourth asbestos lawsuit in Rochester since 1996 that
ended in a payout.
</P>
<P>
	   In January 1996, the family of a retired Kodak worker who had recently died
of mesothelioma - the only form of lung cancer directly linked to asbestos
exposure - was awarded $375,000 in a settlement with five asbestos manufacturers
and a distributor.
</P>
<P>
	   In August 1997, nine asbestos manufacturers and distributors paid more than
$500,000 to the widow of a former Eastman Kodak Co. worker who had died five
months earlier of mesothelioma.
</P>
<P>
	   Last June, 18 makers and suppliers of asbestos paid $1.25 million to a Kodak
worker and the families of four fellow employees who had died of
asbestos-related illnesses.
</P>
<P>
	   According to a 1982 study by the Mount Sinai School of Medicine in New York,
about 27.5 million American workers were exposed to asbestos from 1940 to 1980.
The study estimated that 365,000 people would die from asbestos-related diseases
by the year 2030.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-08-00 0011 </TRAILER>
