<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge: Are estate rights granted before birth?  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) - Two women who had children with a man who died in
an explosion are headed to court to keep another woman's unborn child from any
lawsuit settlement.
<P>
	   A judge will decide the complicated case in Erie County that tackles whether
a fetus has the right to share in the estate of a dead father.
</P>
<P>
	   That man, Keith Bosch, 31, died Dec. 27 from third-degree burns he suffered
in an electrical explosion in Erie County. An attorney said he seeks a civil
suit in the death which could result in a large award or settlement.
</P>
<P>
	   The expectant mother lived with Bosch for two years before his death. On
Thursday, her attorney, Robert Boreanaz, said he will offer court motions to
protect the rights of the fetus. The birth is expected in six months.
</P>
<P>
	   But John F. Maxwell, an attorney representing the mothers of two of Bosch's
other children, is expected to argue that the fetus does not gain rights to an
estate until birth.
</P>
<P>
	   Maxwell added that the father must be identified through DNA and blood
testing, which can only happen after birth.
</P>
<P>
	   Erie County Surrogate Judge Joseph S. Mattina said the decision may hinge on
Roe vs. Wade in which the Supreme Court ruled that "a fetus is not a person . .
. (and) does not have a legal personality or identity until it sees the light of
day."
</P>
<P>
	   If Mattina follows that ruling, the future well-being of the fetus could be
decided by the guardians and attorneys who represent Bosch's two other children.
</P>
<P>
	   Maxwell told Mattina that he would be seeking a "substantial claim ... for
the wrongful death" of Bosch.
</P>
<P>
	   The two mothers he is representing are asking the court to appoint Bosch's
father, Roger Bosch, as administrator of his son's estate and themselves as
co-administrators.
</P>
<P>
	   But Boreanaz countered that because the expectant mother had been living
with Bosch for two years prior to his death, she should be named guardian for
the fetus and co-administrator of the estate.
</P>
<P>
	   Tissue and blood samples from Bosch have been preserved for DNA tests.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-08-00 0011 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000108.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle ground found for dying woman  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) - Sheila Pouliot is near death, and her family wants
to make sure she doesn't suffer unnecessarily any more.
<P>
	   After a series of court hearings and the intervention of the state attorney
general's office, the severely mentally disabled Pouliot won't. Her family and
University Hospital officials settled their dispute on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   Their compromise will let the state provide nutrition while also honoring
the family's wish to avoid intrusive procedures to keep the 42-year-old Pouliot
alive.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's not expected to prolong her life," said Martha Mulroy, the lawyer
representing the Pouliot family. "We agreed to maintain her care and comfort and
make sure her pain management is going to be addressed."
</P>
<P>
	   Pouliot has been disabled since she was 9 months old. She's now unable to
move or communicate. Her family cared for her at home until she was 20. For the
past two decades, she resided at a developmental home. Shortly before Christmas,
a gastrointestinal tube that has been her lifeline began to cause internal
bleeding, and Pouliot was sent to University Hospital for medical help.
</P>
<P>
	   It was a move that left Pouliot in the middle of a court battle over her
family's wishes to let her die versus the hospital's attempt to continue
providing her nutrition.
</P>
<P>
	   The hospital's position is that providing nutrition is not the same as
providing medical treatment. The family contends that providing her nutrition
amounts to major medical treatment that will only prolong her suffering since
death is imminent.
</P>
<P>
	   Pouliot's family, as well as her doctors, clergy and a lawyer appointed to
represent Pouliot's interests, also contend that to provide her nutritional
needs would require medical intervention that could present serious risks.
</P>
<P>
	   To keep her alive, doctors wanted to establish another feeding line in her
leg. That could result in doctors breaking bones in Pouliot's body because of
the rigid position she's in and the brittleness of those bones, according to
court arguments.
</P>
<P>
	   Mulroy went to court Tuesday and obtained an order restraining the hospital
"from providing nutrition of any means or any other life-sustaining treatment"
unless approved in advance in writing by Pouliot's lawyer.
</P>
<P>
	   In court affidavits, Pouliot's doctors said using a femoral line in her leg
increased the possibility for "prolonged pain, infection, fractured bones and
thrombosis (blood clots). These efforts will not ... improve her state of health
or prolong her life."
</P>
<P>
	   While Assistant Attorney General Winthrop Thurlow agreed to the treatment
compromise, the state also filed a notice of appeal of state Supreme Court
Justice James Tormey's restraining order. Thurlow said that legal step in no way
alters the agreement over Pouliot's treatment.
</P>
<P>
	   Thurlow and hospital spokesman Daryl Geddes declined comment on why the
hospital took the action it had.
</P>
<P>
	   Mulroy said the family was satisfied that the focus had remained on Sheila.
</P>
<P>
	   "She's the one we really all do care about," Mulroy said.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's just a matter of maintaining her dignity through this terminal event.
That's what her family wants. They love her very much."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-08-00 0011 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
