<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 00:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Sunday School Teacher Sentenced  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- A former Sunday school teacher who authorities said bilked
church members, neighbors and others out of $5 million pleaded guilty Friday to
mail fraud.
</P>
<P>
	   Donald Eugene James, who supported a lavish lifestyle while posing as a
commodities trader, faces a maximum penalty of five years in prison and a
$200,000 fine at his sentencing in March.
</P>
<P>
	   James, 36, who taught a preschool Sunday school class at the Calvary
Assembly of God in suburban Dunwoody, promised returns of as much as 18 percent
a month on investments he made, according to federal court documents.
</P>
<P>
	   However, James invested less than $200,000, of which he lost about $120,000,
prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
	   Federal authorities said there were at least 25 victims in Georgia and
Florida who invested between $300,000 and $500,000 each in two commodity trading
pools that James established.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
