<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Molinari: McCain on NY primary ballots in 25 CD districts  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Sen. John McCain says he is hoping the federal
courts will put him on New York's Republican presidential primary ballot across
the state.
<P>
	   The head of the Arizona Republican's New York campaign said Friday that
supporters have qualified GOP primary delegate slates in 25 of the state's 31
congressional districts through the state's cumbersome petition process.
</P>
<P>
	   While that falls short of McCain's goal of getting on the ballot statewide
through petitions, it would allow him to give the GOP front-runner, Texas Gov.
George W. Bush, a contest in New York.
</P>
<P>
	   "I feel very pleased," Staten Island Borough President Guy Molinari, head of
McCain's New York effort, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain said that "to have gathered almost 30,000 signatures with very little
resources and without the help of the Republican establishment is simply
astonishing." He also said the fact that he could not get on the ballot
everywhere in the state through petitions, "underscores the unfairness of the
state's Byzantine Republican election laws."
</P>
<P>
	   McCain's all-volunteer New York team was working against a midnight Thursday
deadline for mailing petitions to various election boards across the state.
</P>
<P>
	   Molinari called the results a major accomplishment given the state's
notoriously difficult ballot access rules and the support for Bush from New York
Gov. George Pataki and state GOP Chairman William Powers.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush and millionaire publisher Steve Forbes filed petitions with the state
Board of Elections on Monday they said qualified them for the ballot across the
state. Bush, Forbes and McCain are the only candidates in the state's March 7
GOP primary.
</P>
<P>
	   Al Gore, Bill Bradley and Lyndon LaRouche have filed petitions they say
qualify them statewide for the March 7 Democratic primary.
</P>
<P>
	   The state Board of Elections, after considering challenges to any of the
petitions, plans to certify the Democratic and Republican primary ballots Jan.
31.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain has filed a federal lawsuit seeking to have his delegate slates
placed on the ballot throughout the state. Molinari said he expects that lawsuit
to be heard later this month.
</P>
<P>
	   Aides to Molinari said the congressional districts where McCain forces may
not have been able to collect sufficient signatures from party members to get
delegate slates on the primary ballot are in the lower Hudson Valley and across
upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
	   They identified the districts as the 18th (represented by Rep. Nita Lowey),
22nd (represented by Rep. John Sweeney), 24th (represented by Rep. John McHugh),
27th (represented by Rep. Thomas Reynolds) and 30th (represented by Rep. Jack
Quinn).
</P>
<P>
	   Molinari said it was uncertain if enough signatures had been collected by
the midnight deadline in the 26th Congressional District, which is represented
by Rep. Maurice Hinchey.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
