<HEADLINE> Clinton Plans $1B in Colombia Aid  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton plans to announce next week more than $1
billion in military and development assistance for Colombia, a package that
includes funds to fight the production and trafficking of illegal drugs, The
Washington Post reported.
</P>
<P>
	   The newspaper reported in its Saturday editions that the money, which will
also be used for programs to improve human rights performance, will be provided
over the next two years.
</P>
<P>
	   The White House will request a supplemental appropriation for this fiscal
year to cover more than half of the money, while the rest of the funds will be
part of the 2001 budget, the Post said, quoting unidentified administration
officials.
</P>
<P>
	   The Post said the basic framework of the administration's proposal has been
determined, but discussions are still under way among the Office of Management
and Budget and the State Department, the Pentagon and the Office of National
Drug Control Policy on how the money will be distributed.
</P>
<P>
	   The White House plans to brief congressional leaders on the proposal before
the announcement.
</P>
</TEXT>
