<HEADLINE> Ex-Interior Secretary Has Surgery  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) -- Former Interior Secretary Manuel Lujan Jr. was
recovering from surgery Friday following a heart attack.
</P>
<P>
	   Lujan, 71, had a heart attack Thursday night and was rushed to the Heart
Hospital of New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
	   ``They did a procedure on him this morning and he's doing quite well,'' said
Jean Lujan, his wife. She said doctors plan on releasing him early next week.
</P>
<P>
	   Lujan has suffered from cardiac problems for several years. He had his first
heart attack in 1983 and underwent a triple bypass. He and his brother, Edward,
spent time in the hospital in 1996 after suffering mild heart attacks just days
apart.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Since then it has flared up a little bit, but this was a little more
serious,'' Mrs. Lujan said. ``Thank God he's resting and came out of his
anesthesia.''
</P>
<P>
	   Lujan, a Republican, served 20 years in the U.S. House from New Mexico's 1st
Congressional District. He retired in 1988. President Bush appointed him
interior secretary in 1989, an office he held for four years.
</P>
<P>
	   After retiring, Lujan remarked in an interview that he did not realize how
much his political life had demanded of him.
</P>
<P>
	   However, he has remembered his Cabinet post fondly. He has a framed
photograph of President Bush's first Cabinet meeting and a wooden Interior
Department plaque in his office.
</P>
</TEXT>
