<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    Saturday, Jan. 8, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Anti-Castro Lawmaker Subpoenas Cuban Boy
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   MIAMI (AP) -- In efforts to prevent Elian Gonzalez's return to Cuba, an
anti-Castro lawmaker subpoenaed him Friday to testify before a congressional
committee and one of his Miami relatives sought to become his legal guardian.
Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., said he subpoenaed 6-year-old Elian to testify before
the Committee on Government Reform on Feb. 10, so he remains in the country
while the courts consider his case. In Cuba, Elian's father was angry about
Burton's subpoena. "What right does that man have?" Juan Miguel Gonzalez said
during a news conference in his hometown of Cardenas. "I am the father of Elian
and immigration has said that I am the only one who can speak for him."
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bush, McCain Clash at Debate
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WEST COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Sen. John McCain
clashed sharply over tax cuts in the second Republican campaign debate. McCain
said it was fiscally irresponsible to promise a huge tax cut that is based on a
surplus the U.S. might not have. Bush retorted that his plan was more generous
than McCain's for lower income taxpayers and added firmly: "There is enough
money to take care of Social Security. There is enough money to take care of the
basic services of government, and there is enough money to give the people a
substantial tax cut. And that's what I intend to do."
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S. Claims Mideast Talks Progress
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   SHEPHERDSTOWN, W.Va. (AP) -- In a move portrayed as evidence of progress,
President Clinton presented Israel and Syria a "working document" Friday that
could be a pathway to a land-for-peace treaty between the two old foes. In
another measured step forward, Clinton met with Prime Minister Ehud Barak of
Israel and Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa, first together, then
separately. It was the first face-to-face meeting between Barak and al-Sharaa
since Tuesday. "We are moving down the track," State Department spokesman James
P. Rubin said before formal talks drew to a close for the Jewish Sabbath and the
Muslim Eid al-Fitr, the end of the holy month of Ramadan.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Confederate Flag Supporters Rally
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- With a bell ringing for South Carolina's Confederate
War dead, Confederate flag supporters began a three-day rally Friday at the only
statehouse where the Confederate flag still flies from the dome. The Confederate
flag, with its field of red and star-studded blue cross, is seen as symbol of
hate by some opponents. But groups like those gathering at the rally see it as a
symbol of Southern heritage. South Carolina remains the only state that flies
the flag above its Statehouse, and the NAACP has called a tourism boycott of
South Carolina until the Legislature brings it down.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mexican Students Reject Offer
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Striking Mexican students rejected university officials'
offer Friday to meet some of their demands to end an eight-month strike that has
shut down the nation's largest public school. The strikers, who seized the
campus of the National Autonomous University of Mexico on April 20, said the
offer did not go far enough. The students said they are now demanding the
release of several students arrested after launching bottle rockets at the U.S.
Embassy during a December demonstration. While there are 268,000 students at the
university, the strikers represent a few thousand.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Soars to Record High
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Investors brushed off signs of inflationary pressure as the
Dow Jones industrials soared into record territory Friday. The Nasdaq composite,
which tumbled earlier this week, recorded its best day in history rising 155.45
to 3,882.58. The Dow rose 269.30 to close at 11,522.56, topping its Dec. 31
closing record. Fueled by consumer goods stocks, the rally wiped out the last
remnants of Tuesday's 359-point tumble.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Avalanche Defeat Canadiens 4-1
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   DENVER (AP) -- Milan Hejduk had his fourth two-goal game of the season as
the Colorado Avalanche completed a two-game season sweep of the Montreal
Canadiens with a 4-1 victory Friday night. Former Montreal goalie Patrick Roy
made 22 saves, and Chris Dingman and Adam Deadmarsh added goals to help Colorado
extend its unbeaten streak to a season-best five games (4-0-1). Peter Forsberg
had three assists to extend his points streak to seven games. He has a goal and
12 assists during the streak.
</P>
