<HEADLINE> Russia Shuffles Combat Commanders  </HEADLINE>
   By YURI BAGROV Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   GROZNY, Russia (AP) -- Russia has replaced its two top combat generals in
its campaign in Chechnya, a reshuffle that suggested government frustration with
the failure to take Grozny and strike a decisive blow against rebels.
</P>
<P>
	   The government insisted the changes were a routine staff rotation. The
reshuffle announced Friday came as Russian commanders indicated that a
scaling-back of the bombardment of the shattered capital had been ordered.
</P>
<P>
	   Russian ground forces began a major drive Dec. 25 to take Grozny, but have
made little progress in the face of fierce rebel resistance. Russian commanders
said last month that the city would be taken within days.
</P>
<P>
	   Rebel fighters in the city launched counterattacks this week and showed no
sign of giving up. Rebel commanders say they are ready to fight for years.
</P>
<P>
	   Russian forces, which swept over the northern plains of the breakaway
territory, are also facing touch fighting in the southern mountains, where the
rebels are entrenched in heavily fortified bases.
</P>
<P>
	   The Defense Ministry said Lt. Gen. Gennady Troshev was replaced as commander
of the Eastern front by his deputy, Maj. Gen. Sergei Makarov.
</P>
<P>
	   On the Western front, Maj. Gen. Vladimir Shamanov was sidelined in favor of
Maj. Gen. Alexei Verbitzky. Little was known about the new commanders.
</P>
<P>
	   The Defense Ministry insisted the rotations were normal practice, but the
moves will be seen as dismissals. Acting President Vladimir Putin, who took over
when Boris Yeltsin resigned Dec. 31, may want to wrap up the war before
presidential elections March 26.
</P>
<P>
	   The personnel changes were ``not the result of any professional error of the
commanders who are just returning to their former positions,'' according to a
military statement read on Russian state television networks.
</P>
<P>
	   NTV, a private television channel, said Shamanov's removal might be linked
to reports that Russian soldiers massacred about 40 Chechen civilians last month
in the village of Alkhan-Yurt.
</P>
<P>
	   Shamanov, who helped formulate the strategy to occupy Chechnya, returned to
his previous post as chief of the 58th Army.
</P>
<P>
	   The general became famous at the start of the campaign in September for his
hard-driving tactics. His soldiers adored Shamanov, who had a reputation of
leading from the front, unlike most other senior commanders.
</P>
<P>
	   Troshev, who will continue in his previous post as commander of the Northern
Caucasus military district, insisted at a press briefing Friday in the southern
Russian city of Mozdok that no errors had been made.
</P>
<P>
	   He also said that Russian forces were scaling back their operations in
Grozny, but indicated that fighting was not being called off altogether.
</P>
<P>
	   In a series of confusing remarks broadcast on Russian TV channels, Troshev
said Russian forces would ``suspend military activities in all directions''
because of the threat posed to civilians in Grozny.
</P>
<P>
	   But he also said combat operations would continue in areas of the city where
there were no civilians.
</P>
<P>
	   ``To halt does not mean we won't continue, we are conducting the military
activities around the clock in the areas where there are no civilians,'' he said
in the TV broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
	   The news agency ITAR-Tass reported from Mozdok that Troshev's comments
referred to air and artillery bombardment of the capital. A spokesman for the
Defense Ministry in Moscow said he was not sure what Troshev meant.
</P>
<P>
	   There were no details about how long any pause might last.
</P>
<P>
	   Russian artillery and aircraft have been battering Grozny since September
despite the presence of up to 40,000 civilians hiding in basements in the city.
Russia has announced cease-fires in the past to allow civilians to leave, but
did not halt all combat operations during those lulls.
</P>
<P>
	   In spite of fog and snow, federal planes and helicopter gunships flew 43
combat missions over the past 24 hours, the military said Friday. It claimed to
have killed more than 30 rebels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
