<HEADLINE> Cleveland Orchestra Debuts Hall  </HEADLINE>
   By JOHN AFFLECK Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CLEVELAND (AP) -- The most passionate fans in Cleveland this weekend won't
be football crazies but classical music enthusiasts.
</P>
<P>
	   On Saturday night, the world-class Cleveland Orchestra plays for the first
time in its refurbished home, Severance Hall, following a $36.7 million
renovation.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I can't tell you how much I'm looking forward to it,'' said Jodith Janes,
a season ticket-holder for about 30 years. ``I expect most of the city of
Cleveland is just as eagerly awaiting.''
</P>
<P>
	   Much has changed since work began two years ago on Severance, which is
regarded as one of America's finest concert halls and is on the National
Register of Historic Places.
</P>
<P>
	   An ugly, modernist concert shell has been discarded for an ornate one that
blends seamlessly with the lotus flower decorations throughout the hall. An
organ made unusable by a previous renovation is being reinstalled.
</P>
<P>
	   A new extension to the building has opened up a cramped backstage. All of
the seats in the 2,000-seat hall have been replaced. A full-service restaurant
has been added. So have more women's restrooms, which were almost nonexistent in
the original, 1931 version of Severance.
</P>
<P>
	   The main idea is to give patrons the kind of amenities they have come to
expect from other entertainment venues, from movie theaters to sports arenas
like the newly opened Cleveland Browns Stadium.
</P>
<P>
	   For all that is new, orchestra executives have preserved the look of the old
Severance, right down to matching one-of-a-kind Art Deco light fixtures and rare
Spanish marble in a corridor. And the orchestra has only tinkered with the
Severance's greatest asset: its acoustics.
</P>
<P>
	   Since a renovation in 1958 under the late George Szell, the musical director
who guided the orchestra to international prominence, Severance has had a
distinctive, enveloping sound.
</P>
<P>
	   Judging from a rehearsal for Saturday night's opening concert, which is
being televised locally and sold out despite $300 ticket prices, the Cleveland
Orchestra's fans won't be disappointed.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We're delighted,'' said concertmaster William Preucil. ``The sound's got a
bloom and richness and clarity to it. It's like going home again.''
</P>
<P>
	   During the renovations, the orchestra had to play at a downtown theater.
</P>
<P>
	   In perhaps the most concrete sign of Cleveland's devotion to the group,
orchestra patrons paid for about $25 million of the renovations. The rest came
from a state grant.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-08-00 0109 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000108.0034 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 01:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Buddhist's Exile Spotlights Problem  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The dramatic escape into exile of Tibet's last primary
Buddhist leader was the second incident in two days to show the Chinese
government's persistent problems with organized religion.
</P>
<P>
	   The 14-year-old Karmapa, leader of one of Tibetan Buddhism's four sects,
arrived Wednesday at Dharmsala, India, to meet the Dalai Lama, Tibet's political
ruler in exile.
</P>
<P>
	   On Thursday, Catholics aligned with China's communist regime ordained five
new bishops not recognized by Rome on the very day that Pope John Paul II was
conducting his annual elevation of new bishops from around the world. That
timing was interpreted as a snub that dooms, at least for now, Vatican efforts
to normalize the church situation.
</P>
<P>
	   The Chinese regime has also detained thousands of Falun Gong followers since
outlawing the spiritual movement five months ago.
</P>
<P>
	   The harrowing flight of the Karmapa across the Himalayas ``reveals the
shambles of China's policy of trying to manage religion,'' says Robert Thurman,
Columbia University professor and friend of the Dalai Lama. ``Their suppression
is not working, and their attempt to pretend to get along with Buddhism doesn't
work, either.''
</P>
<P>
	   John Ackerly, president of the International Campaign for Tibet in
Washington, said the Beijing regime tried to use the Karmapa ``to showcase their
religious freedom policies. It will make it much more embarrassing that he's
been so highly covered by the official media.''
</P>
<P>
	   Thurman said it was essential for the Karmapa to leave so he could receive a
thorough Buddhist education and pass on his tradition, which he said was not
possible under Chinese control.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Some distinguished teachers still remain behind, but among the leaders of
the major forms of Tibetan Buddhism, all have now felt it necessary to escape in
order to practice their religion,'' said Donald Lopez, professor of Tibetan
studies at the University of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
	   The only major Buddhist figure who remains in Tibet, said Lopez, is the
Panchen Lama designated by the Chinese government. But he ``has absolutely no
status with the Tibetan people'' because the Dalai Lama has recognized a
different youth whose whereabouts are now unknown.
</P>
<P>
	   China and the Vatican have had no formal relations since 1951, when the
Communist Party kicked out missionaries and forced Catholics to sever ties with
the Vatican.
</P>
<P>
	   The Chinese government refuses to accept the pope's authority to appoint and
consecrate bishops worldwide, and has authorized an official Catholic Church.
</P>
<P>
	   By the official church's count, there are 5 million Catholics in China, with
60,000 new members each year. Catholic experts in Hong Kong put the figure at 10
million to 12 million. Many church members, including priests, move between the
official church and an underground church that is loyal to the pope.
</P>
<P>
	   Overseas monitoring groups say persecution of underground Catholics persists
in some areas of China, with the detentions of priests and worshippers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-08-00 0110 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000108.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 01:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trucks Dominate Detroit Auto Show  </HEADLINE>
    By JUSTIN HYDE AP Auto Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DETROIT (AP) -- If there's one message that will be heard loud and clear at
this year's triumphant Detroit auto show, it's this: The car of the future is a
truck.
</P>
<P>
	   From hulking four-door pickups to micro-sport utility vehicles and station
wagons on steroids, trucks will dominate the 2000 North American International
Auto Show just as they dominated the sales charts in 1999.
</P>
<P>
	   Yet industry watchers point to some warning lights for the industry. Among
them: growing competition and rising fuel prices.
</P>
<P>
	   All of the large American manufacturers, along with several Asian and
European automakers, will show off new production models and concept vehicles at
the show, which begins with media previews Sunday and opens to the public Jan.
15. The emphasis on trucks is so strong that the hometown gang -- General Motors
Corp., Ford Motor Co. and the Chrysler division of DaimlerChrysler AG -- have no
major passenger car introductions scheduled.
</P>
<P>
	   The companies can say they are just giving consumers what they want. SUVs
were the fastest-growing segment in 1999, up 15 percent over the previous year,
according to Morgan &AMP; Co. in West Olive, Mich. Trucks accounted for 58 percent
of the 11.6 million vehicles sold by GM, Ford and Chrysler in 1999 -- and
probably a much larger percentage of their vehicle profits.
</P>
<P>
	   Jim O'Connor, Ford division president, noted that more than 40 new SUV
models have been introduced since 1991 and that at least 10 more are due out in
the next two to three years.
</P>
<P>
	   "Everyone wants a piece of this action," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Why the boom in trucks? One reason is that the strong economy and the
booming stock market are enabling people to buy extra vehicles and more
expensive ones.
</P>
<P>
	   Ken Cherven, an analyst with the Polk Co., found that trucks and SUVs were
often the second vehicle in a family, and that 61.5 percent of U.S. households
owned more than one vehicle in 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   Another reason is the increase in households with children. Analyst Michael
Ward with Salomon SmithBarney found that increases in SUV sales in the 1990s ran
parallel to the boom in children under 14.
</P>
<P>
	   For the Detroit auto show, considered the most important event of its kind
in North America, automakers have prepared several new truck and SUV models.
</P>
<P>
	   GM has already shown its Pontiac Aztek SUV and Chevrolet Avalanche truck-SUV
combo; it will also have further details about its deal with AM General, the
maker of the monster Hummer SUV. Chrysler will unveil new versions of its
minivans. Ford will display a new mini-SUV, its entry against models already on
the market from Honda and Toyota.
</P>
<P>
	   Toyota and Honda will show off new SUVs heading for production, while Audi,
Subaru and even Volkswagen will show off SUV and pickup concept vehicles.
</P>
<P>
	   While experts say total U.S. vehicle sales in 2000 could decline slightly
from a record 16.9 million in 1999, it could also be the year that automakers
sell more trucks than cars in the United States. They came close in 1999, with
trucks accounted for 48.5 percent of sales.
</P>
<P>
	   But with all the new models entering the market, automakers may have to
reduce the profit margins to stay competitive.
</P>
<P>
	   "If history is any indication, companies won't let vehicles sit on their
lots, and price will be the competing mechanism," Cherven said. "There's
certainly some potential benefit to consumers if some of those segments become
overly competitive."
</P>
<P>
	   Rising gasoline prices also could be a threat to truck and SUV sales. Art
Spinella, an industry sales analyst with CNW Marketing Research in Bandon, Ore.,
said GM, Ford and Chrysler could feel a crunch if customers switch back to more
fuel-efficient cars.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's short-sighted, because effectively what they're doing is giving up the
car market," he said. "They're releasing the car market to the Japanese and
Europeans."
</P>
<P>
	   But many of the newer SUVs are designed to deliver better fuel economy. And
Ward predicted that with the strong economy and stable demographics, truck and
SUV sales will remain strong in 2000.
</P>
<P>
	   "Fuel prices certainly are a risk to the SUV market, but we believe that
increasing gas prices would only shift the mix toward minivans -- kids don't
disappear in a recession or when fuel costs are higher," Ward said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-08-00 0110 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000108.0036 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 01:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Claims Mideast Talks Progress  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHEPHERDSTOWN, W.Va. (AP) -- With Mideast peace talks on a break, Israeli and
Palestinian delegates are looking over a U.S. ``working document'' given them by
President Clinton as a possible pathway to a land-for-peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
	   Negotiations were due to resume tonight at the end of the Jewish Sabbath and
continue on Sunday. State Department spokesman James P. Rubin said the round of
talks could wind down early next week.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We are moving down the track,'' Rubin said before formal talks drew to a
close for the Sabbath and the Muslim Eid al-Fitr, the end of the holy month of
Ramadan.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is difficult stuff. This is very hard stuff,'' Clinton said Friday on
his fourth day of mediating between Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel
and Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa on details of a settlement. The
deal would be based on the proposition that Israel should give up the Golan
Heights to gain Syria's diplomatic recognition.
</P>
<P>
	   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said the president gave the U.S.-drafted
document, about seven pages long, to the two sides during a 45-minute, three-way
working meeting.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This working document provides a summary of the issues to be decided and
the differences between the parties,'' Lockhart said. ``It is designed as a
procedural tool to focus the substantive discussions and to help bridge the
differences that now exist.''
</P>
<P>
	   Negotiations in this college town 70 miles northwest of Washington had
stalled over procedural issues.
</P>
<P>
	   Israel insisted that committees on peace terms and border security meet
first, and they did. But Rubin said panels on the timetable of an Israeli
withdrawal on the Golan Heights and on water resources would meet before the
round ends.
</P>
<P>
	   After returning to the White House, Clinton made a series of phone calls to
other world leaders to ``update them on the status of the peace talks in
Shepherdstown and give them a status report, from his perspective, on what
transpired today,'' said national security spokesman David Leavy.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton spoke with French President Jacques Chirac for about 10 minutes,
Leavy said. He then spoke with German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder for 20
minutes and with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat for 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
	   The document, which Secretary of State Madeleine Albright had directed her
aides to prepare, details both the agreements and disagreements during
negotiations here, in Washington last month and before a breakdown four years
ago.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's certainly progress to have a document before the parties,'' Rubin
said.
</P>
<P>
	   But he added, ``We have limited expectations (of) what can be completed with
one round.''
</P>
<P>
	   Albright planned to join al-Sharaa and the rest of the Syrian delegation at
a luncheon today marking the end of Ramadan after attending the Israelis'
traditional dinner Friday evening marking the start of the Jewish Sabbath.
</P>
<P>
	   The Israeli deletation also planned Sabbath services using a Torah borrowed
from a synagogue in Silver Spring, Md.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-08-00 0110 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000108.0037 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 01:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Says No to Hot Cocoa in Court  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAYETTEVILLE, Ark. (AP) -- Steaming cocoa is too hot for federal court.
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. District Judge Jimm Hendren refused on Thursday to allow jurors to
handle cups of hot cocoa as evidence in a lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
	   The lawyer for Ron Austin, who has filed a $1 million lawsuit over spilled
hot chocolate, wanted to perform an in-court demonstration during which jurors
in the lawsuit would be given a cup of 150-degree cocoa.
</P>
<P>
	   Attorney Charles Fuqua said the demonstration was necessary to show the
temperature of the beverage that burned Austin's foot last year when he spilled
a cup in his van while pulling away from a restaurant's drive-through window.
</P>
<P>
	   Austin, who suffered second-degree burns, claimed the van's transmission was
destroyed when he was unable to use the brake and had to throw the vehicle into
reverse to keep from colliding with oncoming traffic.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The proposed demonstration is nothing more than a Perry Mason tactic that
has no place in the courtroom,'' argued Roger A. Glasgow, the restaurant's
lawyer.
</P>
<P>
	   He said Fuqua's ``proposed experiment would not even accomplish its stated
purpose unless he proposes pouring the hot chocolate on the jurors or asking
them to insert their fingers into the hot beverage.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-08-00 0111 </TRAILER>
