<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 01:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Soccer Team Visits U.S.  </HEADLINE>
    By ROB GLOSTER AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Sprinting and passing, dodging and diving, the
Iranian soccer players scrimmaged on the field. Nearby, a huge red billboard
extolled "Bud, King of Beers" -- a potent symbol of the American lifestyle
condemned by Iran's ayatollahs.
</P>
<P>
	   Farshid Asad held a simpler sign, a handmade cardboard placard proclaiming
"Welcome to U.S.A." and featuring green and white Iranian flags. For Asad, the
visit of his nation's team was a reason for optimism.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's the first step, I hope," said Asad, a native of Tehran who now owns a
sandwich shop in San Francisco's suburbs. "It's time to forget the past."
</P>
<P>
	   Next weekend, Iran's soccer team will play the nation its leaders have
branded the "Great Satan." It will be the first time the two teams have met on
U.S. soil since relations between their countries turned hateful over the
1979-81 hostage crisis.
</P>
<P>
	   The game follows an exchange of wrestling teams in 1998 and highlights what
appears to be a partial thaw in relations.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is the latest step in the process of the United States and Iran coming
back together," said John Marks, president of Washington-based Search for Common
Ground, a private group promoting international understanding.
</P>
<P>
	   "The two countries are feeling each other out in a slow way. There are
substantial differences that won't be settled on the soccer field or the
wrestling mat, but these build confidence and make possible other exchanges."
</P>
<P>
	   Iran plays Mexico on Sunday at the Oakland Coliseum, then meets Ecuador on
Wednesday at the Coliseum in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
	   On Jan. 16, the Iranian team plays the United States at the Rose Bowl in
Pasadena -- a rematch of the 1998 World Cup game in which Iran defeated the
Americans 2-1 in France.
</P>
<P>
	   Iran's captain, Javad Zarrincheh, at 32 is one of the few members of his
team old enough to remember the hostage crisis, when Washington severed
diplomatic ties with Iran after militants seized the U.S. Embassy in Tehran in
1979 and held 52 Americans for 444 days.
</P>
<P>
	   "I am very happy that, after 21 years, soccer has given me a chance to be
here," Zarrincheh said through a translator. "I am happy sport will be a bond
that will bring people of the world together."
</P>
<P>
	   Although relations remain tense between the countries, things have improved
since the 1997 election of reformist President Mohammad Khatami and his appeal
for "a crack in the wall of mistrust."
</P>
<P>
	   That led to a group of American wrestlers attending a tournament in Iran in
1998, and an Iranian wrestling team visiting the United States. There have been
exchanges of environmentalists, and an American astronaut went to Iran to watch
an eclipse.
</P>
<P>
	   About 300 Iranians and Iranian-Americans greeted the visiting team at the
Oakland Airport late Wednesday. A few dozen fans were on hand during practice
Thursday, expressing hope the team's visit will work like the ping-pong
diplomacy of the early 1970s, when sports exchanges helped warm U.S. relations
with China.
</P>
<P>
	   "The goal is soccer. We are happy to play against three strong teams," said
Iranian coach Mansour Pourhaidari. "It is also true that sports brings people
together, and I am happy when this gap narrows."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-08-00 0113 </TRAILER>
