<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 01:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fed Surpluses Could Grow Larger  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- White House and congressional budget analysts are ready to
project federal surpluses for the coming decade that may be $800 billion bigger
than last year's $3 trillion estimate, officials of both parties say.
</P>
<P>
	   Thanks to huge piles of unanticipated federal revenue the red-hot economy is
producing, analysts say coming official projections will at least equal the
earlier $3 trillion estimate. Even that would be impressive, considering last
year's spending binge by lawmakers that ate well into the surpluses.
</P>
<P>
	   But depending on what assumptions are made about spending, the new estimates
-- one by the Congressional Budget Office, the other by the White House Office
of Management and Budget -- could surpass last year's by perhaps $800 billion,
said Democratic and Republican legislative aides who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
	   Either way, the stage is set for an election-year showdown over whether the
huge kitty should be used for tax cuts, spending or debt reduction.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The projections are likely going to show there is some real money in our
fiscal future, about which the presidential candidates can have a legitimate
debate,'' said Robert Reischauer, a former CBO director who is now a senior
fellow at the liberal-leaning Brookings Institution.
</P>
<P>
	   CBO and White House officials declined to discuss their numbers. CBO will
release its new projections later this month and the White House on Feb. 7, when
President Clinton presents his budget for fiscal 2001.
</P>
<P>
	   The new estimates will cover the fiscal years 2001 through 2010. Last year's
projections were for the 10 years beginning with 2000, which runs through next
Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
	   For the short run, analysts say the estimates will show a budget surplus,
excluding Social Security, of perhaps $10 billion to $20 billion for this year,
and perhaps up to $60 billion for fiscal 2001.
</P>
<P>
	   Those numbers are important because they would let Republicans claim they
honored last year's promise not to use Social Security money to pay for other
programs. That pledge -- which President Clinton also embraced -- seemed in
jeopardy when lawmakers approved tens of billions in extra spending, threatening
to eat into Social Security's surpluses.
</P>
<P>
	   ``A surging economy is bailing out Bill Clinton and the Republican Congress,
... outpacing even Congress' and Clinton's spending inclinations,'' said Stephen
Moore, fiscal policy director for the libertarian Cato Institute.
</P>
<P>
	   The figures also mean there would be plenty of resources for the tax cuts
Republicans want and the extra spending Democrats prefer for fiscal 2001.
Congress will begin working on tax and spending legislation for 2001 when it
returns to work Jan. 24.
</P>
<P>
	   With both parties trying to create distinctions between themselves that
voters will remember on Election Day, bipartisan agreement on major tax or
spending issues seems unlikely.
</P>
<P>
	   Nonetheless, the projected surpluses should be so big that some of the money
could be used for tax cuts or new spending for Medicare, defense and other
programs and leave huge sums that can be apportioned later. In the meantime, any
unused surplus money automatically would reduce the $5.8 trillion national debt.
</P>
<P>
	   Of the $3 trillion surplus projected last year, $2 trillion was to come from
Social Security. Both parties consider that money politically untouchable for
spending for other programs.
</P>
<P>
	   The remaining $1 trillion in black ink was to come from the rest of the
federal budget.
</P>
<P>
	   The size of the projected surplus is growing chiefly because, for yet
another year, the unexpectedly strong economy is producing more federal revenue
than anticipated. In addition, spending for programs, including Medicare, has
been less than expected.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-08-00 0114 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000108.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 01:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Energy Department Files Nuclear Plan  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Some lawmakers say they're concerned that an Energy
Department reorganization plan that creates a new nuclear weapons agency does
not go far enough to insulate the agency from the rest of the department's
bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
	   Energy Secretary Bill Richardson sent the plan to Congress on Friday and
pledged to complete the reorganization by March.
</P>
<P>
	   In response to alleged Chinese espionage and lax security at nuclear weapons
labs, Congress last year directed that all nuclear weapons programs at DOE be
consolidated under a semiautonomous National Nuclear Security Administration.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We are committed to implementing the (new agency) and ensuring that the
national security mission of the department is met,'' Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
	   But two House members said the planned reorganization contradicts the law's
demand for semiautonomy for the new agency because it has a number of senior
officials serving dual roles within the agency and in the parent department.
</P>
<P>
	   Rep. Mac Thornberry, R-Texas, a leading sponsor of the legislation creating
the new agency, accused Richardson of ``attempting to shoehorn'' the DOE
bureaucracy into the new agency.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The department is clearly resisting one of the most fundamental elements
of the reform plan'' to establish a nuclear weapons program ``distinct and
separate from the Energy Department,'' Thornberry said.
</P>
<P>
	   Rep. Ellen Tauscher, D-Calif., whose district includes the Lawrence
Livermore National Laboratory, also said the reorganization ``contradicts the
law by giving some employees dual responsibilities in the (agency) and the
department.''
</P>
<P>
	   Richardson's planned reorganization requires that agency positions
responsible for security, counterintelligence, legal affairs and environmental
and health protection be held by officials who have those same responsibilities
within the overall department.
</P>
<P>
	   Critics of the reorganization law, including Richardson, are concerned that
the agency would become a powerful fiefdom unaccountable to the rest of the
department. Richardson also has criticized the idea of having separate security
and counterintelligence officials within the agency and DOE.
</P>
<P>
	   Sen. Jeff Bingaman, D-N.M., a Richardson ally, said the reorganization eases
those concerns and still ``complies with the letter and spirit of the law''
creating the agency. He said it also ``protects public health and safety and
protects the important national programs and resources of the (weapons)
laboratories.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bingaman and others also had been concerned that civilian research at the
Los Alamos and Sandia labs in New Mexico, as well as at Lawrence Livermore,
might be jeopardized once the facilities were absorbed within the new agency.
But the reorganization stipulates that the labs be allowed to continue to
perform scientific research for non-defense programs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-08-00 0115 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000108.0043 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 01:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Republicans Debate Again  </HEADLINE>
   By GLEN JOHNSON Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WEST COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- The latest in a series of Republican
presidential debates had a distinctly Southern flavor, with the candidates
haggling over the Confederate battle flag, the value of state lotteries and the
propriety of gays in the military.
</P>
<P>
	   At times, the audience of 3,000 appeared to view Friday's event more as an
athletic contest than a political debate. It gathered in a former warehouse for
chicken and pecan pie at the state GOP's annual ``Silver Elephant Banquet.''
</P>
<P>
	   Boos erupted early, in response to a question posed to the front-runner,
Texas Gov. George W. Bush, about the Confederate flag. It flies atop the nearby
Statehouse, even though some in South Carolina -- especially blacks -- consider
it a racist symbol.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I believe the people of South Carolina can figure out what to do with this
flag issue,'' Bush replied to a chorus of cheers.
</P>
<P>
	   When moderator Brian Williams of MSNBC sought to pursue the issue, the crowd
booed louder, and Bush merely repeated that he thought it was an issue for South
Carolinians to decide.
</P>
<P>
	   Sen. John McCain of Arizona also said it was an issue for the state's
residents to decide.
</P>
<P>
	   South Carolina, which holds its primary Feb. 19, is critical to McCain's
election strategy. He decided to skip the Iowa caucuses on Jan. 24 so he could
focus on the Feb. 1 New Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
	   The senator hopes a victory there can be followed with a strong showing
here, a state with a large military presence that should be hospitable to the
former Vietnam prisoner of war.
</P>
<P>
	   With those stakes, McCain again defended the letters he has written to
federal agencies on behalf of campaign donors. The issue also came up in the
group's debate on Thursday in New Hampshire, and was likely to resurface on
Monday when the candidates reassemble in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
	   Also participating in the debates are conservative activist Gary Bauer,
publisher Steve Forbes, Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah and radio talk show host Alan
Keyes.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Whenever a constituent of mine or a citizen ... can't get an answer ... I
believe that people like me should weigh in,'' said McCain, who wrote the
letters in his capacity as chairman of the Senate Commerce Committee.
</P>
<P>
	   The senator was addressing a question about an Associated Press story
detailing a letter he wrote last year on behalf of Ameritech, which was seeking
permission to merge with another telephone company, SBC.
</P>
<P>
	   The letter-writing issue is a troubling one for McCain, whose candidacy has
flourished on the basis of his call for a ridding the nation's political system
of the influence of big-monied special interests.
</P>
<P>
	   Appearing in a state with substantial military facilities and numerous
military retirees, the GOP contenders also sharply criticized Democratic
presidential candidates for saying they would only appoint to the Joint Chiefs
of Staff officers who would permit gays to serve openly in the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
	   Keyes led the attack, saying he would renew a ban on gays in the military
that was in effect until Bill Clinton won the White House. He challenged McCain
to join him, but the senator refused. He said he would stick with the current
``don't ask, don't tell'' policy.
</P>
<P>
	   They attacked as Vice President Al Gore was backpedaling on comments he had
made earlier in the week, declaring he had not meant ``to imply that there
should ever be any kind of inquiry into the personal political opinions of
officers in the U.S. military.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bush was asked about the Panama Canal by Bauer, who said he opposed the
recent turnover of the waterway to Panama under a treaty ratified by the Senate
in 1977.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush noted that as a young congressional candidate at the time, he had
opposed the treaty. If elected president, he said he will uphold the treaty, but
added that he would do ``whatever it takes to keep the canal open. ... I'll
liberate the canal if I have to'' to maintain Americans' trade and other
strategic interests.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush's father, former President George Bush, dispatched troops to Panama
while in the White House.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain jabbed Bush over taxes as part of a running disagreement between the
two men, and Bush returned fire on the subject of campaign finance.
</P>
<P>
	   He said, as he had in New Hampshire on Thursday night, that McCain's
proposal would hurt Republicans. Hatch said with his insistence on campaign
finance overhaul, McCain was beginning to remind him of ``an accordion player
who only knows one tune.''
</P>
<P>
	   McCain stood his ground and said it was essential to rid the country of the
influence of special interests.
</P>
<P>
	   Several of the contenders tackled another volatile South Carolina issue, a
proposed state-run lottery.
</P>
<P>
	   Bauer said he was opposed, adding, ``the gambling industry is corrupting our
culture.''
</P>
<P>
	   Forbes harkened back to the lessons learned in his home state of New Jersey,
saying that intending to use a lottery to fund education improvements -- as
proposed in South Carolina -- is ``a false deal.''
</P>
<P>
	   Keyes was emphatic. ``If you solicit my advice I'll tell you this: All
governments everywhere -- federal, state, local -- should get out of the
business of putting a corrupting, regressive tax on the backs of their people,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-08-00 0115 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000108.0044 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 01:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Debate Highlights  </HEADLINE>
   By The Associated Press
<TEXT>
<P>
	   Highlights of Friday's debate between Republican presidential hopefuls Gary
Bauer, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah, Alan Keyes, Steve
Forbes and Sen. John McCain of Arizona, as transcribed by the Federal Document
Clearing House:
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   Asked if affirmative action has made America a better nation:
</P>
<P>
	   MCCAIN: Yes, but quotas have made it worse.
</P>
<P>
	   BAUER: I think that the idea behind affirmative action was legitimate and
decent, but when you start counting by race, you divide America, you don't bring
it together.
</P>
<P>
	   BUSH: Only if affirmative action means equal opportunity for everybody.
</P>
<P>
	   FORBES: Quotas and set asides are wrong, and that's why we genuinely need
real affirmation of opportunities starting by letting parents choose their own
schools for their own children.
</P>
<P>
	   HATCH: When affirmative action means job training outreach and education
it's good. When it starts pitting one group against another throw a system of
preferences, it's bad. And I've got to tell you quotas are wrong for America,
and I agree: Equal opportunity is what we should have for everybody.
</P>
<P>
	   KEYES: I think it maybe more important to ask whether it's helped the people
it was supposed to help. And I think it has actually hurt them by damaging the
reputation of many minorities in this country and not giving them credit for
their real achievements, and I think that's wrong.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   Bush was asked by Bauer about the recent turnover of the Panama Canal back
to Panamanian control:
</P>
<P>
	   BAUER: Are you willing to take the steps necessary including putting our
military back in Panama in order to stop the Chinese from taking over influence
there?
</P>
<P>
	   BUSH: Our country has signed a treaty; I believe we ought to honor the
treaty. But when I'm the president, if I find in any way, shape or form the
canal is closed to world interests, I will do whatever it takes to keep the
canal open.
</P>
<P>
	   It is in our national strategic interest to have a peaceful hemisphere. It
is in our national strategic interest to have a hemisphere in which trade can
flow freely. And I will liberate the canal if I have to.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   McCain was asked, for the second night in a row, about his role overseeing
the FCC, which makes important decisions regarding some of his key campaign
donors.
</P>
<P>
	   Q: Senator, I'm reading from the Associated Press ... ``two weeks after
Ameritech's chairman held a fund-raiser for him, Senator John McCain sent a
stinging letter to federal regulators accusing them of being unfair toward the
phone company.''
</P>
<P>
	   Senator, your letter went on to say that the letter was not meant to benefit
any one single person.
</P>
<P>
	   And you have said in your own defense that this is part of what is wrong
with Washington. However, do you understand now the appearance here and can you
tell us here tonight is there anything else about the transportation you use,
about the letters you have written, anything else that you know of that is about
to come out?
</P>
<P>
	   MCCAIN: I have, first of all, no idea. But the fact is that again my job as
chairman of the Committee on Commerce, Science and Transportation is the
oversight of bureaucracies that are supposed to be serving the people. The
Federal Communications Commission has not been doing that. But all the times
when I have weighed in I have asked them to do their duty and to expedite the
procedures as they're laid out under the law and according to existing
regulations.
</P>
<P>
	   I will continue to do that job, and when a constituent, a person of mine who
has trouble -- or a citizen of this country who can't get a reaction or an
answer from a bureaucracy that's paid for with their tax dollars -- I believe
that people like me should weigh in, particularly when it is my responsibility
as chairman of the committee.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   McCain was given the chance to ask Gov. Bush about the differences between
their two proposed tax cut plans.
</P>
<P>
	   MCCAIN: Well, governor, I know your people are running around saying that
your tax cut is bigger than mine. I think the phrase they used was the tax gap
between Bush and McCain. I'm more concerned about the surplus gap. It's fiscally
irresponsible to promise a huge tax cut that is based on a surplus that we may
not have. My tax plan is fiscally conservative. It's about the same as yours for
middle-income and lower income Americans. It places a top priority on saving
Social Security. It offers a needed tax break for middle income people and it
begins paying down the national debt. My friends, we ought to pay down the
national debt. George, the American people are tired of people who make
promises, who make promises about tax cuts that they can't keep.
</P>
<P>
	   BUSH: The senator and I have a fundamental disagreement. Let me see if I can
put it in human terms for you.
</P>
<P>
	   Chris and Beth Bradley came to the airport today. They make $42,000 a year
in income. Under the plan that you laid out, Mr. Senator, here in South
Carolina, they will receive a $200 tax cut. Under the plan that I propose and
will get through the United States Congress, they receive a $1,852 tax cut. The
fundamental difference is that the additional $1,600 -- the difference will go
to Washington under your idea, and under my idea it goes into people's pockets.
There is enough money to take care of Social Security. There is enough money to
meet the basic needs of our government. And there is enough money to give the
American people a substantial tax cut and that's exactly what I'm going to do.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
