<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 01:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York a magnet for out-of-staters with high political hopes  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   WASHINGTON (AP) - New York has long been a lure for immigrants. It is
also still a magnet for out-of-staters who have their eye on elected office.
<P>
	   On the same day that Hillary Rodham Clinton moved into her new Westchester
County home to set down New York roots to run for the U.S. Senate, former
Massachusetts Gov. William Weld unpacked his bags in Manhattan with thoughts of
a possible run for the New York statehouse in 2006.
</P>
<P>
	   Now there's talk that Sen. Bob Kerrey, often mentioned as a Democratic
presidential contender, might accept a job as head of Manhattan's New School
University. That means that if the Nebraska Democrat and former Navy SEAL did
someday mount another run for the White House it could be from the Empire State.
</P>
<P>
	   What's going on?
</P>
<P>
	   "We always lay out the welcome mat in New York. The more the merrier," said
Maurice Carroll, a pollster with Quinnipiac College Polling Institute, which
does some carpetbagging of its own. Despite being based in Hamden, Conn., many
of its polls are on the hot political races in neighboring New York.
</P>
<P>
	   New York does, after all, have a rich heritage of electing outsiders.
</P>
<P>
	   The most noteworthy example is Robert F. Kennedy. Despite the Kennedy name
being virtually synonymous with Massachusetts, he ran for and won a Senate seat
in New York in 1964.
</P>
<P>
	   "New York has a reputation as enough of a cosmopolitan place that you don't
have to have spend your whole life here to develop the political credentials to
win office," said Michael Knox Beran, who wrote "The Last Patrician: Bobby
Kennedy and the End of American Aristocracy."
</P>
<P>
	   More proof was that after Kennedy, James Buckley, of Connecticut,
represented New York in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
	   One of New York's first senators, Rufus King, hailed from Massachusetts and
Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, the man Mrs. Clinton wants to replace, grew up in
New York City's Hell's Kitchen but also spent significant time in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
	   The trail from Boston to New York has also been famously traveled by
baseball greats Babe Ruth, Wade Boggs and Roger Clemens, noted Marist College
pollster Lee Miringoff.
</P>
<P>
	   "That raises the key question for Weld of course," Miringoff joked. "Is he a
Yankee or a Red Sox fan? The answer to that question will determine his
acceptability."
</P>
<P>
	   Weld is not known as a particularly avid baseball fan, preferring to play
squash a few times a week.
</P>
<P>
	   But for a primer on the politics of baseball, just ask Mrs. Clinton.
</P>
<P>
	   She invited a firestorm of skepticism when she tugged on a Yankees cap at
the White House earlier this year and declared she had always been a fan of the
Bronx Bombers. Mrs. Clinton, who rooted for the Chicago Cubs during her
childhood in Illinois, later had to explain that the Cubs had been her National
League favorite while she had adopted the Yankees as her American League team.
</P>
<P>
	   That explanation left some diehard Yankees fans, like her most likely Senate
race rival New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, unconvinced.
</P>
<P>
	   Weld did not return a phone call seeking comment Friday. But in an earlier
interview the moderate Republican said he'd be "hard to stop" if he did decide
to add the title New York governor to his resume. Unlike Mrs. Clinton, who has
never lived or worked in New York, Weld grew up on Long Island and has a
vacation home in the Adirondacks.
</P>
<P>
	   To satisfy New York's residency requirements, Weld must live in New York for
five years before running for governor. For now he's busy buying and selling
companies as a managing partner at McDermott, Will &AMP; Emery's New York office.
</P>
<P>
	   Mrs. Clinton must only be living in New York by election day to run for the
Senate to satisfy residency requirements. She moved into her Chappaqua home this
week to deflect carpetbagging charges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-08-00 0116 </TRAILER>
