<HEADLINE> County Gets Custody of Disabled Boy  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST CHESTER, Pa. (AP) -- A judge has awarded Chester County custody of a
severely disabled boy whose parents left him at a hospital the day after
Christmas with a note saying they could no longer care for him.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We will be developing a treatment plan in the best interests of the child,
like all children we deal with,'' said James Forsyth, executive director of the
county's Department of Children, Youth &AMP; Families.
</P>
<P>
	   Police charged Richard and Dawn Kelso of Exton with abandonment of a child
and conspiracy after they were accused of leaving their 10-year-old son Steven
in the emergency room of the A.I. du Pont Hospital for Children in Rockland,
Del., on Dec. 26.
</P>
<P>
	   He has been at the hospital ever since.
</P>
<P>
	   Officials could not say Friday when the boy would leave the hospital to
return to Chester County, where his parents live.
</P>
<P>
	   On Wednesday, the Kelsos filed a petition asking a judge for permission to
visit him. There was no indication of when they would get an answer.
</P>
<P>
	   Family members have said the couple had been caring for their son in 10-hour
shifts after they were unable to find nursing help during the Christmas
holidays.
</P>
<P>
	   Steven, who was born three months premature and was hospitalized for the
first 18 months of his life, cannot walk or talk, suffers from frequent seizures
and needs constant medical attention.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
