<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 01:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCain Letters Spark Questions  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- From airlines to telephone companies, Sen. John McCain
wrote to federal regulators on behalf of more than a dozen contributors over the
last three years, according to hundreds of documents that were to be made public
today.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain, chairman of the powerful Senate Commerce Committee, weighed in on
behalf of BellSouth, trying to offer long-distance service; Ameritech, trying to
merge with SBC Communications; America West airlines, trying to offer airline
service out of Flagstaff Airport; and other corporate givers.
</P>
<P>
	   The documents were provided to The Associated Press by the Senate Commerce
Committee on Friday. Besides the memos written on behalf of donors, there were
hundreds of letters written in response to individuals, including more than 20
letters referred to the Transportation Department from travel agents upset about
airlines capping their commissions.
</P>
<P>
	   And the memos show that McCain intervened just as forcefully on behalf of
companies that did not give to his campaign. For example, in a July 1999 letter
to Federal Communications Commission Chairman William Kennard, McCain complained
about the delay in transferring a broadcast license for a Texas radio station.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain is hardly alone in his letter writing. The FCC said this week it had
received between 7,000 and 8,000 pieces of correspondence a year from lawmakers
in the past three years about issues pending before the agency.
</P>
<P>
	   Aides said the senator would ask all federal agencies on Monday to release
the letters he had sent them over the last three years. And the senator
challenged his competitors for the Republican presidential nomination to release
letters they had sent on behalf of campaign contributors.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain's letters came to light at a pivotal time. The Arizona senator has
risen in the polls while campaigning to rid the nation's political system of
what he calls the ``pernicious'' influence of money.
</P>
<P>
	   That campaign theme has struck a chord among independents, and has helped
vault McCain into a highly competitive race with Texas Gov. George W. Bush in
New Hampshire, the nation's first primary state.
</P>
<P>
	   But in recent days, he has been forced to answer questions about his role
helping donors.
</P>
<P>
	   Twice in 1998, McCain urged Kennard to consider wireless services, such as
Sprint PCS, as competitors to BellSouth, which wants to provide long-distance
service. Such a ruling would remove a regulatory barrier the regional Bell
companies faced in their bids to enter the long-distance market.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I encourage you to give serious consideration to whether PCS is providing
competition to the local exchange market,'' McCain wrote.
</P>
<P>
	   Senate Commerce Committee Republican staff director Mark Buse said McCain's
advocacy on behalf of the Baby Bells was consistent with his support for
telecommunications competition that would result in lower prices for customers.
</P>
<P>
	   BellSouth and its employees have contributed $30,000 to his presidential bid
through Sept. 30, his third-most generous contributor. The company also hosted a
fund-raiser for him in Atlanta this spring.
</P>
<P>
	   BellSouth spokesman Bill McCloskey said the company has been a longtime
donor to McCain's campaigns.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We tend to give to people who ask us,'' McCloskey said. ``People who have
influence over our industry are more likely to ask us because they know us, and
they know us before we appear before their committee. We help our friends, and
John McCain is our friend.''
</P>
<P>
	   McCain also went to bat before the FCC on behalf of two other Baby Bells,
Ameritech and SBC Communications, who were seeking the agency's permission to
merge.
</P>
<P>
	   Two weeks after Ameritech Chairman Richard Notebaert held a fund-raiser for
him last spring, McCain sent a stinging letter to federal regulators accusing
them of being unfair toward the merger.
</P>
<P>
	   The letter accused the commission of ``applying a different, and much
stricter, burden of proof in this merger proceeding than the commission has
applied in evaluating other mergers.''
</P>
<P>
	   It also said, ``This letter expresses no view on the merits of any issues in
this proceeding and is not written to benefit any particular party.''
</P>
<P>
	   At a debate Friday night, McCain was questioned about the Ameritech letter.
</P>
<P>
	   ``All the times when I have weighed in, I have asked them to do their duty
and to expedite the procedures as they're laid out under the law and according
to existing regulations,'' he said. ``I will continue to do that job, and when a
constituent, a person of mine who has trouble -- or a citizen of this country
who can't get a reaction or an answer from a bureaucracy that's paid for with
their tax dollars, I believe that people like me should weigh in.''
</P>
<P>
	   Ameritech denied any connection between the fund-raisers and McCain's
letter.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This was totally Dick Notebaert's personal involvement as a member of the
host committee in Chicago,'' spokesman Dave Pacholczyk said.
</P>
<P>
	   Bude, the Commerce Committee staff director, noted that McCain also has
butted heads with the Bells. For example, Bude said, McCain is a strong
supporter of portability, the practice of allowing telephone customers to retain
their phone numbers if the move within the same area code. And he challenged the
fees the Bell companies were charging competitors to use their networks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-08-00 0118 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
