<DOCNO> APW20000108.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 01:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feds: Endangered Fish on the Rebound  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, Mo. (AP) -- An endangered fish whose ancestors swam with the
dinosaurs appears to be making a comeback in the Missouri River, the U.S. Fish
and Wildlife Service said.
</P>
<P>
	   Biologists working at the Big Muddy National Fish and Wildlife Refuge said
they have found pallid sturgeon hatchlings in the wild for the first time in
decades, an encouraging sign in the effort to save the species from extinction.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is wonderful,'' said Steve Krentz, who leads the Bismarck, N.D.-based
Pallid Sturgeon Recovery Team. ``Until these were found, the only young pallid
sturgeon we'd seen were products of spawning operations at hatcheries.''
</P>
<P>
	   Wildlife workers found the fish in August. A laboratory analysis, just
completed, confirmed at least one to be a pallid sturgeon, Krentz said Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   The pallid sturgeon can grow to 100 pounds, reach 6 feet in length and live
60 years. Distinguished by pale, bony plates instead of scales, it has a
reptile-like body, a sucker-type mouth and large whisker-like growths that help
it sense its surroundings.
</P>
<P>
	   The fish, once common, has been on the endangered species list since 1990.
Dams built on the river altered the pallid sturgeon's habitat, taking away the
shallow, silty conditions -- along with the sand and gravel bars -- that it
needs to thrive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-08-00 0119 </TRAILER>
