<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 01:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dying Cost Rises in Silicon Valley  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN MATEO, Calif. (AP) -- In Silicon Valley, getting a place for a family of
four is expensive. Throw in a mountaintop view and a professionally tended yard
and a $265,000 find is a steal.
</P>
<P>
	   This is not about a reasonably priced home. It's a cemetery plot.
</P>
<P>
	   A special section of four-person burial plots with panoramic views at San
Mateo County's Skylawn Memorial Park are part of Silicon Valley's other
real-estate boom. Cemetery lots in desirable settings appreciate in value as
fast as houses.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's demand, like anything else,'' said John Milne, director of family
services at San Jose's Oak Hill Memorial Park. ``You can buy a cemetery lot in
Iowa for $100. Here, the average price is about $3,400.''
</P>
<P>
	   A General Accounting Office study found cemetery lots nationally ranged from
$150 to $1,900 in 1997, but government officials and industry groups said they
usually don't track such costs.
</P>
<P>
	   Nonetheless, people in the business say they've seen big price hikes
recently.
</P>
<P>
	   Karel van Haeften, part owner of Cemetery Property Resales in San Mateo, in
1999 brokered 21 cemetery plots whose value increased considerably faster than
the Consumer Price Index.
</P>
<P>
	   One San Jose are plot priced at $1,250 in 1987 was valued recently at
$3,720. Another sold for $2,500 in 1987 is now worth $12,095. By contrast, the
average price of goods tracked by the CPI has approximately doubled since 1980.
</P>
<P>
	   As with housing for the living, cemetery plots in choice locations tend to
be pricier.
</P>
<P>
	   At Skylawn, plots low on the hill sell for $7,500. Built into a plaza at the
very top were 20 family plots, each big enough for four people, which were going
for $265,000 or $66,250 per body.
</P>
<P>
	   ``People are willing to pay for the value that they receive,'' said the
cemetery's general manager, Margo Scolari, noting that three of the plaza plots
have been sold.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-08-00 0126 </TRAILER>
