<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 01:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Floor Brokers Sentenced for Scam  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- A judge has sentenced four New York Stock Exchange floor
brokers and two executives to prison or home detention for engaging in illegal
trading.
</P>
<P>
	   William Killeen, 39, the head of Wall Street brokerage Oakford Corp., was
sentenced to 20 months in prison and the firm's vice president, Thomas Bock, 46,
was sentenced to 18 months. Both men were fined $50,000.
</P>
<P>
	   They admitted that their now-defunct company illegally allowed floor brokers
to execute personal trades ahead of orders from their customers.
</P>
<P>
	   This was believed to be the first case to result from illegal personal
trades by floor brokers.
</P>
<P>
	   Floor brokers are paid a commission to conduct trades for client brokerages
and their customers. They are not permitted to make trades for themselves or for
any account in which they have an interest because they can have immediate
access to market-moving news, giving them an unfair advantage.
</P>
<P>
	   The judge on Friday rejected arguments that four of the firm's brokers
should not face prison terms because they were not properly informed by the
Stock Exchange that what they were doing was a crime.
</P>
<P>
	   The brokers, John Savarese, 35, Mark Savarese, 38, Edward Mueger, 65, and
Thomas Cavallino, 43, had all pleaded guilty earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
	   The Savarese brothers were each sentenced to four months in prison followed
by two months of home detention. They were each fined $15,000.
</P>
<P>
	   Mueger was sentenced to three months in prison and three months of home
confinement. He was also fined $15,000.
</P>
<P>
	   And Cavallino was sentenced to six months of home confinement and fined
$100,000. The judge spared Cavallino a prison term but increased his fine after
listening to pleas that he be left at home to care for his son.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-08-00 0131 </TRAILER>
