<DOCNO> APW20000108.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 02:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syrian Village Watching Peace Talks  </HEADLINE>
   By SUSAN SEVAREID Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HADAR, Syria (AP) -- In a village on a snowy hillside where people have to
shout across a mined valley to relatives in Israeli-occupied territory,
residents have been closely following the peace talks being held in an equally
secluded town in rural West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
	   On radios and televisions, they hear and see the Arab news broadcasts from
Shepherdstown, W. Va., where President Clinton intervened again Friday to try to
push Israel and Syria to a land-for-peace agreement that would end 50 years of
hostilities and change the map of their area in the Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1973, Israel occupied Hadar, this Druze village of 10,000 people, and
then abandoned it the following year as its troops pulled back 3 miles.
</P>
<P>
	   Mashir Bassar, a 46-year-old resident who works as a teacher, said Friday
that he is hopeful peace will result -- and is afraid the opportunity may not
come around again. But he said he is concerned that there has been no formal
Israeli commitment to returning all of the Golan to Syria.
</P>
<P>
	   Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak has said the price of peace would be
painful to his country but has not publicly spelled out any plan of withdrawing
completely from the 744 square miles that Israel still occupies.
</P>
<P>
	   Bassar said his secondary school students discuss the peace process in class
and follow developments at home.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We teach the students about full peace -- the need for returning all of
the land,'' he said. ``What we have heard up to now from Israel is only words
about peace, nothing about returning the land.''
</P>
<P>
	   Syria's state-run media, which reflects government thinking, voiced similar
complaints Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   The newspaper Al-Thawra called on Israel to announce an ``honest, specific
and clear position that reflects its commitment to the land-for-peace
principle.''
</P>
<P>
	   Damascus Radio accused Israel of procrastinating at the talks in their fifth
day on Friday, saying the Israelis ``say things that completely differ from what
they do.''
</P>
<P>
	   Syrian negotiators, the radio commentary said, went to West Virginia
``basically to discuss peaceful relations with Israel but also to restore the
whole area of Golan.''
</P>
<P>
	   Hadar residents agree that less than a full Israeli withdrawal is not
acceptable. But even those who have lived through the past half century of wars
and hostility say they have hope for peace soon.
</P>
<P>
	   Osman Yatouf, 65, says he expects peace to come in his lifetime. For Yatouf
-- who sells costume jewelry, baby clothes, socks and lotions in a cramped shop
along Hadar's steep and winding main street -- peace would mean visiting his
sister any time he likes.
</P>
<P>
	   Sihan Yatouf lives in Majd al-Shams, a Druze village just inside
Israeli-occupied territory.
</P>
<P>
	   The Red Cross arranged for her to visit Hadar for a month nine years ago.
She can telephone her brother from time to time. But the siblings mainly
communicate through megaphones that allow them to call out news 200 yards across
the mined valley that divides them.
</P>
<P>
	   It is a valley that has earned two names over the decades -- the Valley of
Shouts and the Valley of Tears.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-08-00 0209 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000108.0076 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 02:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexican Students Reject Offer  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Students who have shut down Mexico's largest public
school with an eight-month strike rejected an offer from university officials to
meet some of their demands, saying the offer didn't go far enough.
</P>
<P>
	   The offer that the strikers turned down Friday included eliminating a plan
to raise tuition at the National Autonomous University of Mexico from the
equivalent of a few cents to $140 annually. That proposed tuition increase --
the first in decades -- was what originally sparked the strike.
</P>
<P>
	   The university negotiators walked out of Friday's talks after six hours
because the students refused to discuss the offer.
</P>
<P>
	   After the talks, the strikers said in a statement that they are now
demanding the release of several students arrested during a Dec. 11
demonstration for allegedly hurling rocks and launching fireworks at the U.S.
Embassy and police. That protest was called to demand the release of other
demonstrators arrested during the recent World Trade Organization meeting in
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
	   A group of striking students seized the university campus April 20. While
there are 268,000 students at the university, the strikers represent a few
thousand.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We have come close to meeting the demands originally put forward'' by the
striking students, said Xavier Soberon, who represents the university's rector
in the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
	   The students' demands also include automatic admission for graduates of the
university's prep school and a lowering of academic standards.
</P>
<P>
	   The university offer, drawn up by newly appointed Rector Juan Ramon de la
Fuente, maintained that those issues should be voted on at a convention of
university staff, faculty and students.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
