<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 02:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bills' Reed Stands By His Words  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    ORCHARD PARK, N.Y. (AP) -- Buffalo Bills wide receiver Andre Reed promises
to be his old self today.
</P>
<P>
	   Coach Wade Phillips "is looking for me to play 100 percent, and that's what
I'm going to do," Reed said as the Bills prepared to meet Tennessee in a
wild-card playoff game. "The bottom line is I'm going to go out and try to be
the best I can to help this team win. It's about winning, and that's all I want
to do."
</P>
<P>
	   Earlier in the week, it was all about criticizing. Reed made disparaging
comments about the team on his Internet site Tuesday. His discouraging words
came only two days after he helped Buffalo beat Indianapolis 31-6 with five
receptions.
</P>
<P>
	   The catches moved him into second place on the NFL's career receptions list
with 945, behind only Jerry Rice of the San Francisco 49ers. But on Tuesday, it
didn't seem to matter to Reed.
</P>
<P>
	   "It wasn't just a happy moment for me, but also frustration," Reed wrote.
"The five balls that I did catch weren't even routes, and that just makes me
look bad, like they have to give me charity throws. They've just been throwing
me bones to keep me happy, but I'm not happy at all.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think the franchise realizes that, and they know that I don't want to be
here anymore," Reed continued. "You look at the game Monday night with Jerry in
San Francisco. The 49ers still respect Jerry, and whether it was his last game
in that uniform or not, I think he went out the way he wanted to.
</P>
<P>
	   "Here, they haven't given me that freedom and respect. I'm sure San
Francisco wouldn't do that to Jerry Rice. It'll be a chip on my shoulder for a
long, long time. I think I can start fresh somewhere else and offer a team
something next year and hopefully go out the way I want to."
</P>
<P>
	   When confronted Thursday about his remarks, Reed was not contrite.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm not going to duck anything about how I feel about the situation this
year," he said. "People have their own feelings about things. Sometimes you
close your mouth so many times and it eats you up. And it's been eating me up
all year. I just said how I feel."
</P>
<P>
	   Reed, a 15-year veteran and likely Hall of Famer, said he has put the matter
behind him -- for now -- and is focusing on Saturday's game.
</P>
<P>
	   Reed's journal also included criticism of quarterback Doug Flutie, who was
replaced by Rob Johnson after starting the first 15 games of the season.
</P>
<P>
	   "You may have heard that I am not on speaking terms with Doug Flutie," Reed
wrote. "Doug Flutie has changed as a person over one year."
</P>
<P>
	   Flutie and Reed spoke to each other on Thursday and cleared the air.
</P>
<P>
	   "There's no problem between Andre and I," Flutie said. "It never has been as
far as I was concerned."
</P>
<P>
	   Flutie said Reed apparently was upset because he thought Flutie had him
pulled from the Nov. 28 game at New England. Reed did not catch a pass and his
playing time was limited by the coaching staff because he suffered from a rib
injury the previous week.
</P>
<P>
	   "I was told during the New England game that he was hurt, that his ribs were
bothering him, and they put Peerless (Price) in," Flutie said. "I guess he was
under the impression that I went to the coaches, and that was the only thing he
indicated was bothering him."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
