<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 02:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Baseball Roundup  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Free agents Aaron Sele, Andy Benes and Juan Guzman have
picked the places where they want to pitch in 2000.
</P>
<P>
	   Sele, 38-20 for Texas the past two seasons, agreed to a $29 million,
four-year contract with the Baltimore Orioles on Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   Benes, whose career slumped during two seasons with Arizona, returned to the
St. Louis Cardinals for an $18 million, three-year deal.
</P>
<P>
	   Guzman, who finished strong for Cincinnati, got a two-year contract from
Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
	   Sele, whose deal was subject to him passing a physical, was 18-9 with a 4.79
ERA last year. The 29-year-old right-hander had narrowed his choices to Tampa
Bay and Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
	   His deal calls for salaries of $7 million in each of the first three years
and $8 million in the fourth. The Orioles are deferring $2 million a year
without interest.
</P>
<P>
	   Benes was 18-10 on the Cardinals' NL Central championship team in 1996. He
left as a free agent after 1997 when general manager Walt Jocketty and Benes'
agent, Scott Boras, agreed to a five-year deal about 1 1/2 hours after the Dec.
7 deadline for players to re-sign. The contract was rejected by the
commissioner's office.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm thrilled to death to be coming back," Benes said. "I really felt in my
heart St. Louis is the place I want to be. The last couple years I've had on a
different color uniform, but my heart was in St. Louis."
</P>
<P>
	   Benes, 32, was 13-12 with a 4.81 ERA in 198 1-3 innings last year, winning
six of his last seven decisions.
</P>
<P>
	   His deal calls for a $2 million signing bonus that's payable from 2003-10,
$2.5 million this year and $6 million in the next two seasons. The contract has
a $6 million mutual option for 2002 with a $1.5 million buyout.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition, he can make $500,000 a year in performance bonuses if he has 34
starts and 230 innings.
</P>
<P>
	   Guzman, 33, was a combined 11-12 with a 3.74 ERA in 33 starts for Baltimore
and Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
	   Tampa Bay wanted a starting pitcher to replace Rolando Arrojo, traded last
month in a four-team deal that brought hard-hitting third baseman Vinny
Castilla. Guzman's contract includes a club option for a third year.
</P>
<P>
	   The Devil Rays, who also signed slugger Greg Vaughn last month, had pursued
free agent pitchers Sele and Steve Trachsel.
</P>
<P>
	   "Juan brings not only outstanding pitching credentials, but a tremendous
competitive spirit and the experience of pitching for championship ballclubs,"
general manager Chuck LaMar said.
</P>
<P>
	   Several other free agents found new homes Friday. Utilityman F.P. Santangelo
got a $1.6 million, two-year deal from the Los Angeles Dodgers, and right-hander
Brian Williams got a $600,000, one-year contract from the Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
	   Anaheim signed three second basemen, agreeing to a one-year contract with
Scott Spiezio and minor league contracts with Pat Kelly and Jason Bates.
</P>
<P>
	   Left-hander Norm Charlton decided to stay with the Tampa Bay Devil Rays,
agreeing to a minor league contract. He would get a $500,000, one-year deal if
he's added to the major league roster and the chance to earn $500,000 more in
performance bonuses.
</P>
<P>
	   Six free agents who rejected salary arbitration offers from their former
teams faced a midnight EST deadline Saturday to re-sign: left-hander Chris Haney
(Cleveland), right-hander Omar Olivares (Oakland), right-hander Steve Trachsel
(Chicago Cubs), outfielder Shawon Dunston (New York Mets) and left-hander Darren
Oliver (St. Louis).
</P>
<P>
	   Five players eligible for salary arbitration agreed to one-year deals
Friday, including Los Angeles right-hander Darren Dreifort ($3.7 million),
Toronto left-hander Pedro Borbon ($800,000).
</P>
<P>
	   Also signed were three Cardinals: third baseman Craig Paquette ($595,000),
left-hander Paul Spoljaric ($550,000) and right-hander Mark Thompson ($400,000).
</P>
<P>
	   Approximately 107 players are eligible to file for arbitration by the Jan.
14 deadline.
</P>
<P>
	   Also, the San Francisco Giants acquired right-hander Ken Ray from the Kansas
City Royals to complete the Dec. 13 trade that sent right-hander Jerry Spradlin
to the Royals.
</P>
<P>
	   And Pete Incaviglia, who hit 206 home runs during several stops in the
majors, signed with the Nashua Pride of the independent Atlantic League.
</P>
<P>
	   The 35-year-old outfielder hit a combined .181 with one homer and 13 RBIs
last year while playing for the Triple-A teams of Arizona and Houston.
</P>
<P>
	   "He says his arm is feeling better than it ever has," newly picked Nashua
manager Butch Hobson said. "He can hit the ball a long way. He'll get some
standing ovations."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
