<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 02:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Woods Cruising To Another Win  </HEADLINE>
    By DOUG FERGUSON AP Golf Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   KAPALUA, Hawaii (AP) -- Ernie Els wanted a chance to play with Tiger Woods
early in the year, the perfect opportunity to see what the two-time U.S. Open
champion would have to do in order to challenge the No. 1 player in the world.
</P>
<P>
	   The first meeting on Friday was a real eye-opener.
</P>
<P>
	   While Els put together a solid 3-under 70 under more blustery winds in Maui,
Woods seemed to be playing a different course -- certainly a different game --
in the second round of the Mercedes Championship.
</P>
<P>
	   Woods put himself halfway home to his fifth straight PGA Tour victory with a
7-under 66 -- eight strokes better than the average score Friday -- that gave
him a four-stroke lead over Els and left everyone else wondering whether Woods
had a pulse.
</P>
<P>
	   "The guy is kind of a freak, you know what I mean?" Els said.
</P>
<P>
	   Woods drove the green on two par 4s and had four eagle putts for the second
round. While the trade winds continued to rage across the Plantation Course at
Kapalua, he missed only two greens and made his only bogey on a three-putt from
about 105 feet.
</P>
<P>
	   After two days, Woods was at 9-under 137 and on cruise control.
</P>
<P>
	   Jesper Parnevik made two double bogeys on the back nine for the second day
in a row, but this time it cost him. He had a 1-over 74 and was six strokes
behind at 143. Jeff Sluman (72) was another stroke back.
</P>
<P>
	   Defending champion David Duval continued to save his worst swings for the
par-5s and shot even-par 73, joining Tim Herron and Jim Furyk at 1-under 145. No
one else was under par through 36 holes, and not many had a realistic chance of
catching Woods.
</P>
<P>
	   "The more you're in awe of him, the more you can't beat him," Stuart Appleby
said. "He has the potential to be the best player in the last 50 years, no doubt
about that. You could pat him on the back, but what's the point? He knows how
good he is."
</P>
<P>
	   No one since Ben Hogan in 1953 has fired off five straight victories. Woods
reached four at the American Express Championship in Valderrama to close out
last year, in which he became the first player in 25 years to win eight tour
events.
</P>
<P>
	   Seven weeks later, not much has changed. New season, same old story.
</P>
<P>
	   Woods, however, isn't thinking about his streak. As far as he's concerned,
it ended as soon as the PGA Tour ran out of official events in 1999. The streaks
of Hogan in 1948 and '53, and the record of 11 by Byron Nelson, all took place
in the same calendar year.
</P>
<P>
	   "The string is over," Woods said of his four straight victories to close out
the '99 season. "That was last year. This is a whole new year. I need a fresh
start. I need to move on and try to play good golf and improve my game."
</P>
<P>
	   For all the talk about a rivalry between Woods and Duval, or Woods and
Sergio Garcia, the player Woods has confronted more during his short career is
Els.
</P>
<P>
	   Two years ago in Thailand, Woods charged from eight strokes off the lead in
the final round of the Johnnie Walker to catch Els and beat him in a playoff.
Still stinging over that loss, Els returned the favor a month later by crushing
Woods in a 36-hole Sunday at Bay Hill.
</P>
<P>
	   Their last encounter was three months ago in Disney, where Els made a
crucial bogey on the back nine Sunday and lost by one.
</P>
<P>
	   Lately, Els concedes he isn't in the same league as Woods, or even Duval.
But he also views 2000 as a turning point in his career, a challenge to himself
that he can compete with the best players in the world.
</P>
<P>
	   Today might be as good a day as any to find out.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'd like to beat him once," Els said. "Don't get me wrong -- I'm not out
there playing for second. But it's awfully tough playing a guy who's driving
onto greens that are 450 yards away."
</P>
<P>
	   Els exaggerated, but only slightly.
</P>
<P>
	   Woods popped his driver a mere 398 yards to reach the green on the par-4
6th, then nailed another one on the 373-yard 11th hole that grazed Furyk's left
foot as he was lining up a putt.
</P>
<P>
	   "Tiger ... this guy is on fire," Els said. "He's got all the talent in the
world. What can you do? You've just got to stick to your guns. But he's got
bigger guns than I have. If he goes out there and shoots another two 66s,
there's no way we can get there.
</P>
<P>
	   "You never know," he said. "Tiger might make mistakes. Hopefully, he's
human."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-08-00 0247 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
