<HEADLINE> Beckham Suspended for World Cup Game  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- David Beckham could have wound up in worst
shape. All he got for his latest violent kick was a one-game suspension and
$1,250 fine.
</P>
<P>
	   The Manchester United star was penalized Friday by FIFA, soccer's governing
body, for his actions in Thursday's 1-1 tie against Mexico's Necaxa in the first
World Cup Championship.
</P>
<P>
	   Manchester United coach Alex Ferguson, ejected for protesting Beckham's
expulsion, also was suspended for one game and fined $3,125. The pair will miss
today's Group B game against Brazil's Vasco da Gama.
</P>
<P>
	   FIFA could have suspended Beckham for longer, but its disciplinary committee
decided not to.
</P>
<P>
	   Beckham also was ejected for a violent kick during England's second-round
loss to Argentina in the 1998 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
	   Neither Beckham nor Ferguson, who on Thursday said the expulsions were
"unfair," were immediately available for comment.
</P>
<P>
	   In Sao Paulo, Real Madrid of Spain and Corinthians of Brazil (both 1-0-1)
played a 2-2 tie in the opener of Friday's Group A doubleheader. Nicolas Anelka
scored for Real Madrid in the 19th and 71st minutes, but Corinthians got goals
from Edilson in the 28th and 70th.
</P>
<P>
	   Corinthians goalkeeper Dida stopped a penalty kick by Anelka in the second
half after Fabio Luciano fouled Savio inside the penalty area.
</P>
<P>
	   In the second game, Saudi Arabia's Al-Nassr beat Morocco's Raja Casablanca
4-3 on Moussa Saib's 85th-minute goal.
</P>
<P>
	   Fuad Al Amin, Ahmed Bahja, Fahad Al Husseini also scored for Al-Nassr (1-1).
Omar Nejjary, Bouchaib El Moubarki and Talal El Karkouri scored for Raja (0-2).
</P>
</TEXT>
