<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 02:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Utah City Prepares for Olympics  </HEADLINE>
By TIM KORTE-
AP Sports Writer-
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARK CITY, Utah (AP) -- John Aalberg has a full plate this weekend.
</P>
<P>
	As manager of the Soldier Hollow venue that will stage the cross country and
biathlon events during the 2002 Winter Olympics, he's got lots to monitor during
the U.S. cross country championships.
</P>
<P>
	``We're testing the flow of people,'' said Aalberg, a U.S. Olympic skier in
1992 and `94. ``We're asking the athletes how they like the course of the trail.
There are so many little things. It's a lot of work.''
</P>
<P>
	The Nordic skiing event that begins today is part of a big Olympic weekend in
the Park City area.
</P>
<P>
	There's also a World Cup freestyle skiing competition and U.S. championships in
the so-called ``sliding'' sports of bobsled, luge and skeleton, which is sort of
a face-first version of luge.
</P>
<P>
	With the Winter Games 25 months away, the competitions represent the Salt Lake
Organizing Committee's first major events at three important Olympic venues.
</P>
<P>
	``There's a big reason we do these test events,'' said Herwig Demschar, SLOC's
director of Alpine sports. ``You can't just pull the Olympic Games out of your
pocket.''
</P>
<P>
	World Cup skiing races in the super-G and slalom were scheduled for Park City
in November but that event was moved to Colorado because of a lack of snow in
Utah.
</P>
<P>
	Now there's plenty of snow, setting the stage for another try.
</P>
<P>
	At Deer Valley Resort, the freestyle skiing World Cup runs today and Sunday.
Skiers will pound the moguls one day and perform daring aerials the next.
</P>
<P>
	At the largest Olympic venue, the expansive Soldier Hollow, some 400 Nordic
skiers will trek over trails carved through the woods near Midway. The event
runs through Jan. 16.
</P>
<P>
	At the Utah Winter Sports Park, the frozen track that winds down Bear Hollow
gets a big test as American titles are decided in bobsled, luge and skeleton.
</P>
<P>
	In skeleton, athletes race alone down the course face first, their chins only
inches above the ice at speeds up to 80 mph. Skeleton, dropped in the early
1900s as an Olympic sport, returns in 2002.
</P>
<P>
	Duncan Kennedy, America's most successful singles luger and a television
commentator for this week's events, said it's significant to stage all three
sliding sports simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
	``This is a huge event for everybody involved,'' Kennedy said. ``Whether they
can pull it off, we'll see, but it's a great experiment. We're really setting a
footprint for the future.''
</P>
<P>
	The Paralympic Games, which will run in March 2002 after the Olympics, also had
a preview this week with the Huntsman Cup for disabled skiers at Park City
Mountain Resort.
</P>
<P>
	After months of planning and construction, the three venues are largely
finished. However, officials will work out of trailers until buildings go up at
Soldier Hollow at the Winter Sports Park.
</P>
<P>
	Other facilities, such as parking lots, remain unfinished.
</P>
<P>
	``We haven't really done much to publicize the sliding events because we still
don't have enough parking,'' said Wendy Watkins, a clerk at the Winter Sports
Park.
</P>
<P>
	It was a mass of frenzied voices inside the Winter Sports Park's main trailer
Friday, as a stream of bobsledders, lugers and skeleton racers and officials
checked in.
</P>
<P>
	At each site, the people in charge were eager to start.
</P>
<P>
	``We've done our homework,'' said Jeff Chumas, who will oversee the freestyle
events. ``I just really look forward to these next couple of days and certainly
the next couple of years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-08-00 0248 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000108.0092 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 02:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Denver Johnson New Ill. State Coach  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NORMAL, Ill. (AP) -- As football coaching jobs go, Denver Johnson is walking
into a pretty good situation at Illinois State.
</P>
<P>
	   Instead of taking over a struggling program, Johnson is inheriting a team
that had one of the best seasons in school history last year.
</P>
<P>
	   The Redbirds already play a style of football similar to his own, so he
won't have to teach totally new schemes.
</P>
<P>
	   About the only downside, Johnson said, is that expectations tend to be
higher for coaches taking over successful teams. But he thinks there is plenty
of opportunity to exceed recent achievements.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think there is a tremendous amount of unrealized potential here," Johnson
said as he was introduced as coach Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   Johnson left Murray State, where he had a 21-12 record in three years.
</P>
<P>
	   "Denver knows the complexities of what it takes to be a successful head
coach because he's been one," Perk Weisenburger, ISU athletics director, said.
</P>
<P>
	   Johnson, 41, replaces Todd Berry, who left at the end of the season to take
the top job at Army. Berry rebuilt Illinois State football, leading the Redbirds
to the Gateway Conference title this season and an 11-3 record, losing to
Georgia Southern 28-17 in the I-AA semifinals.
</P>
<P>
	   Berry was voted the league's coach of the year. His overall record at the
school was 24-24 in four seasons.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think the horizon has broadened and the future is bright for Illinois
State football," Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
	   He said Berry left behind a program that's in good shape with young players
and plenty of momentum. Johnson, who coached with Berry at Tennessee-Martin,
said they follow similar coaching philosophies, and he doesn't expect to make
many changes on either side of the ball.
</P>
<P>
	   "As a fan sitting in the stands, I don't think you'll notice any drastic
changes," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   First on the agenda, Johnson said, is recruiting. He said he will contact
the two high school seniors who have already committed to ISU and then begin
working on other recruits. But he said he must begin building relationships with
returning players immediately.
</P>
<P>
	   "The first recruiting job I feel like I have to do right now is with the
young men already in this program," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Johnson played on the offensive line at the University of Tulsa, then spent
four seasons in professional football. His first full-time coaching job was at
Tennessee-Martin, and he later coached at Oklahoma State and Mississippi State.
He spent one year at Oklahoma before taking over at Murray State in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
