<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 02:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hockey Roundup  </HEADLINE>
    By The Associated Press
<TEXT>
<P>
	   Paul Coffey talked. Jeff O'Neill listened -- and scored.
</P>
<P>
	   O'Neill had two third-period goals as the Carolina Hurricanes rallied to tie
visiting Anaheim 4-4 on Friday night, the franchise's first four-goal comeback
since 1980.
</P>
<P>
	   "Between the second and third periods, Paul Coffey motivated the troops,"
said O'Neill, who drew Carolina within two 36 seconds into the third off an
assist from Coffey.
</P>
<P>
	   O'Neill made it 4-3 midway through the period with his 14th goal, and Glen
Wesley tied it with 7:27 left. Coffey, the highest-scoring defenseman in NHL
history, also assisted on Wesley's goal.
</P>
<P>
	   In other NHL games, it was Pittsburgh 5, Toronto 2; Vancouver 3, Dallas 1;
Edmonton 5, Tampa Bay 1; and Colorado 4, Montreal 1.
</P>
<P>
	   Andrei Kovalenko began the rally -- the Hurricanes franchise's first
four-goal comeback since the Hartford Whalers tied Montreal 5-5 on March 19,
1980 -- late in the second period.
</P>
<P>
	   "This was a big character point," Carolina coach Paul Maurice said. "It's
going to have some long-lasting affects in that room."
</P>
<P>
	   Teemu Selanne had a first-period goal, and Marty McInnis, Jim McKenzie and
Jeff Nielsen scored in a 6 1/2-minute span of the second period to give Anaheim
a 4-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's ridiculous what happened," Anaheim coach Craig Hartsburg said. "Guys
stopped working. Some guys didn't. Some guys stuck with it, but a lot of guys we
count heavily on just shut it down."
</P>
<P>
	   Anaheim is 0-4-1 in its last five.
</P>
<P>
	   Alexei Kovalev scored a short-handed goal in the second period as Pittsburgh
beat visiting Toronto to give Herb Brooks his 200th NHL coaching victory.
</P>
<P>
	   Brooks, 10-4 since replacing Kevin Constantine on Dec. 9, has a career
record of 200-202-61 with the New York Rangers, Minnesota, New Jersey and
Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
	   Darius Kasparaitis, Michal Rozsival, Jan Hrdina and Martin Straka also
scored for Pittsburgh. Dimitri Yushkevich and Jonas Hoglund scored for Toronto.
</P>
<P>
	   Donald Brashear scored the go-ahead goal with 7:03 left in Vancouver's
victory in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
	   Todd Bertuzzi and Alexander Mogilny also had third-period goals, and Garth
Snow made 31 saves to help the Canucks win for only the third time in their last
19 games (3-12-4).
</P>
<P>
	   Kirk Muller scored for Dallas.
</P>
<P>
	   Tommy Salo stopped Mike Sillinger on a penalty shot in the second period as
Edmonton beat Tampa Bay, extending the Lightning's winless streak to 10 games.
</P>
<P>
	   Todd Marchant, Ryan Smyth, Rem Murray, Ethan Moreau and Bill Guerin scored
goals, and Mike Grier matched his career high with three assists to help the
Oilers improve to 5-0-3 in their last eight home games. Fredrik Modin scored for
Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
	   Milan Hejduk scored two goals late in the second period and former Montreal
goalie Patrick Roy made 22 saves for Colorado.
</P>
<P>
	   Chris Dingman and Adam Deadmarsh added goals, and Peter Forsberg had three
assists to help Colorado extend its unbeaten streak to a season-best five games
(4-0-1). Eric Weinrich scored for visiting Montreal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
