<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 02:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Basketball Roundup  </HEADLINE>
    By The Associated Press
<TEXT>
<P>
	   Break up the Bulls!
</P>
<P>
	   Better yet, break up the Wizards.
</P>
<P>
	   The worst team in the NBA finally put together its first two-game winning
streak of the season Friday night, beating Washington 110-103 just two nights
after defeating the Wizards in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
	   "They haven't scored 100 points all year and they went and scored 110
tonight. I don't know who is the worst team, them or us," Washington coach Gar
Heard said.
</P>
<P>
	   Toni Kukoc, in his second game back after missing most of the season with
back spasms, led the Bulls with 33 points.
</P>
<P>
	   Elsewhere, the Lakers defeated Charlotte 87-83, Vancouver beat New Jersey
101-91, Phoenix routed San Antonio 102-83, Atlanta beat Toronto 105-97, New York
defeated Orlando 94-86 and Boston beat Sacramento 101-93.
</P>
<P>
	   Chicago gained its first road victory of the season after 15 consecutive
losses.
</P>
<P>
	   The Wizards held several 10-point leads in the first half and had an
11-point advantage early in the third quarter before Kukoc and B.J. Armstrong
sparked the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
	   Armstrong scored 10 of his 14 points in the third quarter as the Bulls
rallied from a nine-point halftime deficit to take a 77-73 lead heading into the
final period.
</P>
<P>
	   Kukoc scored 10 in the fourth quarter, including a jumper with one second
left on the shot clock and 2:45 left in the game for a 101-90 lead.
</P>
<P>
	   "We probably can't go lower than this," Washington guard Rod Strickland
said. "We can't help but take the heat for this one. This is not good."
</P>
<P>
	   Glen Rice's 3-pointer against his former teammates gave Los Angeles its
first lead with 2:36 left and the Lakers went on to their 13th consecutive win.
</P>
<P>
	   Shaquille O'Neal had 23 points and 16 rebounds as the Lakers rallied in the
fourth quarter and overcame a 34 percent shooting night at home to win for the
20th time in 21 games.
</P>
<P>
	   Rice finished with 17 points.
</P>
<P>
	   Derrick Coleman had 17 points for Charlotte, including the 10,000th of his
career, and David Wesley and Bobby Phills added 17 points each.
</P>
<P>
	   At East Rutherford, N.J., Michael Dickerson scored 28 points as Vancouver
won its second road game in four nights.
</P>
<P>
	   Mike Bibby finished with 20 points, nine rebounds and nine assists, Shareef
Abdur-Rahim had 19 points and Othella Harrington added 16 points and 12
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
	   The Grizzlies, who won just one of their first 13 road games, improved to
4-6 overall and 2-4 on the road since Lionel Hollins took over as coach on Dec.
16. They beat the Heat in Miami earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
	   The Grizzlies also snapped New Jersey's home winning streak at nine games.
New Jersey hadn't lost at the Meadowlands since Dec. 4.
</P>
<P>
	   At Phoenix, David Robinson had 24 points and nine rebounds and Tim Duncan
had 19 points and 15 boards as San Antonio routed Phoenix for the Suns' worst
loss in Scott Skiles' 11 games as coach.
</P>
<P>
	   San Antonio, which had lost two in a row and five of eight, built a 22-point
lead in a dominating third quarter and coasted in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
	   The Spurs were 13-for-13 at the foul line in the third quarter, while the
Suns were 0-for-2.
</P>
<P>
	   At Atlanta, Jim Jackson scored 22 of his 31 points in the second half as the
Hawks snapped a season-high five-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
	   Isaiah Rider added 27 points, 20 in the first half, and Alan Henderson had
19 for the Hawks, who played their third game in a row with Stan Albeck handling
the coaching duties for Lenny Wilkens, who has the flu.
</P>
<P>
	   Vince Carter broke out of a mini-slump and had 34 points for the Raptors,
who erased a 17-point lead and went in front 82-81 on two free throws by Carter
with 6:28 left in the final period.
</P>
<P>
	   Anthony Johnson's basket from the top of the key with 6:10 to play gave the
Hawks the lead for good, 83-82.
</P>
<P>
	   At Orlando, Allan Houston scored 23 points and Latrell Sprewell had 19 as
New York won its third in a row.
</P>
<P>
	   Patrick Ewing had 18 points, nine rebounds and three blocks, while reserve
Kurt Thomas finished with 10 points and nine rebounds.
</P>
<P>
	   The loss was the sixth in seven games for Orlando.
</P>
<P>
	   At Boston, Kenny Anderson hit his only 3-pointer with two minutes left after
Nick Anderson's long-range shots kept bringing Sacramento back.
</P>
<P>
	   Boston won for the third time in four games behind Paul Pierce's 19 points,
Antoine Walker's 17 and Vitaly Potapenko's 16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
