<DOCTYPE> SUBDIVIDED </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 03:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    Saturday, Jan. 8, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Anti-Castro Lawmaker Subpoenas Cuban Boy
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   MIAMI (AP) -- In efforts to prevent Elian Gonzalez's return to Cuba, an
anti-Castro lawmaker subpoenaed him Friday to testify before a congressional
committee and one of his Miami relatives sought to become his legal guardian.
Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., said he subpoenaed 6-year-old Elian to testify before
the Committee on Government Reform on Feb. 10, so he remains in the country
while the courts consider his case. Elian was found Thanksgiving Day clinging to
an inner tube at sea after his mother, stepfather and eight other people drowned
while trying to reach Florida by boat. The boy was placed with family in Miami.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore Backpedals on Gay Policy
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Under political pressure, Vice President Al Gore
backpedaled Friday from his statement that he would require candidates for the
Joint Chiefs of Staff to agree with his intention to let gays serve openly in
the military. "I did not mean to imply that there should ever be any kind of
inquiry into the personal political opinions of officers in the U.S. military,"
Gore told reporters. Gore, under fire from military brass and some of his own
political allies, spoke two days after his original comments at a candidates'
debate. The comments have sparked dissent from former members of the joint
chiefs and from Sen. John Kerry, a Vietnam veteran campaigning for Gore in New
Hampshire.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Russia Shuffles Combat Commanders
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   GROZNY, Russia (AP) -- Russia has replaced its two top combat generals in
its campaign in Chechnya, a reshuffle that suggested government frustration with
the failure to take Grozny and strike a decisive blow against rebels. The
government insisted the changes were a routine staff rotation. The reshuffle
announced Friday came as Russian commanders indicated that a scaling-back of the
bombardment of the shattered capital had been ordered. Russian ground forces
began a major drive Dec. 25 to take Grozny, but have made little progress in the
face of fierce rebel resistance.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
County Gets Custody of Disabled Boy
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WEST CHESTER, Pa. (AP) -- A judge has awarded Chester County custody of a
severely disabled boy whose parents left him at a hospital the day after
Christmas with a note saying they could no longer care for him. "We will be
developing a treatment plan in the best interests of the child, like all
children we deal with," said James Forsyth, executive director of the county's
Department of Children, Youth &AMP; Families. Police charged Richard and Dawn Kelso
of Exton with abandonment of a child and conspiracy after they were accused of
leaving their 10-year-old son Steven in the emergency room of the A.I. du Pont
Hospital for Children in Rockland, Del., on Dec. 26.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bush, McCain Clash at Debate
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WEST COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Sen. John McCain
clashed sharply over tax cuts in the second Republican campaign debate. McCain
said it was fiscally irresponsible to promise a huge tax cut that is based on a
surplus the U.S. might not have. Bush retorted that his plan was more generous
than McCain's for lower income taxpayers and added firmly: "There is enough
money to take care of Social Security. There is enough money to take care of the
basic services of government, and there is enough money to give the people a
substantial tax cut. And that's what I intend to do."
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Life Cereal To Revive Mikey Ads
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   CHICAGO (AP) -- Life cereal is bringing back Mikey, the character made
famous in the 1970s commercial. The Mikey ad campaign is being relaunched, 28
years after its debut, with an all-adult cast. The lines are the same, and so is
the shtick. Only the actors playing Mikey and his breakfast mates are new. In
the original ad, which aired from 1972-84, two kids share their suspicion of a
cereal that's "sposed ta be good for ya." They decide to test it out on their
kid brother Mikey, because "he hates everything." But pudgy-faced Mikey, who
never utters a word, takes to it, prompting the famous lines: "He likes it! Hey,
Mikey!" The new commercial is to be launched Jan. 17 and run through June.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Soars to Record High
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Investors brushed off signs of inflationary pressure as the
Dow Jones industrials soared into record territory Friday. The Nasdaq composite,
which tumbled earlier this week, recorded its best day in history rising 155.45
to 3,882.58. The Dow rose 269.30 to close at 11,522.56, topping its Dec. 31
closing record.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Lakers Defeat Hornets 87-83
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Glen Rice's 3-pointer against his former teammates gave
Los Angeles its first lead with 2:36 left and the Lakers downed the Charlotte
Hornets 87-83 Friday night for their 13th consecutive win. Shaquille O'Neal had
23 points and 16 rebounds as the Lakers rallied in the fourth quarter and
overcame a 34 percent shooting night to win for the 20th time in 21 games.
</P>
