<HEADLINE> Former Soccer Star Maradona Ailing  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    PUNTA DEL ESTE, Uruguay (AP) -- Former soccer star Diego Maradona has a
serious heart condition and will remain hospitalized for about a week.
</P>
<P>
	   Maradona, who tested positive for cocaine after he was hospitalized this
week, was in intensive care on Tuesday after doctors diagnosed him with high
blood pressure and an irregular heartbeat.
</P>
<P>
	   He was moved to a regular hospital room on Thursday after improving.
</P>
<P>
	   "We have detected a severe heart pathology," Dr. Frank Torres said Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   Torres said he consulted with Maradona's personal physician, who said the
condition had not been detected in previous checkups.
</P>
<P>
	   Dr. Alfredo Cae, Maradona's personal doctor, described the former star's
condition as "delicate." Cae said he did not think Maradona's condition was
life-threatening.
</P>
<P>
	   Torres said Uruguayan police will continue their investigation into
Maradona's case after blood and urine samples taken from the star on Wednesday
revealed heavy traces of cocaine.
</P>
<P>
	   Maradona has not been questioned in the case, although his manager,
Guillermo Coppola, and a friend, Pablo Consentino, have been queried by
Uruguayan authorities. Police have also searched the summer home where Maradona
was staying.
</P>
<P>
	   An admitted cocaine addict, Maradona was twice banned from international
competition after testing positive for drug use. A positive test for cocaine in
1991 prompted a 15-month suspension from the Italian League and a positive test
for stimulants during the 1994 World Cup led to a 15-month suspension by FIFA.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
