<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 03:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Japan To Develop Nuke Robot  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Japan will develop a robot that can clean up radioactive leaks
like the one that killed a worker last year in the nation's worst nuclear
accident, a news report said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   The Ministry of Trade and Industry plans to team up with several companies
to develop the robot, which would spare humans the dangerous task of controlling
leaks at nuclear plants, Kyodo News agency reported. Ministry officials were
unavailable for comment over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
	   Several workers were exposed to dangerous levels of radiation when they
dealt with an accident in September at a uranium-reprocessing facility in
Tokaimura, 70 miles northeast of Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
	   A worker who was among those who triggered the disaster by using too much
uranium to make fuel died last month from radiation sickness. Two other workers
remain in serious condition.
</P>
<P>
	   The leak exposed at least 92 other people to less serious doses of
radiation.
</P>
<P>
	   The budget for the robot is equivalent to $29 million, and the government
hopes to complete the project by 2001, Kyodo said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-08-00 0308 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000108.0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 06:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Objects to 'Anna and King'  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- After banning "Anna and The King" within its
borders, Thailand is taking its objections to the film overseas, instructing its
embassies to explain to the world why it sees the movie as a distortion of
history.
</P>
<P>
	   New guidelines issued to Thai embassies by the country's Foreign Ministry
were published Saturday in the newspaper the Nation. Thai censors decided the
film denigrates a beloved 19th-century monarch, King Mongkut, by portraying him
as being under the sway of teacher Anna Leonowens, who taught English to the
king's children.
</P>
<P>
	   "The film attributes part of Thailand's success to Anna Leonowens, whom it
believes belongs to a superior race, while she was in fact an individual of
doubtful origin and could have even been half-Indian," said the guidelines.
</P>
<P>
	   The ministry, like the censors, found the film offensive and said it wrongly
portraying the king of Siam -- as Thailand was then known -- as barbaric,
senseless and irrational.
</P>
<P>
	   The measures highlight deep feelings in Thailand against the film, which was
made by 20th Century Fox and stars Oscar-winner Jodie Foster and action hero
Chow Yun-fat.
</P>
<P>
	   Fox has decided not to appeal the censor board's ruling against the film
last month, saying there is no chance it could be reversed.
</P>
<P>
	   Police, meanwhile, arrested a third person for allegedly trafficking in
pirated video compact-disc copies of the film. Panlop Yusabai, 24, was taken
into custody Friday, the Bangkok Post newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   Charges of counterfeiting the movie carry a two-year prison term, but police
also have threatened to file charges punishable by up to 15 years in prison for
any act that lowers the standing of the monarchy.
</P>
<P>
	   The law forbidding insults to the king is seldom applied. King Bhumibol
Adulyadej, the world's longest-reigning living monarch, is said to have made it
known that he does not want anyone prosecuted under the law this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-08-00 0610 </TRAILER>
