<HEADLINE> Zambia Denies Massing Border Troops  </HEADLINE>
   By MILDRED MULENGA Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LUSAKA, Zambia (AP) -- Zambia's government on Saturday denied reports that
it was deploying troops on the Angolan border to resist a possible cross-border
strike by Angolan government forces against Angolan rebels.
</P>
<P>
	   The report in South African media is ``totally false, baseless and
malicious,'' Zambian Information Minister Newstead Zimba said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The government's position of neutrality in any conflict in the region,
including that in Angola, is well known and cannot be over emphasized,'' Zimba
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Angolan government troops recently launched an offensive against UNITA
rebels along the country's southern border with Namibia. The Angolan troops,
with Namibia's permission, crossed into Namibian soil last month to crush
pockets of UNITA resistance. The troops were moving eastward along the
Angolan-Namibian border toward the Zambian border.
</P>
<P>
	   The Angolan government has previously accused Zambia of allowing war
materiel to pass over its porous border to UNITA, but amid Zambia's denials has
patched up relations with the neighboring country.
</P>
<P>
	   The Zambian information minister said his country ``has never supported
UNITA and has no intention whatsoever of doing so now or in the future as long
as that movement does not respect international norms of conduct.''
</P>
<P>
	   The United Nations has imposed sanctions on UNITA for its violations of the
U.N.-brokered peace pact that unraveled in late 1998 when full-scale war
resumed. Zambian President Frederick Chiluba has accused the rebels of breaching
the peace pact and restarting Angola's 25 year civil war.
</P>
<P>
	   Zimba said renewed fighting in Angola has damaged Zambia's security,
stability and economic development.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-08-00 1004 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
