<DOCNO> APW20000108.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 10:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Family Planning Funds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton said today he will ask Congress for tens
of millions more in funding for contraception and other family planning services
at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
	   In his weekly radio address, Clinton said his 2001 budget proposal will
include $35 million more to underwrite such services in the United States -- a
15 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
	   The money does not go to fund abortions, the White House said. Instead, the
money is intended to help prevent unwanted pregnancies among poor women,
teen-agers and others with reduced access to health care.
</P>
<P>
	   ``By making sure women have family planning choices, we are helping to make
abortion more rare,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
	   The proposed increase is the largest in more than two decades, and brings
the total administration proposal for family planning in the United States to
$274 million for next year, the White House said.
</P>
<P>
	   The money would be shared among 4,600 clinics nationwide, and pay for what
the White House called ``the full range of reproductive health services,''
including contraceptives and health screenings.
</P>
<P>
	   ``These services make a critical difference in people's lives,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
	   The funds will help prevent more than one million unintended pregnancies
each year, a White House statement said.
</P>
<P>
	   The president also is seeking $169 million in new money for family planning
and counseling services overseas -- a 45 percent increase over the fiscal 2000
budget.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I am asking Congress to support these funds, and to provide them without
restrictions that hamper the work of family planning organizations, and even bar
them from discussing or debating reproductive health policies,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
	   As part of a deal to get Congress to release $926 million in back payments
to the United Nations last year, the administration reluctantly accepted
restrictions on $385 million in federal funds for groups that perform abortions,
or lobby for liberalized abortion laws internationally.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton said then he would try to remove the restrictions, which barred U.S.
money to private family planning groups that perform or promote abortions even
with their own money.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-08-00 1006 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000108.0115 </DOCNO>
