<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 10:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Putin May Have E.German Stasi Honor  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- Acting Russian President Vladimir Putin earned a decoration
for service from East Germany's Stasi secret police during the time he worked
there as a KGB agent, according to reports Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   Der Spiegel and Focus newsmagazines reported that Putin earned the bronze
order in 1988 from former Stasi head Erich Mielke. Spiegel said the honor wasn't
anything particularly outstanding, but showed he was a typical rank-and-file
member of the intelligence service.
</P>
<P>
	   Between 1975 and 1990, Putin worked as a KGB officer in East Germany. In
Dresden, where he was working with the rank of major when he earned the medal,
he recruited businessmen from West Germany and East German citizens to work as
informers for Moscow, Spiegel reported.
</P>
<P>
	   Putin, who became acting president after Boris Yeltsin's surprise
resignation Dec. 31, is the front-runner in Russian elections set for March 26.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
