<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 11:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Congressman Sees Tax Relief  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Americans can look forward to a year of tax relief if
Republicans have their way, beginning with an end to the ``marriage penalty,''
Rep. J.C. Watts Jr., chairman of the House Republican Conference, said today.
</P>
<P>
	   ``As the sun rises on a new century, we are ready to take the next steps,''
Watts, R-Okla., said in the weekly Republican radio address. ``We will make the
tax code equally fair to one-income and two-income families.''
</P>
<P>
	   The marriage penalty is the additional tax many two-income married couples
must pay above what they would owe if they were single. Watt said passing
marriage penalty relief by April was only the first of three tax-relief bills
planned for 2000.
</P>
<P>
	   Congressional Republicans also want to allow parents to put up to $2,000
annually for each child into tax-free education savings accounts, Watts said.
The third bill would offer tax incentives to struggling rural and urban
communities.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It will create jobs, encourage savings and help poor neighborhoods become
prosperous,'' Watts said.
</P>
<P>
	   Noting this week as the fifth anniversary of the Republican takeover of
Congress, Watts said the GOP's accomplishments would continue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-08-00 1106 </TRAILER>
