<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tribe Kids Seek Thai Citizenship  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- About 100 colorfully costumed children from
Thailand's northern hill tribes petitioned Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai to grant
them Thai citizenship as part of national Children's Day.
</P>
<P>
	   Their demand underscored the ambiguous legal status of hundreds of thousands
of ethnic hill-tribe people, some of Thailand's poorest, who populate border
regions.
</P>
<P>
	   They may have lived in Thailand for generations but are not recognized as
citizens, often because they are not proficient in the Thai language or because
they live outside normal administrative channels.
</P>
<P>
	   The children who petitioned Chuan on Saturday, members of the Akha tribe,
sang songs in their native language for the premier, who opened his office to
the public as part of Children's Day.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is not the first time I have received such request,'' Chuan told
reporters after the meeting. ``I will instruct concerned agencies to do their
best.''
</P>
<P>
	   One of the children told Chuan that she had been born in Thailand but was
not considered a citizen, denying her opportunity for education and, in future
years, employment.
</P>
<P>
	   Hill-tribe people without citizenship need permission from local government
authorities to leave the district where they reside, cannot own land and cannot
send their children to high school.
</P>
<P>
	   The hill tribes generally live off subsistence agriculture and handouts from
backpacking tourists. Many hill-tribe girls end up in the flesh trade in
Bangkok, where they are often infected with the AIDS virus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-08-00 1144 </TRAILER>
