<DOCNO> APW20000108.0126 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 12:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hurricane Carter: Still fighting - in film, books, life  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   TORONTO (AP) - Rubin "Hurricane" Carter deals with life like he boxed in
the 1960s: fists up, coming at you, "no dancing, no shuffling, no jiving."
<P>
	   That stormy style inspired the nickname synonymous with the man. And his
swarming, straight-ahead approach has been the lone constant in six decades of
contrasts so striking that his survival seems remarkable, his triumph
impossible.
</P>
<P>
	   A juvenile delinquent turned prizefighter who beat a world champion, Carter
was wrongfully convicted of three murders in 1966 and spent 19 years in prison.
Drawing on a burning intensity fueled by anger, he overcame personal demons and
a corrupt and racist criminal justice system to clear his name and regain his
freedom in 1985.
</P>
<P>
	   Bob Dylan wrote a ballad about "The Hurricane," and Muhammad Ali championed
his cause. And now Norman Jewison ("In the Heat of the Night," "Moonstruck,"
"The Thomas Crown Affair") has told Carter's shattering story in a new movie,
"The Hurricane," starring Denzel Washington as the boxer.
</P>
<P>
	   At the same time, a new biography has hit bookstores and a 1991 account of
his two-decade legal odyssey has been republished to coincide with the film's
release.
</P>
<P>
	   The telephone at the Victorian house in Toronto where Carter lives and runs
his Association in Defense of the Wrongly Convicted rang constantly during a
recent interview, and with each call, Carter talks loudly into the receiver
about a hectic schedule of interviews, film screenings and an upcoming
appearance at the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
	   No one is more surprised about all the hoopla than the still muscular
62-year-old.
</P>
<P>
	   "I am absolutely flabbergasted that my life has been so full, you know, of
all sorts of things," Carter says in his deliberate, strongly inflected style.
"And yet this is not the ending. This is just the beginning. ... Man, my life is
miraculous. My life is wonderful. I am healthy. I am awake. What more could one
want? I am perfect."
</P>
<P>
	   Those who know him say such language reflects Carter's intensity more so
than any total fulfillment.
</P>
<P>
	   "'The Hurricane' to us is energy and power," says Sam Chaiton, co-author of
"Lazerus and The Hurricane," the 1991 account of how Chaiton and his housemates
took up Carter's cause and helped him overturn his murder rap in a U.S. federal
court in 1985. "He's able to give back to society after having so much taken
from him."
</P>
<P>
	   What exactly did "Hurricane" Carter lose? The chorus of Dylan's song ends
with the line: "One time he could've been the champion of the world." And the
movie shows him stopping then welterweight champion Emile Griffith in the first
round of a non-title bout three years before his 1966 arrest with John Artis for
the triple murder of three whites in a Paterson, N.J., bar.
</P>
<P>
	   He is asked if he ever saw Griffith's later legendary bouts with Nino
Benvenuti, and Carter's normally robust voice shrinks to a whisper.
</P>
<P>
	   "No, I was in prison," he says. "That's gone. Two decades just gone."
</P>
<P>
	   Sitting at his cluttered desk, wearing a blue University of San Diego law
school sweatshirt, dark pants and knee-high dark buckskin boots with a tassled
fringe, Carter constantly leans forward and gestures with his large boxer's
hands while recounting his prison struggles.
</P>
<P>
	   In the film, Washington, portraying Carter, refuses to wear prison clothes
or eat prison food in a protest of his unjust conviction. While stripped of any
ambiguity - the film justifies Carter's stabbing of a white pedophile that
landed him in a juvenile reformatory - it depicts the boxer's personal
transformation during lengthy sessions in solitary confinement.
</P>
<P>
	   Sounding like a middleweight Nelson Mandela, Carter described the thought
process at the time: "Go beyond yourself in these arduous conditions. Don't give
in to your captors. Realize this is an opportunity, instead of a tragedy. It's
an opportunity because now you don't have ... all the trappings of civility. You
have time, you have space on your hands. Use it."
</P>
<P>
	   In his affinity for overstating and understating in the same thought, Carter
attributed his strength and sustenance in prison to "anger, true and utter,
unmitigated anger, anger that the system, that the government, is going to
impose guilt on me when the government knew I was not guilty."
</P>
<P>
	   The current release of James Hirsch's authorized biography, "Hurricane - The
Miraculous Journey of Rubin Carter," has sparked another kind of anger. While
the film is based on Carter's jail house book "The 16th Round" and "Lazerus and
The Hurricane," Carter is promoting the Hirsch book while ignoring the
re-release of Chaiton's account written with Terry Swinton.
</P>
<P>
	   Chaiton and Swinton were two of the 13 Canadians who learned of Carter's
case through Lezra Martin, a Brooklyn, N.Y., youth they helped educate. The
first book Martin ever read in his life was "The 16th Round," and he started a
correspondence with the imprisoned Carter that led to his benefactors'
involvement.
</P>
<P>
	   In the film, the Canadians are depicted as three composite characters -
Chaiton, Swinton and Lisa Peters, who later married Carter when he got out of
prison and moved into the group house in Toronto where the Canadians lived.
Carter and Peters now are separated, and he lives with someone else.
</P>
<P>
	   Hirsch's book describes the group house as a different kind of prison for
Carter, who says in the book he felt like a "trophy horse" there but wanted to
pay back the Canadians for the money they spent on his case.
</P>
<P>
	   Chaiton and Swinton called the description of life in the group house
untrue. They said - and Carter agreed - that he would have faced problems
adapting no matter where he lived after prison.
</P>
<P>
	   "If you stay in those conditions for 20 long years, fighting the prison
system tooth and nail every single day, you're going to need a lot of
readjustment when you walk away from there," Carter said. "You're never
completely readjusted. Those things are always there. They're dormant, but
they're there, and if you forget about them, they'll become active."
</P>
<P>
	   Leon Friedman, a Hofstra University law professor who worked on Carter's
case, said he thinks "The Hurricane" has softened a bit but still has a
prizefighter's mentality.
</P>
<P>
	   "He had one focus then - getting out of jail. Now I think he's a little more
mellow," Friedman said. "The intensity is still there. He's still fighting."
</P>
<P>
	   Through his Association in Defense of the Wrongly Convicted, Carter has
helped a handful of people correct legal wrongs. He put up $34,000 in proceeds
from the film for the case of 28-year-old Christopher Bates, who has spent six
years in prison on a murder charge he claims is bogus.
</P>
<P>
	   On Dec. 29, Bates refused to plead guilty to a reduced charge of
manslaughter that would have set him free. He said Carter advised him to fight
the charge instead of accepting guilt in exchange for his release.
</P>
<P>
	   "His nickname, 'The Hurricane,' just suits this guy perfectly," Bates told
The Toronto Star. "He said, 'Don't worry. We're going to take care of this thing
right.' "
</P>
<P>
	   End Adv for Weekend Editions
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
