<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 12:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hundreds of bills passed by Senate, Assembly die on backburner  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Shall builders be required to pay an "impact fee"
to offset the added costs for new classrooms and police officers when the new
residents flood into those new homes?
<P>
	   Perhaps, but the Legislature won't force them to do it in this session.
</P>
<P>
	   Is it fair that lawyers who defend accused killers are allowed to dismiss
more potential jurors than prosecutors are allowed to?
</P>
<P>
	   Perhaps not, but the Legislature is not going to change these rules anytime
soon.
</P>
<P>
	   Shall troopers and their supervisors be held publicly accountable when
citizens are mistreated and file formal complaints about it?
</P>
<P>
	   Not by any new state law they won't be.
</P>
<P>
	   And is it finally time to revise fair housing laws so rural towns are not
required to provide a quota of affordable units that has no relation to their
sparse populations?
</P>
<P>
	   If so, it will not be done by legislation now.
</P>
<P>
	   All four initiatives were crafted into bills that passed either the Senate
or Assembly last year but which have not been posted for action Monday in the
final session of the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
	   These four and 332 other bills and resolutions will die as the 208th
legislative session draws to an official close Tuesday at noon.
</P>
<P>
	   There are thousands of bills and hundreds of resolutions filed in the past
two years that will expire into so much recycled paper.
</P>
<P>
	   But 336 of these bills and resolutions had gone through the committee
systems and won approval in either the Senate or Assembly.
</P>
<P>
	   Most of the thousands of bills and resolutions never moved off of the
backburner. Most are minor but some are not.
</P>
<P>
	   By design, action on the multi-billion-dollar school construction and
transportation bills will spill into the new term starting this week.
</P>
<P>
	   Less by design will come the death of a bill to require health insurers to
pay into a reserve that would have been used to pay off $120 million owed to
doctors and hospitals by the bankrupt HIP Health Plan.
</P>
<P>
	   Gun control legislation exists at both extremes, with one bill proposing to
ban all handguns and another bill proposing to let law-abiding citizens carry
concealed weapons wherever they go. Both bills go up in smoke Tuesday at noon -
and are prefiled for reintroduction as new bills on Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
	   No less than 174 bills that passed the Senate are foundering on the Assembly
backburner. Likewise, 162 bills that passed the Assembly remain bottled up in
Senate committees.
</P>
<P>
	   The Senate passed the impact-fee bill in November and the State Police
report bill last May. The Assembly has not acted on them and is not scheduled to
do so Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   The Assembly in June passed the jury selection bill and fair housing
amendment. The Senate has not acted on them and is not scheduled to do so
Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   The Republican leaders of the two houses, Senate President Donald
DiFrancesco and Assembly Speaker Jack Collins, are sensitive to these points.
They have released lengthy session agendas for their respective houses on
Monday, with the Assembly taking up 43 bills that have already passed the Senate
and the Senate handling 25 bills that have already passed the Assembly.
</P>
<P>
	   Following are other prominent bills scheduled to suffer an anonymous death
this week:
</P>
<P>
	   - A bill eventually requiring handguns to be sold with "smart gun" safety
sensors. The Senate passed it in July.
</P>
<P>
	   - A bill to permit off-track betting on horse racing. The Senate passed it
in July.
</P>
<P>
	   - A bill to require insurance coverage for all costs related to Pap smear
tests. The Assembly passed it in June.
</P>
<P>
	   - A bill to increase the penalty to $250 for parents who allow their
children to miss school. The Senate passed it in March 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   - A bill to allow private firms to run cafeterias in county jails. The
Senate passed it in February 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   - A bill to have convicted sex offenders sentenced more harshly as repeat
offenders if they had any such convictions as juveniles. The Assembly passed it
last February. Usually juvenile convictions do not count in adult sentencing.
</P>
<P>
	   - A bill to form a "Domestic Violence Victims Fund" with special fees
charged to those convicted of domestic violence charges. The Assembly passed it
in May.
</P>
<P>
	   - A bill to change drug law so dealers can be prosecuted according to the
number of doses, or "units," they sell rather than by simple weight, which is
misleading for drugs such as LSD or amphetamines. The Assembly passed it last
month.
</P>
<P>
	   - A bill to toughen penalties for resisting arrest or quarreling with
police. The Assembly passed it in July 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   - A bill to allow police officers who live in New Jersey and work
out-of-state to carry firearms off duty. The Senate passed it last month.
</P>
<P>
	   - A bill prohibiting casino owners from donating funds to recall election
campaigns. The Assembly passed it almost two years ago.
</P>
<P>
	   - A bill to repeal New Jersey's motorcycle helmet law. The Senate passed it
in October 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   - A bill to allow nonprofit clubs with liquor licenses to have
"casino-night" fundraisers. The Senate passed it in July 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   - A bill to move the New Jersey national primary to March. The Assembly
passed it in October 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
