<BODY>
<HEADLINE> On some shows, TV station displays ads at bottom of screen  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) - Need a break from commercials?
<P>
	   A Rochester television station is leaving no room for viewers to leave the
room during commercial breaks. Fox network affiliate WUHF-TV has begun
displaying small text ads at the bottom of the screen during some of its shows.
</P>
<P>
	   So far, the advertisements have run only in the afternoon and early evening.
Called banners, they are already popular on both the Internet and European
sports broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
	   John Galbraith, president of Twin Advertising Inc. in the suburb of
Pittsford, was looking for a novel way to advertise a high-speed Internet
service, and convinced the station to give the ads a trial run.
</P>
<P>
	   WUHF is the first in the country to do so, the Rochester Democrat and
Chronicle reported Saturday, quoting unidentified industry insiders.
</P>
<P>
	   "People may hate it, but you've got to try it," Galbraith said. "No one else
is trying it."
</P>
<P>
	   Allen Banks, chairman of the media policy committee at the American
Association of Advertising Agencies, called the idea intriguing but risky.
</P>
<P>
	   "As a viewer, I think it's disruptive," he said. "It's a misguided attempt
to get more revenues."
</P>
<P>
	   WUHF is owned by Sinclair Broadcasting, one of the country's largest
broadcast groups, with 59 television stations.
</P>
<P>
	   Rochester is not being used as a test market for banner ads on other
Sinclair stations, said Matt Kreiner, vice president and general manager at
WUHF.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
