<DOCNO> APW20000108.0132 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 12:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Metro-North trains to be equipped with black boxes  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) - Metro-North commuter trains are now equipped with
devices similar to the flight data recorders currently used on airliners.
<P>
	   The event recorders register a number of functions on the train, including
speed, brake pressure and signals. Metro-North's equipment also will measure
other data, including heating and cooling functions, distribution of electricity
to train cars and performance of car doors.
</P>
<P>
	   "We've used some kind of black box device since 1990, but we just finished
installation of the federally mandated equipment," said Marjorie Anders, a
Metro-North spokeswoman. "We were using it for troubleshooting and will continue
to use it as a maintenance tool in addition."
</P>
<P>
	   The railroad spent $13 million over several years to install the equipment,
Anders said Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   The devices are required under 1985 federal legislation. The program was
administered by the federal Department of Transportation's Federal Railway
Administration division. Every train contains at least one device, she said.
</P>
<P>
	   Additional technology that will send instant radio communication about
equipment failures to Metro-North fleet managers will be installed throughout
the year, Anders added.
</P>
<P>
	   "If there's an obvious problem on one of your trains, we can spot those
types of things, but this equipment will allow us to learn about less obvious
equipment malfunction that you may not be able to spot instantly," she said.
</P>
<P>
	   James Cameron, vice chairman of the Connecticut Metro North-Shoreline East
Rail Commuter Council, said he and the council were unaware of the black box
project.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm pleased to see that Metro-North is using technology to enhance
passenger safety," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
