<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 12:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Whitman to stress high tech economy, the elderly in State of State  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Gov. Christie Whitman is nearing the end of her
gubernatorial career, but there are still some things she wants to accomplish.
<P>
	   On Tuesday, during her annual State of the State message to lawmakers,
she'll unveil a number of new policy initiatives for the second to last of her
eight years in office, according to her spokesman, Peter McDonough.
</P>
<P>
	   "There's a growing sentiment that, in the second half of her second term,
it's time to rest on laurels, time to buff the image. We're not looking at it
that way," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is not going to be a recitation of where we've been. There are two
more States of the State to do that," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Whitman will focus on four themes in her speech: education, the environment,
the elderly and the economy. McDonough described the goals the governor wants to
accomplish, but declined to detail the means until the governor actually
delivers her speech.
</P>
<P>
	   Whitman wants to enhance New Jersey's reputation as a technology hub by
providing more qualified entry level workers, improving delivery of high tech
products to the marketplace, and taking advantage of computer technology in
cities, McDonough said.
</P>
<P>
	   "High technology is the engine of our economic development and the insulator
from future economic downturns," he said. "It will be for the 21st century what
manufacturing was for the early- and mid-20th century."
</P>
<P>
	   Whitman will also detail a plan to encourage parental involvement in
schools, McDonough said.
</P>
<P>
	   "One thing that has become absolutely apparent is that the level of parental
involvement in schools is directly proportional to the quality of the school,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The governor also wants to improve the quality of New Jersey's teachers and
bolster state initiatives that improve school facilities and build on
curriculum, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   For the elderly, Whitman will unveil ideas to encourage independent living,
good nutrition and personal security, McDonough said.
</P>
<P>
	   The governor will propose new brownfield redevelopment ideas in urban cores
and emphasize the importance of watershed management and air quality monitoring.
</P>
<P>
	   She will also "offer up a smart growth proposal that has some substantial
teeth in it, that is a significant exercise in planning," her spokesman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
