<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 12:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia's Putin Looks Like a Winner  </HEADLINE>
   By BARRY RENFREW Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MOSCOW (AP) -- Vladimir Putin appears headed for easy victory in Russia's
presidential election, even though he says he'll be too busy as acting president
to campaign and has barely mentioned his platform.
</P>
<P>
	   Even some of the opposition candidates say Putin is unbeatable and they are
just running for appearances' sake in an 11-week campaign that is looking more
like a formality than a test of candidates and ideas.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I imagine that Putin will not have any particular election campaign,''
said Igor Shabdurasulov, deputy chief of the acting president's staff.
</P>
<P>
	   The presidential contest set for March 26 looks to be very different from
recent Russian elections, when candidates savaged each other and tried every
trick and gimmick their strategists could come up with.
</P>
<P>
	   Boris Yeltsin won re-election as president in 1996 only after a frenzied
campaign that included the ailing incumbent stiffly strutting in front of rock
bands to appeal to young voters. Recent elections have been dubbed wars of
``kompromat,'' or compromising materials, because candidates focused on leaking
claims of immorality and criminality against opponents.
</P>
<P>
	   Unlike most Russian politicians, Putin is not tainted by corruption
allegations. His unsmiling, stern manner exudes rectitude, appealing to voters
desperate for a strong leader to tackle Russia's problems after years of
stagnation under Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
	   Some politicians who were top presidential prospects just a few months ago,
such as former premier Yevgeny Primakov and Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov, are now
considering whether to run at all.
</P>
<P>
	   The three other men who have declared their candidacies stand no chance of
winning, analysts say. They expect Communist Party leader Gennady Zyuganov, who
lost to Yeltsin in 1996, to get 25 percent of the vote, and predict liberal
Grigory Yavlinsky and extreme nationalist Vladimir Zhirinovsky will get about 5
percent each.
</P>
<P>
	   ``If everything stays the same, Vladimir Putin will win,'' Yavlinsky
conceded when he announced his own candidacy Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Aside from his strong popularity, Putin has an enormous advantage as the de
facto incumbent. He will get the full support of state-run television networks,
which already portray him daily as a dashing, competent leader and which likely
will be ready to attack any candidate who even looks like he could challenge
Putin.
</P>
<P>
	   Caught by surprise by Yeltsin's Dec. 31 resignation, rival candidates have
very little money and even less time to assemble campaigns. Regional governors
and big businesses will be wary of financing them because a Putin victory seems
inevitable -- and they'll want to stay on his good side and avoid making an
enemy of the federal government.
</P>
<P>
	   Although the popularity of politicians can evaporate overnight in Russia and
things could go wrong for Putin, most analysts say the only real question is
whether he can win more than 50 percent of the votes and avoid a runoff with the
No. 2 vote-getter.
</P>
<P>
	   Some politicians worry a barely contested election may not be the best thing
for the country's fragile democracy. They say candidates and issues should get a
rigorous testing.
</P>
<P>
	   ``If there are no other contenders, that means we have no democracy,'' said
Vasily Starodubtsev, governor of Tula Province.
</P>
<P>
	   The election will be viewed as a test of how serious Putin is about his
commitment to continue democratic reforms and safeguard individual rights.
</P>
<P>
	   Putin said he wants a clean election and criticized the Dec. 19
parliamentary elections, in which state TV mercilessly vilified some opposition
leaders. But Putin, who was prime minister, did not voice objections at the
time, and he was one of the main beneficiaries when parties allied to him did
well.
</P>
<P>
	   Russians applaud Putin's calls to revive the country as a global power and
support his tough handling of the war in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
	   Some Western analysts are wary of Putin, saying they detect an authoritarian
streak in the ex-KGB officer. Others say it is too early to tell, arguing his
intentions will become apparent only when he forms a government.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I think we need to wait and see who's reappointed to the Cabinet and see
what figures emerge before we can really understand what policy directions he's
likely to take,'' said Rani Kronick, an analyst at Control Risks Group Ltd.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-08-00 1237 </TRAILER>
