<HEADLINE> N.Y. TV Station Running Banner Ads  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) -- A local TV station doesn't have to take a break to
show its commercials.
</P>
<P>
	   WUHF-TV began displaying small text ads across the bottom of the screen
during some of its programs last week.
</P>
<P>
	   The Fox network affiliate is the first station to tuck banner ads into
television shows between the commercial breaks, the Rochester Democrat and
Chronicle reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   The station was persuaded to give the ads a trial run by John Galbraith,
president of Twin Advertising Inc., who was looking for a novel way to advertise
a high-speed Internet service.
</P>
<P>
	   "People may hate it, but you've got to try it," Galbraith said. "No one else
is trying it."
</P>
<P>
	   But one advertising expert doesn't like the idea.
</P>
<P>
	   "As a viewer, I think it's disruptive," said Allen Banks, chairman of the
media policy committee at the American Association of Advertising Agencies.
</P>
<P>
	   WUHF is owned by Sinclair Broadcasting, one of the country's largest
broadcast groups with 59 television stations. Rochester is not being used as a
test market for banner ads on other Sinclair stations, said Matt Kreiner, WUHF's
vice president and general manager.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
