<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 13:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Nike Shirts Are Safe  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- Nike soccer jerseys pulled from store shelves across Germany
after a television report do not contain a dangerous amount of a toxic
antibacterial chemical, according to a report Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   Der Spiegel newsmagazine quoted an unnamed expert at Germany's federal
institute for consumer protection who said tests Friday found that the jerseys
posed ``no danger to health,'' and amounts of the chemical were far below risk
levels.
</P>
<P>
	   Nike has said it would investigate whether the yellow-and-black jerseys
contain tributyltin, a heavy metal compound used in anti-barnacle paint for
ships.
</P>
<P>
	   At high levels in humans, experts say TBT is believed to cause neurological
problems, damage the immune system and harm the liver.
</P>
<P>
	   Also used to kill bacteria and quell the smell of sweat, TBT would seem an
ideal additive for sports shirts. But British and Dutch tests have shown the
substance to cause mutations in marine snails, and the World Wildlife Fund is
calling for its global ban.
</P>
<P>
	   German public television's consumer show ``Plusminus'' reported a private
lab it commissioned to test clothing items found TBT and similar compounds in
the Nike jerseys and several other products. The items were chosen at random in
German stores, according to the report, which provided no figures on the TBT
levels.
</P>
<P>
	   The soccer jerseys caused the biggest storm because the club, 1997 European
champion Borussia Dortmund, has a big national following.
</P>
<P>
	   Three German department store chains stopped selling the shirts as a
precaution, and the club whose jerseys were tested suspended their sale at its
official fan store.
</P>
<P>
	   At least three other first-division clubs that use Nike jerseys have said
they were asking the company's German headquarters to confirm their equipment
was safe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-08-00 1305 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
