<HEADLINE> Kosovo Girl Treated at US Hospital  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Doctors are hopeful that a 14-year-old Kosovar girl who lost
her legs in a land mine explosion will walk again.
</P>
<P>
	   Ibadete Thaqi, who is being treated at a New York hospital, will be fitted
with temporary prostheses on Monday and will not need further surgery, her
doctors said Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   ``She will leave walking without assistance,'' said Dr. David Helfet, head
of the Hospital for Special Surgery's orthopedic trauma service. ``She will
absolutely be walking in three to six months.''
</P>
<P>
	   Ibadete, who arrived in New York last week with her mother, lost both legs
in June after returning to Kosovo following the NATO bombing. She picked up a
bucket of water to help her mother clean the house, and a land mine hidden
inside the pail exploded, tearing both her legs off at the knees.
</P>
<P>
	   A Manhattan real-estate agent organized the financing for the trip and the
hospital is treating her for free.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I'm happy to be in America,'' she told reporters in English. Speaking
through a translator, she said she hopes to become a doctor.
</P>
</TEXT>
