<HEADLINE> Palestinians Urge Progress on Peace  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAZA CITY, Gaza Strip (AP) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat on Saturday
called on President Clinton, currently mediating Israeli-Syrian peace talks, to
push Israeli-Palestinian negotiations forward.
</P>
<P>
	   Arafat made the request after receiving holiday telephone calls from Clinton
and Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak, who were in Sheperdstown, W.Va., for the
talks with Syria.
</P>
<P>
	   During their phone conversation, Barak and Arafat agreed to meet after the
Palestinian leader returns from a meeting with Clinton in Washington on Jan. 20,
Arafat aide Nabil Abourdeneh told the Palestinian News Agency WAFA.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I ask President Clinton to exert his efforts to see the implementation of
the agreements signed,'' Arafat said during a speech in Gaza on the occasion of
the Muslim feast of Eid al-Fitr, which began Friday and marks the end of the
holy month of Ramadan.
</P>
<P>
	   Arafat renewed his vow to establish a Palestinian state with its capital in
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
	   Abourdeneh said Clinton told Arafat that he remained committed to advancing
the peace process and planned to formulate new ideas with Arafat during their
meeting.
</P>
<P>
	   The Palestinians have expressed concern that negotiations with Syria would
distract Israel and the United States from the Palestinian track.
</P>
<P>
	   Israel and the Palestinians have set a Feb. 13 deadline for completing the
broad outlines of a final peace treaty, which is to resolve issues such as
borders, the fate of Palestinian refugees and the status of Jerusalem, claimed
by each side as its capital.
</P>
</TEXT>
