<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 13:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hearts of museum organizers heavy  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ENFIELD, Conn. (AP) - Organizers of the proposed National Purple Heart
Museum are again under fire, this time for claiming they had the support of
Persian Gulf war commander Gen. H. Norman Schwarzkopf.
<P>
	   Aside from telling a stranger two years ago that "of course" he would
support a museum for Purple Heart veterans, the twice-decorated Purple Heart
recipient said Friday he has had "zero involvement" with the project.
</P>
<P>
	   "I understand the advantage of using the name. Bit that, to me, is phony,"
Schwarzkopf said.
</P>
<P>
	   Schwarzkopf denied he was ever a member of the museum's advisory board, as
directors of the National Purple Heart Museum Committee Inc. indicated in their
push for millions of dollars in private donations.
</P>
<P>
	   "As far as a formal membership, I don't like to go on boards of directors or
chairmanships if I can't make a personal commitment," Schwarzkopf said.
</P>
<P>
	   Joseph M. Donahue, the former executive director of the museum, disputed the
general's claim that he had no involvement with the charity.
</P>
<P>
	   Donahue could not be reached by The Associated Press for comment. A
telephone message was left for him at his office Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   Connecticut Attorney General Richard Blumenthal filed a critical report this
week, claiming the museum's board of directors had spent $620,000 - $500,000 in
state money and $120,000 in private donations - with only a set of architectural
plans worth about $33,000 to show for it.
</P>
<P>
	   Blumenthal also said bookkeeping records for the National Purple Heart
Museum Committee Inc. are so incomplete that it is nearly impossible to track
how and when money was spent.
</P>
<P>
	   "They're way out of line here," Charles Alfano, the museum's current
executive director said of Blumenthal's report. "In total, maybe under $20,000
is in question - not hundreds of thousands."
</P>
<P>
	   The committee was formed in 1986 to build a museum dedicated to recipients
of the Purple Heart service award. It received $250,000 in state grant money for
planning and design costs in 1992, and $1 million in 1998 - half of which was
supposed to be matched with private donations.
</P>
<P>
	   The organization also has failed to collect the $18.75 million of private
donations it promised to raise in its 1997 state grant application, Blumenthal
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Donahue left his post as executive director in April, and now works for a
branch of the Vietnam Veterans of America Foundation in Washington.
</P>
<P>
	   According to Blumenthal's investigation, Donahue took a $6,000 private
donation for the museum, kept $500 and funneled the rest to his wife's bank
account in Texas.
</P>
<P>
	   Alfano was appointed to his unpaid position in September.
</P>
<P>
	   The latest cost estimate to build the museum is nearly $19 million, but the
volunteer board of directors now has only a few thousand dollars, including a
$16,000 fund for commemorative bricks, and roughly $850,000 left of a $1 million
grant promised by the state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-08-00 1312 </TRAILER>
