<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley, Gore Vow Vigorous Debate  </HEADLINE>
   By MIKE GLOVER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   JOHNSTON, Iowa (AP) -- Bill Bradley and Al Gore, debating Saturday for the
second time in four days, promised a vigorous confrontation as the former
senator defends his ``big ideas'' campaign and the vice president his missteps
that angered blacks and military leaders.
</P>
<P>
	   The two-man battle for the Democratic presidential nomination intensified
less than three weeks before the leadoff precinct caucuses in Iowa, where Gore
leads Bradley in the polls, and less than a month before the primary in New
Hampshire where the contenders are neck-and-neck.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I think vigorous competition is good for our democracy,'' Gore said,
vowing to draw sharp distinctions with Bradley on issues such as health care,
education and farming policy, which is especially important in Iowa. ``I intend
to get it on the agenda,'' he said of farming.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley, a former professional basketball player, said he was relished sharp
exchanges and called the series of debates -- their fifth since the fall --
``exercises in discipline'' and ``kind of fun.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``People used to come off the bench and give me an elbow to get me off my
game,'' said Bradley. ``All that stuff just rolls off my back.''
</P>
<P>
	   The afternoon debate was sponsored by the Des Moines Register, and editor
Dennis Ryerson was moderating. The format called for him to pose questions to
the candidates submitted by readers, but the candidates also were given a chance
to question each other.
</P>
<P>
	   The debate, televised nationally by CNN and C-Span, was set in a suburban
public TV station before a carefully selected audience of 300. Questions were
coming from that audience as well.
</P>
<P>
	   Both candidates came into the debate on the defensive: Gore mending fences
with Gen. Colin Powell and backpedaling on a sticky question of gays in the
military, and Bill Bradley buying $250,000 worth of TV ad time to justify the
premise of his ``big ideas'' campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore criticized Bradley agenda, which he said is top-heavy with a massive
health care plan, to Ronald Reagan's for its focus on only ``one or two
things.'' The Bradley campaign responded by putting up a new television ad that
would pelt New Hampshire voters five or six times on Manchester TV and another
five or six times from nearby Boston stations.
</P>
<P>
	   ``People accuse me of offering big ideas that they say are risky,'' Bradley
says in the ad. ``I say the real risk is not doing the things I've set out to do
in this campaign.''
</P>
<P>
	   It marked the first time that Bradley, in his active ad campaign, used a
spot to respond to Gore.
</P>
<P>
	   Over in the Gore camp, the vice president spent Friday evening in
damage-control mode, trying to clear up an embarrassment caused by his campaign
manager, and retracting comments he made in a Wednesday debate that he would set
a ``litmus test,'' requiring candidates for the Joint Chiefs of Staff to agree
with his intention to let gays serve openly in the military.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I did not mean to imply that there should ever be any kind of inquiry into
the personal political opinions of officers in the U.S. military,'' Gore said in
a hastily called news conference in Iowa after his comments sparked criticism
from former members of the joint chiefs.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley, when asked if he would make agreement on gays in the military a
litmus test for appointments to the joint chiefs, told the debate moderator it
was unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
	   On another sticky matter, Gore stood by his campaign manager Donna Brazile
for saying in a recent interview that Republicans used blacks like General Colin
Powell, former chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to pose for pictures, but
did not really care about them.
</P>
<P>
	   Powell responded with an angry letter to the Gore campaign that he
distributed to reporters.
</P>
<P>
	   Brazile and Gore separately telephoned Powell. Gore refused to say whether
either of them apologized outright.
</P>
<P>
	   While some worry that the competitive Democratic fight will damage the
party's chances to hold the White House in November, both Gore and Bradley have
dismissed those worries.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I think that people in New Hampshire and Iowa are beginning to pay
attention,'' said Bradley. ``I don't think there's national attention. That
starts after Iowa and New Hampshire.''
</P>
<P>
	   Gore said, ``A fair debate on the issues is healthy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-08-00 1319 </TRAILER>
