<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NRC reaffirms sanctions against managers at nuclear plant  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   WATERFORD, Conn. (AP) - Federal regulators have reaffirmed the decision
to sanction four Millstone nuclear power plant executives for harassment of
workers who raised questions about plant safety.
<P>
	   The Nuclear Regulatory Agency's report released Friday concluded that the
executives discriminated against the employees.
</P>
<P>
	   The NRC also released to The Day newspaper summaries of the investigations
it conducted into allegations of discrimination and harassment at Millstone.
</P>
<P>
	   The newspaper first requested the records under the federal Freedom of
Information Act in August 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   The documents outline examples of worker harassment and raise questions
about whether documents were destroyed as part of a cover-up.
</P>
<P>
	   Three of the four men sanctioned Friday remain with Northeast Utilities. Two
of them still hold management positions at Millstone.
</P>
<P>
	   Eric DeBarba, a former vice president at Millstone, received the severest
penalty, a "Level 2" violation. He was not fined.
</P>
<P>
	   The NRC cited him for his role in 1993 in demoting two supervisors who had
sought to address safety problems at the Millstone nuclear plants. DeBarba was
fired in 1996.
</P>
<P>
	   Last June, DeBarba returned to the company, hired as an account manager in
the company's Select Energy Division.
</P>
<P>
	   The other three sanctioned individuals received written reprimands. Among
them is Hollis Risley, who worked directly under DeBarba and was also cited for
his role in the unfair demotion of two supervisors in 1993. Risley is no longer
with NU. He works as a consultant to nuclear utilities.
</P>
<P>
	   Also receiving written reprimands were Raymond P. Necci, currently vice
president of engineering services, and Steven A. Sudigala, a manager at
Millstone.
</P>
<P>
	   They were charged with an act of retaliation for the decision to fire an
employee who had raised safety concerns about problems with the system that
detects pipe breaks that, if left unchecked, could lead to a nuclear accident.
</P>
<P>
	   Originally, the NRC Enforcement Office concluded there was not sufficient
evidence of discrimination, a decision that was met by protest from elected
leaders and the public.
</P>
<P>
	   A special review committee concluded that the evidence could support a
finding of discrimination, which in turn led to the NRC's decision to hand down
the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
	   Joe Pillittere, a spokesman for NU, said that despite the sanctions, both
Necci and Sudigala have the support and backing of Chief Nuclear Officer Leon J.
Olivier.
</P>
<P>
	   "Based on their recent performance in effectively handling employee issues
and other matters and on reviews of their performance, we believe that they are
now and will continue to be first-rate members of the Millstone team,"
Pillittere said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
