<HEADLINE> Doctors: Kosovar girl will walk again  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - Doctors are hopeful that a 14-year-old Kosovar girl who
lost her legs to a land mine will be able to walk again.
<P>
	   Ibadete Thaqi, who is being treated at a New York hospital, will be fitted
with temporary prostheses on Monday and will not need further surgery, her
doctors said Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   "She will leave walking without assistance," said Dr. David Helfet, head of
the Hospital for Special Surgery's orthopedic trauma service. "She will
absolutely be walking in three to six months."
</P>
<P>
	   Ibadete, who arrived in New York on Thursday with her mother, lost both legs
in June, after returning to Kosovo following the NATO bombing. She picked up a
bucket of water to help her mother clean the house, but a land mine was hidden
inside the pail, and it tore both her legs off at the knees.
</P>
<P>
	   Well-wishers are helping to pay her expenses in New York, and the hospital
is treating her for free.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm happy to be in America," she told reporters in English. Speaking
through a translator, she then said she hopes to become a doctor.
</P>
<P>
	   Ibadete's new physical therapist says if she works hard, she'll make a good
recovery.
</P>
<P>
	   "She is young and obviously fit and keen to get going," said therapist Paddy
Rossbach.
</P>
</TEXT>
