<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCain Defends Regulators' Letters  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sen. John McCain said Saturday he only was trying to
protect consumers and prod regulators to act when he wrote letters on behalf of
large donors and other companies in his capacity as Commerce Committee chairman.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I have acted on one fundamental principal and that is to try to protect
the consumer,'' the GOP presidential contender said while campaigning in South
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain, R-Ariz., said most of the 500 letters he has written to regulators
urged them to act on matters concerning telecommunications and airlines that
were languishing.
</P>
<P>
	   ``An overwhelming majority of these communications are, 'please act, please
act,''' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
	   The senator wrote federal regulators on behalf of more than a dozen
contributors over the past three years, according to hundreds of documents being
made public Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   The memos show McCain intervened just as forcefully on behalf of companies
that did not give to his campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   For example, in a July 1999 letter to Federal Communications Commission
Chairman William Kennard, McCain complained about the delay in transferring a
broadcast license for a Texas radio station.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain, an outspoken supporter of campaign finance reform, complained he was
being held to a different standard compared with other members of Congress, most
of whom write federal agencies on behalf of constituents and donors.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Take a look at what other congressmen and senators do,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain said that in keeping most of his letters focused getting regulators
to act on matter of public interest, he was adhering to a higher standard than
others.
</P>
<P>
	   ``What is the standard and am I acting in higher standard? I think so,'' he
said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain weighed in on behalf of BellSouth, trying to offer long-distance
service; Ameritech, trying to merge with SBC Communications; America West
airlines, trying to offer airline service out of Flagstaff Airport; and other
corporate givers.
</P>
<P>
	   In one such letter, McCain urged the Federal Communications Commission in
the fall of 1998 to give ``serious consideration'' to BellSouth's request to
offer long-distance service. BellSouth employees are the third-largest
contributor to his presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   Two weeks after Ameritech's chairman held a fund-raiser for him last spring,
McCain sent a stinging letter to federal regulators accusing them of being
unfair toward the phone company's proposed merger with another Bell company.
</P>
<P>
	   The letter accused the commission of ``applying a different, and much
stricter, burden of proof in this merger proceeding than the commission has
applied in evaluating other mergers.''
</P>
<P>
	   It also said, ``This letter expresses no view on the merits of any issues in
this proceeding and is not written to benefit any particular party.''
</P>
<P>
	   The documents were provided to The Associated Press by the Senate Commerce
Committee on Friday. Besides the memos written on behalf of donors, there were
hundreds of letters written in response to individuals, including more than 20
letters referred to the Transportation Department from travel agents upset about
airlines capping their commissions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
