<HEADLINE> Irish Record Shows 1969 Arms Demand  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) -- Three Northern Ireland legislators appealed to
Ireland for rifles to protect Catholics when sectarian violence erupted in the
British province three decades ago, according to government documents released
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   Legislators turned up at the foreign ministry in Dublin on the night of Aug.
30, 1969, to ask for smuggled arms, saying ``a few hundred rifles'' from the
Irish Army could ``easily be lost and would not be missed,'' the records showed.
</P>
<P>
	   The legislators were identified as Paddy Devlin, then of the Northern
Ireland Labor Party, Paddy Kennedy of Republican Labor, and Paddy O'Hanlon, an
independent from County Armagh. Devlin and Kennedy are both dead.
</P>
<P>
	   The three were members of a Northern Ireland assembly which was dismantled
by Britain because of the unrest. A new Northern Ireland Cabinet of Protestants
and Catholics was formed recently under the 1998 Good Friday peace accord.
</P>
<P>
	   The records, released because 30 years have elapsed, said legislators
demanded to see Ireland's then prime minister, Jack Lynch, but were seen instead
by an official of the External Affairs department, now called Foreign Affairs.
</P>
<P>
	   They told the official that the Catholic minority in Northern Ireland was
under attack, including by the since-disbanded B Specials police unit, and was
in danger of being squeezed into a Catholic ghetto in the Falls Road area of
Belfast.
</P>
<P>
	   ``He (Kennedy) said that soon the whole Catholic population in Belfast would
be concentrated in the Falls Road area and they would be massacred,'' the
documents said.
</P>
<P>
	   After the three men left close to midnight, extra police guards were mounted
at Lynch's residence, the documents said -- implying that the request was
refused.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-08-00 1409 </TRAILER>
