<HEADLINE> LA May Limit Cops in Anti-Gang Unit  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Officers working in police department's anti-gang unit
could be limited to three years on the detail under changes proposed by Chief
Bernard Parks to reform the embattled division.
</P>
<P>
	   The unit has emerged at the center of the worst Los Angeles police
corruption scandal in decades.
</P>
<P>
	   So far, four people have been released from prison, other convictions have
been thrown out and a dozen officers have been removed from active duty amid
allegations that arrests were fabricated and suspects were shot by police
officers for no reason.
</P>
<P>
	   At the center of the probe is the department's Rampart Division and its
Community Resources Against Street Hoodlums, or CRASH, unit.
</P>
<P>
	   Among the changes detailed Friday is a limit to an officer's time on the
detail to three years. The department is also considering changing the unit's
name and increasing the supervision of anti-gang officers.
</P>
<P>
	   ``They are making some realignments and some consolidation,'' said Dennis
Zine, vice president of the Los Angeles Police Protective League. ``They are not
calling for the disbandment of police involvement in the gang area.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``We're not abolishing the anti-gang program at all,'' added Sgt. John
Pasquariello, a police spokesman. ``We're making it better and a little more
accountable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
