<HEADLINE> Austria Coalition Return Possible  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria (AP) -- Three months after inconclusive national elections,
Austria's old coalition partners could form a new government next week, the head
of the conservative party told a leading weekly.
</P>
<P>
	   Wolfgang Schuessel was quoted by Format magazine as saying that his
conservative People's Party would not turn down the leading Social Democrats if
they are ``ready to do the things which are necessary.'' The conservatives have
long advocated membership in NATO, while the Social Democrats have insisted on
maintaining neutrality.
</P>
<P>
	   The interview is to be published Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   The conservatives have governed with the Social Democrats for 13 years, but
the balance was upset in Oct. 3 elections with the second-place finish of Joerg
Haider's Freedom Party, which ran on an anti-immigrant platform. The Social
Democrats finished first, but didn't have enough support to form a majority
government on their own.
</P>
<P>
	   Schuessel, whose party finished third, told Format he would not rule out
cooperation with Haider's Freedom Party if talks with the Social Democrats fail.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Toward the end of the week, we must see whether it's going to be a go,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
