<DOCNO> APW20000108.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 14:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Defends Washington Bunker Role  </HEADLINE>
   By MIKE GLOVER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   JOHNSTON, Iowa (AP) -- Debating in Iowa, Vice President Al Gore told
Democratic rival Bill Bradley on Saturday that he's not in a Washington bunker
trying to fend off the scandals of the past, he's on ``the front lines in the
battle for our future.''
</P>
<P>
	   It was an echo of their last debate, in New Hampshire, and Gore delivered
his answer in opening this round. ``I want to start by telling you what we were
doing in that Washington bunker,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   He said the administration has delivered new jobs, reformed welfare, and
strengthened the economy, and that his goals as president would produce more
progress.
</P>
<P>
	   ``That's not a bunker,'' Gore said. ``Those are the front lines in the fight
for our future.''
</P>
<P>
	   They went on to argue a familiar topic, health insurance, Bradley again
accusing the vice president of misrepresenting his position by saying it would
undermine Medicare and do away with Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I'd replace Medicaid with something better,'' Bradley said, accusing Gore
of always conveniently ignoring that.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore said he wants to come back to Iowa and debate Bradley on agricultural
policy. He rolled out his challenge to twice weekly debates with no more
television ads.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I know that you have said no, but as they say on that millionaire
television show, is that your final answer?'' he asked Bradley, who ignored it.
</P>
<P>
	   On agriculture, Bradley said family farmers have had no real help, ``no
safety net whatsoever,'' from the current administration. The former New Jersey
senator said he wants policy changes to help small farmers. ``You can talk about
the past, but I want to talk about the future,'' Bradley told Gore.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore said he could understand Bradley's reluctance to talk about the past,
saying his rival had voted against emergency aid to farmers in midwest floods,
and against subsidies for ethanol, a fuel derived from corn.
</P>
<P>
	   Both candidates talked tough on farm policies important in Iowa, demanding
that foreign markets be opened to genetically modified commodities. Europe and
Japan resist those products.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We can't let Europe and Japan determine our farm policy,'' said Gore, who
said ``sound science'' should govern.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The most important thing we can do is use our authority to petition to get
access to markets,'' said Bradley. ``The problem with agriculture in America is
serious, in Iowa it's dead serious.''
</P>
<P>
	   The latest Iowa poll showed the challenge facing Bradley; Gore led him by 21
percentage points in a survey for the Des Moines Register among Democrats who
said they intend to vote in the party caucuses two weeks from Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
