<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 15:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State Police memo reveals racial profiling took place as early as  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - New Jersey State Police officials knew troopers had
been stopping a disproportionate number of minority motorists more than two
years before the state admitted the practice of racial profiling, according to
an internal memo enclosed in court papers filed on Friday.
<P>
	   The memo, dated Oct. 4, 1996, said a routine internal affairs inspection of
the Moorestown barracks found the percentage of minorities stopped by its
troopers was "dramatically higher" than the rates that had been cited in a
landmark court case earlier that year, The Star-Ledger of Newark reported in
Saturday's editions.
</P>
<P>
	   In the case, State vs. Pedro Soto, Superior Court Judge Robert E. Francis
ruled that troopers pulled over motorists on the basis of their race between
April 1988 and May 1991 along the New Jersey Turnpike south of Interchange 7A.
</P>
<P>
	   A study introduced during the trial revealed that 35.6 percent of motorists
stopped on that particular stretch of roadway were black. South of Interchange
3, 46 percent of all motorists stopped between 1988 and 1991 were black.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition, the study concluded that only 15 percent of drivers speeding on
that roadway were black.
</P>
<P>
	   Although the memo did not specify a percentage of minority drivers that had
been stopped, it mentioned that almost five years after the time period covered
in the court case, the rate at which they had been stopped had increased.
</P>
<P>
	   The memo recommended ways to correct the problem, including changing patrol
logs to require troopers to record the race of motorists who were stopped and
incorporating that information in troopers' bi-annual evaluation reports.
</P>
<P>
	   Troopers receiving unsatisfactory ratings could be referred to the Internal
Affairs Bureau.
</P>
<P>
	   The memo, from Internal Affairs Bureau Chief Capt. Richard Touw to Maj.
Michael Fedorko, is part of a series of documents the State Police was ordered
to release to attorneys representing two defendants who are appealing drug
convictions on grounds they were illegally stopped in Hunterdon County.
</P>
<P>
	   Fedorko, who was later promoted to lieutenant colonel and retired in October
as acting superintendent, told the newspaper he did not remember the memo and
did not know if any of the recommendations were put into place.
</P>
<P>
	   When asked about the memo, Roger Shatzkin, spokesman for Attorney General
John Farmer Jr., said the State Police is now focusing on reforms rather than
past problems.
</P>
<P>
	   "We're looking to the future to make things better and make sure to the best
of our ability that this doesn't happen in the future," Shatzkin told the
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
	   The Rev. Reginald Jackson, executive director of the Black Ministers Council
of New Jersey, said Friday the memo reinforces his belief that top State Police
officials knew of the problem and denied it.
</P>
<P>
	   "With everything that's come out, no one in leadership positions other than
(former New Jersey State Police Superintendent Carl) Williams has been held
accountable," Jackson said, referring to Gov. Christie Whitman's demand for
Williams' resignation after he made statements suggesting minority groups were
responsible for drug trafficking.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-08-00 1505 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000108.0172 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 15:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Troops: Russia Understating Deaths  </HEADLINE>
   By ANNA DOLGOV Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SLEPTSOVSKAYA, Russia (AP) -- Russian soldiers said Saturday that the
military is understating casualties in Chechnya, hushing up the deaths of scores
of men to avoid a public backlash against the increasingly bloody war.
</P>
<P>
	   In a series of interviews, Russian soldiers in Chechnya and the adjoining
region of Ingushetia claimed their units had suffered numerous casualties that
have not been reported. It was not possible to obtain overall figures, but
soldiers in some units said more than half the men in their detachments had been
killed or wounded in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
	   At the Kavkaz checkpoint near Sleptsovskaya, Interior Ministry soldiers said
Saturday that they see trucks coming from Chechnya every day with dead and
wounded personnel despite official claims of very few casualties.
</P>
<P>
	   ``They would announce that two or three people have been killed, but the
actual number is two or three times higher,'' said one of the soldiers at the
checkpoint, who identified himself only by his first name, Sergei.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We can see that because all the corpses go through us.''
</P>
<P>
	   Ever since its Chechen offensive began in September, the military has
stressed that casualties have been low, hoping to avoid public opposition of the
kind provoked by heavy Russian losses in the 1994-96 Chechen war. The military's
strategy is based on heavy air and artillery bombardment of rebel positions,
followed by mopping-up operations.
</P>
<P>
	   The most recent official casualty figures, released Thursday, say 465
Defense and Interior Ministry troops have been killed and 1,583 have been
wounded in Chechnya since fighting began in September. The numbers do not
include any figures for soldiers missing in action or those whose bodies are too
badly disfigured to allow identification.
</P>
<P>
	   Independent analysts and soldiers' rights groups have disputed the numbers
for months, saying the toll is much higher. Accounts by soldiers on the ground
support the claims.
</P>
<P>
	   Of the 115 men who have been guarding a stretch of road in the Grozny
neighborhood of Chernorechye since September, only 58 are left. Some were
wounded, but most were killed, members of the unit said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The company is gone already. And they (the military) keep saying there are
no casualties,'' said Pyotr, a young conscript who refused to give his last
name. He said that another 115-strong company was stationed nearby on Dec. 11,
and that only 17 men were left when it was redeployed on Jan. 2.
</P>
<P>
	   Russian troops faced little resistance as they took control of Chechnya's
lowlands in the autumn, but they have been stalled in their two-week push to
seize Grozny and penetrate into the rebel-held southern mountains.
</P>
<P>
	   The Grozny area was mostly quiet Saturday, one day after Russian commanders
declared that the bombardment of the shattered capital would be reduced. Weather
also appeared to be a factor in the letup in air and artillery raids, with the
capital shrouded in heavy fog.
</P>
<P>
	   The military command said the pause in bombardment was announced in part to
allow thousands of civilians who have been trapped in Grozny to escape. However,
no large movements of civilians were reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   The military may be using the lull to prepare for a major new drive to take
Grozny, although Russian commanders refused to say anything about their plans.
</P>
<P>
	   There was scattered fighting outside Grozny on Saturday, with the military
claiming it had trapped a group of rebels near the town of Argun, nine miles
east of Grozny, and surrounded more rebels in the southern rebel stronghold of
Vedeno.
</P>
<P>
	   The military said 40 militants had been killed in airstrikes on rebel bases,
and that only one Russian soldier was killed in the fighting, the ITAR-Tass news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
	   More clashes were reported in Russian-controlled northern Chechnya. A rebel
band attacked Russian police forces in Gudermes on Friday, wounding one
policeman, and another clash broke out near the nearby village of Dzhalka,
police commander Boris Ostankov said.
</P>
<P>
	   The Russian government on Saturday tried to play down its decision to
replace the two top combat generals in Chechnya. Lt. Gen. Gennady Troshev and
Maj. Gen. Vladimir Shamanov were returned Friday to the posts they occupied
before the war, and their deputies took their places.
</P>
<P>
	   Removing combat commanders at the height of the military campaign in
Chechnya suggested government displeasure with their failure to take Grozny or
deal a decisive blow against the rebels.
</P>
<P>
	   But acting President Vladimir Putin, emerging from an Orthodox Christmas
mass Saturday, said the issue was a technical one.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Russia doesn't throw away such generals as Troshev and Shamanov. There has
been no replacement and no replacement has been planned. It is a technical
question,'' he said, giving no further details.
</P>
<P>
	   Putin, who built much of his political popularity on tough handling of the
war, is thought to want to wrap up the fighting before presidential elections
March 26.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-08-00 1508 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000108.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 15:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hundreds of bills passed by Senate, Assembly die on backburner  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Shall builders be required to pay an "impact fee"
to offset the added costs for new classrooms and police officers when the new
residents flood into those new homes?
<P>
	   Perhaps, but the Legislature won't force them to do it in this session.
</P>
<P>
	   Is it fair that lawyers who defend accused killers are allowed to dismiss
more potential jurors than prosecutors are allowed to?
</P>
<P>
	   Perhaps not, but the Legislature is not going to change these rules anytime
soon.
</P>
<P>
	   Shall troopers and their supervisors be held publicly accountable when
citizens are mistreated and file formal complaints about it?
</P>
<P>
	   Not by any new state law.
</P>
<P>
	   And is it finally time to revise fair housing laws so rural towns are not
required to provide a quota of affordable units that has no relation to their
sparse populations?
</P>
<P>
	   If so, it will not be done by legislation now.
</P>
<P>
	   All four initiatives were crafted into bills that passed either the Senate
or Assembly last year but have not been posted for action Monday in the final
session of the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
	   These four and 332 other bills and resolutions will die as the 208th
legislative session draws to an official close Tuesday at noon.
</P>
<P>
	   There are thousands of bills and hundreds of resolutions filed in the past
two years that will expire into so much recycled paper.
</P>
<P>
	   But 336 of these bills and resolutions had gone through the committee
systems and won approval in either the Senate or Assembly.
</P>
<P>
	   Most of the thousands of bills and resolutions never moved off of the
backburner. Most are minor but some are not.
</P>
<P>
	   By design, action on the multi-billion-dollar school construction and
transportation bills will spill into the new term starting this week.
</P>
<P>
	   Less by design will come the death of a bill to require health insurers to
pay into a reserve that would have been used to pay off $120 million owed to
doctors and hospitals by the bankrupt HIP Health Plan.
</P>
<P>
	   Gun control legislation exists at both extremes, with one bill proposing to
ban all handguns and another bill proposing to let law-abiding citizens carry
concealed weapons wherever they go. Both bills go up in smoke Tuesday at noon -
and are prefiled for reintroduction as new bills on Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
	   No less than 174 bills that passed the Senate are foundering on the Assembly
backburner. Likewise, 162 bills that passed the Assembly remain bottled up in
Senate committees.
</P>
<P>
	   The Senate passed the impact-fee bill in November and the State Police
report bill last May. The Assembly has not acted on them and is not scheduled to
do so Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   The Assembly in June passed the jury selection bill and fair housing
amendment. The Senate has not acted on them and is not scheduled to do so
Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   The Republican leaders of the two houses, Senate President Donald
DiFrancesco and Assembly Speaker Jack Collins, are sensitive to these points.
They have released lengthy session agendas for their respective houses on
Monday, with the Assembly taking up 43 bills that have already passed the Senate
and the Senate handling 25 bills that have already passed the Assembly.
</P>
<P>
	   Following are other prominent bills scheduled to suffer an anonymous death
this week:
</P>
<P>
	   - A bill eventually requiring handguns to be sold with "smart gun" safety
sensors. The Senate passed it in July.
</P>
<P>
	   - A bill to permit off-track betting on horse racing. The Senate passed it
in July.
</P>
<P>
	   - A bill to require insurance coverage for all costs related to Pap smear
tests. The Assembly passed it in June.
</P>
<P>
	   - A bill to increase the penalty to $250 for parents who allow their
children to miss school. The Senate passed it in March 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   - A bill to allow private firms to run cafeterias in county jails. The
Senate passed it in February 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   - A bill to have convicted sex offenders sentenced more harshly as repeat
offenders if they had any such convictions as juveniles. The Assembly passed it
last February. Usually juvenile convictions do not count in adult sentencing.
</P>
<P>
	   - A bill to form a "Domestic Violence Victims Fund" with special fees
charged to those convicted of domestic violence charges. The Assembly passed it
in May.
</P>
<P>
	   - A bill to change drug law so dealers can be prosecuted according to the
number of doses, or "units," they sell rather than by simple weight, which is
misleading for drugs such as LSD or amphetamines. The Assembly passed it last
month.
</P>
<P>
	   - A bill to toughen penalties for resisting arrest or quarreling with
police. The Assembly passed it in July 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   - A bill to allow police officers who live in New Jersey and work
out-of-state to carry firearms off duty. The Senate passed it last month.
</P>
<P>
	   - A bill prohibiting casino owners from donating funds to recall election
campaigns. The Assembly passed it almost two years ago.
</P>
<P>
	   - A bill to repeal New Jersey's motorcycle helmet law. The Senate passed it
in October 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   - A bill to allow nonprofit clubs with liquor licenses to have
"casino-night" fundraisers. The Senate passed it in July 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   - A bill to move the New Jersey national primary to March. The Assembly
passed it in October 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
