<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Debate Notebook  </HEADLINE>
   By KEN THOMAS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   JOHNSTON, Iowa (AP) -- Milk and cookies were available Saturday outside the
Iowa Public Television studios while Democrats Bill Bradley and Al Gore debated
inside.
</P>
<P>
	   The treat was provided by Iowans for Sensible Priorities, which handed out
cookies decorated with a pie chart of defense spending while group members
performed a skit depicting the Pentagon as a ``sacred cow.''
</P>
<P>
	   A woman in a cow suit was carried around on a platform by two men wearing
masks of Al Gore and Bill Bradley, while she was sprinkled with rose petals and
worshipped by others around her.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There's talk about how the Pentagon (budget) is thought of as untouchable.
We want people to know that if we reduce spending there, we'll have more money
for health care and education,'' said Erica Swanson, who played the cow.
</P>
<P>
	   M.L. Lindon, the woman in the apron handing out the cookies, has attended
scores of political events over the past year.
</P>
<P>
	   Her group advocates cutting defense spending and shifting the money to
social programs.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   In front of the building was a 25-foot inflatable ear of corn, courtesy of
the group Ozone Action, which is asking candidates to include solutions for
global warming in their environmental platform.
</P>
<P>
	   Five activists from around the country plan to follow politicians across
Iowa until the caucuses on Jan. 24, drawing attention to the effect global
warming may have on agriculture.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Agriculture is life in Iowa,'' said Kate Simmons, a spokeswoman for the
group. ``God made Iowa to grow corn.''
</P>
<P>
	   The group also plans trips to other early states, such as New Hampshire and
California.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   Not all the activists outside the debate were Democrats.
</P>
<P>
	   John Strong, a Republican from West Des Moines, held in his right hand the
metal skeleton of a blue umbrella, stripped of its fabric. Hanging from the ribs
of the umbrella was a little white sign reading: ``Rebuild Veterans Health
Care.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``If they keep cutting it back, it will be like this umbrella -- almost
useless,'' Strong said.
</P>
<P>
	   Strong said he will spend the campaign season pushing for improved benefits
for veterans.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   Paul and Erma Joslin, who live across the street from the studios, brought
their 6-year-old grandson, Matthew Joslin, outside to watch as activists chanted
and performed and dancers and cheerleaders streamed past them.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's fun,'' Matthew said, though not as much as cartoons.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   An index card was the vice president's prop in the last debate. In this
debate, he turned to real people to make his points against Bradley, the former
senator from New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore scored one of his sharpest points by planting folks in the studio.
</P>
<P>
	   Trying to pin Bradley to the ropes on agriculture, an important issue in
this farm state, Gore called on farmer Chris Peterson. ``Could you stand up,
Chris?'' The man stood mute while Gore pointed out that Peterson lost 300 acres
in 1993 flooding.
</P>
<P>
	   Turning to Bradley, Gore asked, ``Why did you vote against the disaster
relief for Chris Peterson, when he and thousands of other farmers here in Iowa
needed it?''
</P>
<P>
	   Later, it was an elementary school teacher's turn. Pam Willard stood, a
little fidgety, while Gore introduced her as Des Moines teacher with 29 kids in
her class.
</P>
<P>
	   ``She needs help, not just talk. She needs new resources,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
	   Two or three other people Gore had picked up along the campaign trail were
on hand to illustrate issues that did not come up in the end.
</P>
<P>
	   While the surrogates were meant to put an outside-the-Washington-beltway
face on Gore's agenda, the candidates themselves were in full Washington costume
for their fifth televised meeting -- nearly identical dark suits and red ties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
