<HEADLINE> Homeless man sentenced to 18 years for killing of Hasbrouck Heights  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   HACKENSACK, N.J. (AP) - A homeless man was sentenced on Friday to 18
years in prison for the 1990 stabbing death of a bartender from Hasbrouck
Heights, authorities said.
<P>
	   David Livingstone, 32, must serve at least six years of the sentence handed
down by Superior Court Judge John A. Conte before he is eligible for parole,
said Bergen County Assistant Prosecutor Ike Gazvy.
</P>
<P>
	   He pleaded guilty to charges of aggravated manslaughter in November.
</P>
<P>
	   Authorities say Vernon Joliff was stabbed more than 30 times in his chest
and torso in his apartment on Sept. 11, 1990.
</P>
<P>
	   Investigators knew only that Joliff was last seen leaving the Manhattan bar
where he worked with a man named David.
</P>
<P>
	   In January 1997, authorities issued a warrant after they matched
fingerprints taken from Joliff's apartment with those taken from Livingstone
after an arrest in New York.
</P>
<P>
	   Livingstone was arrested eight days later after he jumped a subway turnstile
in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
	   He told authorities he killed Joliff after the two men fought at Joliff's
apartment. They had met in the bar earlier that evening.
</P>
</TEXT>
