<HEADLINE> Nike Says Shirts Aren't Toxic  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- Nike soccer jerseys pulled from store shelves across Germany
after a television report do not contain a dangerous amount of a toxic
anti-bacterial chemical, the company said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   Citing preliminary tests conducted by a Hamburg laboratory, Nike said the
jerseys present no danger to people.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Consumers and merchants can trust that no damage to health can arise from
this jersey,'' Charlie Denson, general manager for Nike Europe, said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
	   Der Spiegel newsmagazine also reported Saturday that an unnamed expert at
the federal institute for consumer protection said the tests found the jerseys
to be safe.
</P>
<P>
	   Three German department store chains stopped selling the shirts after the
television program Plusminus reported tests had turned up amounts of
tributyltin, or TBT, a heavy metal compound used in anti-barnacle paint for
ships. The program said it had commissioned a private lab to conduct the tests
on clothing items chosen at random in German stores.
</P>
<P>
	   Also used to kill bacteria and quell the smell of sweat, TBT would seem an
ideal additive for sports shirts. But at high levels in humans, TBT is believed
to cause neurological problems, damage the immune system and harm the liver,
some experts say. British and Dutch tests have shown the substance to cause
mutations in marine snails and the World Wildlife Fund is calling for a global
ban.
</P>
<P>
	   Nike cited another Hamburg scientist, Michael Braungart, as saying the tests
on sea animals were done with amounts 10 to 20 times higher than what was found
in the shirts and that the tests were not relevant to how the chemical would be
absorbed by the skin.
</P>
<P>
	   Nike said it would work with its suppliers to ensure no illegal substances
were used in its products. The jerseys were sold only in Europe, and stitched
together by a British company.
</P>
<P>
	   The initial report saying the shirts were contaminated caused a scandal in
part because the jerseys are worn by the popular German soccer club Borussia
Dortmund, which won the 1997 European championship. The club suspended sales of
the shirts at its official fan store.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-08-00 1521 </TRAILER>
