<HEADLINE> Payment delay forces state to halt anti-tobacco ads  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - New Jersey health officials have halted their
"Don't Get Sucked In" anti-smoking campaign because a legal dispute is delaying
the state's first installment in national tobacco settlement money.
<P>
	   The state Department of Health and Senior Services has begun taking down
about 70 billboards and pulling television and radio advertisements educating
young people about the health effects of smoking, The Record of Hackensack
reported in Saturday's editions.
</P>
<P>
	   A dispute over plaintiffs' legal fees in the government settlement has
delayed the first installment payment, officials said.
</P>
<P>
	   New Jersey is scheduled to receive $7.5 billion from tobacco companies over
25 years. It is one of only six states that have not yet received any money from
the national settlement.
</P>
<P>
	   State health officials had planned to use $7.2 million from the first
settlement payment to expand its existing ad campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   The lease for "Don't Get Sucked In" billboards expired at the end of 1999,
and the state is out of money to continue all but a few of them, said health
department spokesman Tom Breslin. The $2 million in state funding for television
and radio spots and movie trailers also ran out at the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
	   Anti-smoking activists criticized the legal dispute that prompted the
suspension of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   "An opportunity to warn youth about the dangers of tobacco has been lost
because the settlement has been delayed," said Larry Downs, director of the
anti-tobacco group New Jersey Breathes.
</P>
<P>
	   Attorneys representing a Passaic County smoker and the family of a Bergen
County woman have filed motions to force the state's attorneys to share legal
fees from the massive settlement.
</P>
<P>
	   The Attorney General's office has asked state courts to expedite a decision
on the dispute, but no action has been taken.
</P>
<P>
	   The state cannot receive any settlement money until a decision is made.
</P>
<P>
	   New Jersey is scheduled to receive $247 million from the tobacco settlement
this year. The state has agreed to spend $775 million over 30 years on tobacco
control programs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
