<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Displaced Syrians Hope To Return  </HEADLINE>
   By SUSAN SEVAREID Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) -- Syrian refugees displaced from the Israeli-occupied
Golan Heights celebrated the end of Ramadan on Saturday, visiting relatives and
taking their children for rides on a mini Ferris wheel set up in an empty lot.
</P>
<P>
	   A year from now, they hope, they'll be celebrating the same rituals to end
the Muslim month of fasting but in a different place-- on the land they fled
after Israel captured it during the 1967 Arab-Israeli War. The Middle East peace
talks in West Virginia have stirred their expectations.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I will leave soon and leave everything behind,'' Ahmed Mustafa Diab said
in Wafideen, a camp for displaced people 11 miles east of Damascus.
</P>
<P>
	   Before the war, the 31-year-old Diab's parents lived near Lake Tiberias,
also known as the Sea of Galilee. ``We hope this year, in 2000, we will
return,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Hope is much harder to come by among the nearly 35,000 Palestinians living
in Jaramana refugee camp, four miles east of Damascus and 16 miles from
Wafideen.
</P>
<P>
	   Their families also come from villages near the lake -- but the area they
came from is now recognized Israeli territory, not occupied land. They fled
homes near Safed, Israel, in 1948. Many say their return is years or generations
away.
</P>
<P>
	   Mahmoud Saleh, 38, points to the pavement in Jaramana camp and says this is
where he will spend many Ramadans to come.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is the situation now,'' he said. ``It is politics.''
</P>
<P>
	   The fate of the 3.5 million Palestinian refugees scattered across Syria,
Lebanon, Jordan, the West Bank and the Gaza Strip is one of the issues facing
the Israeli and Palestinian negotiators who are trying to forge a final peace
accord by Sept. 13.
</P>
<P>
	   Syrian-Israeli peace talks, which resumed last month after a freeze of
nearly 4 years, are expected to lead to the return of most, if not all, of the
Golan Heights to Syria. That could mean the Syrian refugees will be going home.
</P>
<P>
	   The Israeli-Palestinian dispute, with a history of stalls and missed
deadlines, is considered the harder problem to resolve.
</P>
<P>
	   Publicly, Palestinian officials are adamant about the right for refugees
from the 1948 and 1967 wars with Israel to return to their old homes. But unlike
those displaced in 1967, the 1948 refugees came from places that are now part of
Israel and will not be included in any future Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
	   Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak has indicated he would not object to
Palestinian refugees being resettled in a future Palestinian state. The sheer
numbers, however, would make doing so extremely difficult.
</P>
<P>
	   Some Jaramana residents accuse Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat of giving up
too much or looking after only the 1967 refugees.
</P>
<P>
	   ``As long as Arafat is our leader, he won't accept responsibility for us and
will leave us alone,'' said Khalid Khaldesayn, a 32-year-old Jaramana resident.
``He doesn't think about us.''
</P>
<P>
	   Khaldesayn is affiliated with Fatah Uprising, one of eight Palestinian
groups based in Damascus that have rejected Arafat's peace with Israel. But even
those who support Arafat say they know they won't be leaving Jaramana -- a
sprawl of concrete homes and twisting, narrow alleys -- any time soon.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Returning is not for me,'' said Abdullah Nimr Taher, a 40-year-old
mechanic. ``It is the second or third generations to come that will return to
their land.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-08-00 1524 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000108.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hillary Clinton campaign attacks Giuliani's fund raising methods  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - Hillary Rodham Clinton's Senate campaign accused Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani Saturday of evading fund-raising limits by using three separate
political committees to support his expected Senate bid.
<P>
	   Howard Wolfson, Mrs. Clinton's campaign spokesman, cited a New York Times
report that said Giuliani had raised and spent almost $1 million since March
1998 through two committees that operate under looser restrictions than his
official campaign organization.
</P>
<P>
	   Much of the money given to the two committees - called Solutions America and
Giuliani for New York - came from a group of loyal donors who have also given
the $2,000 legal limit to Giuliani's official Senate campaign committee, the
Times said, citing disclosure records.
</P>
<P>
	   "The mayor has established a political network of multiple fund-raising
committees and taxpayer resources to finance his Senate campaign, and it must
stop," Wolfson told reporters at a news conference in front of City Hall. "By
law, these committees should have remained separate and apart. But in fact, the
mayor has been operating them as if they were a single political fund-raising
machine, 'Rudy Inc."'
</P>
<P>
	   Solutions America, designed to promote Giuliani's political philosophy,
limits individual donations to $5,000 annually. Giuliani for New York operates
under state rules and allows donors to contribute up to $45,000 each. The two
committees have taken in and spent nearly $1 million since March 1998, records
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Federal rules bar funds raised by such committees from being used for
federal campaigns. In 1998 and the first half of 1999, Solutions America and
Giuliani for New York helped pay for at least one major Giuliani fund-raiser,
plus rent, salaries and other administrative costs for the mayor's political
operation, according to the Times.
</P>
<P>
	   Aides say that in the second half of 1999, while Giuliani considered and
planned his Senate bid, the committees were used not for that campaign but
primarily to finance advertisements for a referendum to change the City Charter.
Voters rejected the proposal in November.
</P>
<P>
	   Bruce Teitelbaum, who heads Giuliani's campaign committee, said all the
mayor's fund raising and spending was "perfectly appropriate and has been
reviewed and analyzed very carefully."
</P>
<P>
	   "This latest attack is a typical example of Clinton-style posturing and
hypocrisy," he continued. "Wolfson is trying to accuse and blame others to
deflect attention from serious campaign finance abuses the Clintons are famous
for."
</P>
<P>
	   In recent weeks Giuliani has criticized Mrs. Clinton for collecting more
than $360,000 in unregulated donations for a special Democratic party fund set
up for the New York Senate race. About $338,000 of that so-called soft money was
apparently spent on television ads that showed footage of the first lady in New
York and asked voters to "call Hillary."
</P>
<P>
	   Wolfson said the concerns about Giuliani's fund raising methods were real.
</P>
<P>
	   "'Rudy Inc.' has taken in more than $700,000 from donors who reached the
legal contribution limit for a Senate race," he charged. "And 'Rudy Inc.' has
subsidized the mayor's Senate campaign to the tune of over $600,000 by paying
for expenses that should have been assumed by Friends of Giuliani," the mayor's
Senate committee.
</P>
<P>
	   Teitelbaum said Solutions America and Giuliani for New York were both
created more than two years ago, long before the mayor began contemplating a
Senate run.
</P>
<P>
	   Aides to the mayor told the Times that the two committees' fund raising and
spending had been largely curtailed since last April, when Giuliani formally
notified the Federal Election Commission he was considering a Senate run.
</P>
<P>
	   "Up until late April we could raise and we could spend money without it
being viewed as promoting a Senate campaign because in fact the mayor was
undecided," said John Gross, the mayor's campaign treasurer.
</P>
<P>
	   But some campaign finance experts challenged that interpretation, saying the
unregulated money could not be spent on a Senate campaign at any time,
regardless of when Giuliani notified the FEC that he might run.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
