<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Patient glut from flu outbreak strains emergency rooms statewide  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - A raging flu outbreak and a shortage of beds and
staff in some hospitals have combined to tax emergency rooms statewide.
<P>
	   State Heath Depatment officials are reporting a dramatic increase in the
number of flu outbreaks being recorded statewide. Officials have documented 80
outbreaks of flu, compared to 19 this time last year.
</P>
<P>
	   Health officials track flu through the number of outbreaks in long term care
facilities such as nursing homes. This allows them to track the size and
seriousness of an outbreak.
</P>
<P>
	   "Numbers usually rise after the holiday, but this year is worse," Kristine
Smith, a spokeswoman for the state Health Department said. "We've tracked four
times as many outbreaks this year over last."
</P>
<P>
	   The situation has been particularly acute in western New York, Smith said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   In Rochester, hospitals are hiring temporary nurses and warning ambulances
away from crowded emergency rooms because of a sudden influx of patients
stricken with flu and pneumonia.
</P>
<P>
	   The surge in flu-related admissions began the week after Christmas, about a
month earlier than usual. In the last week, some patients have had to wait on
gurneys in emergency rooms for more than a day before beds opened up.
</P>
<P>
	   On Thursday, the city's two largest hospitals - Strong Memorial and
Rochester General - issued "code red" warnings to ambulances that they had no
beds open for incoming patients. That triggered a "mega red" declaration under
which the hospitals had to alternate opening every four hours regardless of
their bed status.
</P>
<P>
	   Most hospitals are reopening some of the beds they had closed in recent
years because of falling occupancy.
</P>
<P>
	   In Buffalo, Mercy Hospital was forced to divert ambulances with all but the
most critical patients to other institutions for long stretches of time almost
daily from late Dec. 23 to midnight Jan. 4. The hospital had no place to put
them.
</P>
<P>
	   Officials opened 16 additional beds and on Wednesday expressed confidence
that the problem had been solved.
</P>
<P>
	   But many hospitals continue to experience delays for care.
</P>
<P>
	   During the week Erie County Medical Center reported delays of several hours
in their emergency rooms.
</P>
<P>
	   University Hospital in Syracuse has since Monday been treating about 20
patients a day.
</P>
<P>
	   "We have seen an increase but we've not been forced to call in extra
people," Darryl Geddis, a spokesman for University Hospital, said. "Most of
those who have been hit are among the elderly population or people who are
working in nursing homes or day care centers."
</P>
<P>
	   New York is just one of 16 states reporting an outbreak of influenza,
according to the federal Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
	   Key flu symptoms include a sudden high fever, cough, sore throat, fatigue
and muscle aches. Most people who get flu recover completely in one to two
weeks, but some develop serious and potentially life-threatening illnesses, such
as pneumonia.
</P>
<P>
	   Between 10 percent and 20 percent of the country's population is laid low
each flu season, and about 200,000 people end up hospitalized. About 20,000
people nationwide die from complications of flu each year.
</P>
<P>
	   Four drugs are available to treat flu victims. In addition to amantadine and
rimantadine, which work only against the more common type A flu strains,
patients can get relief with two new anti-virals, Tamiflu and Relenza, which
work against both type A and type B. However, the new drugs must be taken within
two days of the start of symptoms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
