<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Threat Halts Berlin Communist Rally  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- Berlin police banned an annual communist demonstration on
Saturday after a man threatened to use a machine gun and hand grenades on the
thousands of expected participants.
</P>
<P>
	   Police said the former East German communists received a letter containing
the threat Friday from Olaf Juergen Staps, who was already being sought on arson
charges.
</P>
<P>
	   Hagen Saberschinsky, head of the Berlin police, said Staps was considered
unstable. He said the threat against the demonstration, which had been scheduled
for Sunday, was being taken very seriously.
</P>
<P>
	   Saberschinsky said he held extensive discussions with leaders of the Party
of Democratic Socialism, and they agreed to call off the protest because of the
threat. The party also agreed not to lay a wreath at a socialist memorial,
normally part of the event.
</P>
<P>
	   Last year, about 100,000 people participated in the demonstration held each
year in memory of Rosa Luxemburg and Karl Liebknecht, founders of the German
Communist Party who were killed in a failed January 1919 uprising in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
	   The anniversary of the death of Liebknecht and Luxemburg was an annual
celebration when the communists held power in East Germany. The PDS revived the
demonstrations in 1992.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
