<HEADLINE> Minister: Fonda More 'Spiritual'  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- A minister who knows Jane Fonda says the Academy
Award-winning actress is seeking a more spiritual life, but won't say if that
was the reason for her separation from husband Ted Turner.
</P>
<P>
	   The Web site WorldNetDaily.com reported last week that the separation was
partially caused by Fonda's ``embrace of 'born-again' evangelical
Christianity.'' It also reported she was attending Bible study in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
	   The Rev. Gerald Durley said he doubted that Fonda, 62, was regularly
attending Bible study but that she has ``found a certain sense of peace among
people who've found peace with Christianity.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``I think as she approached her 60th birthday, she began to search for more
meaning,'' Durley told The Atlanta Journal-Constitution. ``I am extremely
impressed with the genuineness and sincerity in her search for spirituality and
wholeness.''
</P>
<P>
	   Durley is pastor of Providence Missionary Baptist Church and former
president of Concerned Black Clergy.
</P>
<P>
	   The newspaper said Durley would not comment on the couple's eight-year
marriage, Turner, or the cause of the separation that was announced last week.
</P>
<P>
	   Officials of Turner Broadcasting System officials would not comment on the
Web site report.
</P>
<P>
	   Durley did not return several calls for additional comment Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1990, Turner denounced Christianity as being for ``losers.'' He also
insulted Pope John Paul II and told a Polish joke during a 1998 speech. He later
apologized.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
