<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: EU Balkan Envoy Criticized  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- The European Union's foreign affairs commissioner is leveling
harsh criticism at the chief EU envoy for Balkan reconstruction, a newsmagazine
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   The office of EU foreign affairs commissioner Chris Patten has criticized
Bodo Hombach for having no clear projects to foster the Balkan Stability Pact's
goals, Der Spiegel reported. It cited a memo it obtained from a Dec. 22 meeting.
</P>
<P>
	   Spiegel reported that the memo also criticized Hombach for having requested
``excessive'' finances for the job. For this year, the magazine said, Hombach
requested a $234,000 allowance.
</P>
<P>
	   The memo criticized Hombach's finances for budgeting him to travel 225 days
this year -- every working day on the calendar, Spiegel said.
</P>
<P>
	   Hombach, however, told the Welt am Sonntag newspaper that the memo had not
come from Patten himself, but from someone working in his office. Hombach said
Patten ``didn't criticize my work, but actually the opposite,'' during a meeting
between the two men shortly before Christmas.
</P>
<P>
	   Andrew Levi, a spokesman in Hombach's office, said the requested expenses
were in line with what an EU commissioner normally receives.
</P>
<P>
	   Hombach served as Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder's chief of staff before
taking the EU post on Aug. 1. The stability pact was launched in September at a
summit in Sarajevo, Bosnia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
