<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chess Prodigy Leko Wins Match  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) -- Hungarian chess prodigy Peter Leko won a challenge
match against a Russian world champion after playing to a draw Saturday in the
fifth game of the tournament.
</P>
<P>
	   After the 43rd move, Alexander Khalifman, the champion of last year's Las
Vegas world championship, had no other choice but to offer a draw, the
tournament's spokesman Daniel Molnar told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Leko was obviously much better prepared for this tournament, and he
deserved to win,'' the 33-year-old Russian said after the four-hour match.
</P>
<P>
	   Leko, 21, has won two games and tied three in the exhibition tournament.
With one point for each win and half a point for each tie, he leads 3.5-1.5 and
will win regardless of the outcome of the next game.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I'm very glad to have won, that's all I can say at the moment,'' Leko
said.
</P>
<P>
	   The two players agreed to play their best in Sunday's match, even though the
tournament victory is no longer at stake.
</P>
<P>
	   Despite being world champion, Khalifman is 28th on FIDE's most recent world
list, while Leko is eighth.
</P>
<P>
	   The tournament is sponsored by the German Westfaelische Ferngas AG. The
winner receives $10,280, and the loser gets $5,140.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile at a meeting in Budapest, European Chess Union officials agreed to
hold the first European men's individual championship in the history of chess,
the state news agency MTI reported. The championship is to be held in Italy in
June 2000, with prize money of $52,643.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
