<HEADLINE> Anderson Urges Campaign Reform  </HEADLINE>
   By KEN THOMAS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Former independent presidential candidate John
Anderson said Saturday that the Reform Party should advocate campaign finance
reform.
</P>
<P>
	   Anderson, who earned 7 percent of the vote in the 1980 presidential
election, said the Reform Party is adrift and should push for the public
financing of elections.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I think that the Reform Party, to have any chance at all, has to define
itself much better than they have been able to do,'' Anderson said in an
interview with The Associated Press. ``I think it's a party in search not only
of a candidate but even more importantly the predicate for a successful
candidacy has to be a successful platform.''
</P>
<P>
	   Anderson also spoke to about 50 members of the Iowa Citizen Action Network,
an advocacy group that hopes to push campaign finance reform at the Jan. 24
caucuses. The group has signed up 434 activists and hopes to enlist 1,000
people.
</P>
<P>
	   Anderson said he still is hoping that the Reform Party will push campaign
finance reform, a key issue for Republican John McCain and Democrat Bill
Bradley.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The campaign is not over yet. Maybe someone on behalf of the Reform Party
will pick up that issue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Anderson's name was recently placed on California's ballot of the Reform
Party along with Donald Trump and three lesser-known Reform Party candidates.
Commentator Pat Buchanan announced his Reform Party bid last fall and Trump has
expressed interest in a Reform Party run.
</P>
<P>
	   Anderson said the decision to be placed on the California ballot was made
without his efforts. But he could not rule out a possible third-party campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I did not initiate the effort. It was done strictly by the chair of the
party,'' Anderson said. ``They were obviously not satisfied that the only name
to this date is Donald Trump. I have not declared a potential candidacy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
