<HEADLINE> Ex-councilman sentenced to jail, probation in race bias case  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   MOUNT HOLLY, N.J. (AP) - A white former Mount Holly councilman has been
sentenced to jail time and probation for his role in a racially charged attack
in a local tavern.
<P>
	   Robert Byham, 40, was sentenced Friday to two years probation and 30 days in
jail on the bias harassment and assault charges.
</P>
<P>
	   Byham, who also is a former Mount Laurel police officer, and white
codefendant Thomas Dillon were convicted for their fight with two black men at
Thirsty's Pub in 1997.
</P>
<P>
	   Byham was accused of using a racial slur and instigating the fight. He was a
councilman at the time of the incident.
</P>
<P>
	   Dillon, 36, of Mount Laurel, was sentenced to one year probation and 50
hours of community service after he was found guilty of bias harassment.
</P>
<P>
	   "There was nothing indirect or subtle about this case," Superior Court Judge
Victor Friedman said in sentencing the men. "This case was stark and arrogant."
</P>
<P>
	   Byham vowed to appeal the sentence. He suggested that the prosecutor, James
Ronca, pursued the case for political reasons.
</P>
<P>
	   "I am not a racist," Byham said outside the courtroom. "I never have been."
</P>
</TEXT>
