<HEADLINE> Ed Board meets to discuss interim chancellor candidates  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - With pressure from City Hall mounting, the Board of
Education met Saturday to discuss candidates for interim schools chancellor.
<P>
	   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani appeared strongly opposed to the board's leading
choice, Harold Levy, a banking executive with ties to the Democratic Party.
Board members interviewed Levy and two other candidates Friday, and said they
hoped to choose a temporary replacement for ousted former Chancellor Rudy Crew
by Sunday.
</P>
<P>
	   The Giuliani administration was pressuring board members to back off their
support for Levy, a lawyer for Citicorp and a member of the state Board of
Regents.
</P>
<P>
	   Giuliani's supporters on the board had appeared to be pushing for Joseph
Viteritti, a New York University research professor who has served as a policy
adviser to the mayor. But the cable news channel New York 1 reported Saturday
that Viteritti withdrew his name from consideration.
</P>
<P>
	   City Hall may try to propose a compromise candidate. Robert Kiley, former
chairman of the Metropolitan Tranportation Authority and current head of the New
York City Partnership, was considered a strong possibility.
</P>
<P>
	   On Friday, board members interviewed Levy, Viteritti and John Jay Iselin,
who has been president of Channel 13 and Cooper Union for the Advancement of
Science and Art.
</P>
<P>
	   The board reconvened Saturday afternoon to assess the merits of each
candidate. The board has said it's seeking a leader with strong management
skills.
</P>
<P>
	   Members voted to buy out the remainder of Crew's contract. The board will
choose a new chancellor after finding an interim replacement.
</P>
</TEXT>
