<HEADLINE> Chirac Visits Storm-Battered Areas  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   USSEL, France (AP) -- President Jacques Chirac visited a wind-battered forest
on Saturday and met with cleanup teams in a central region of France badly hit
by storms that swept through Europe two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's the place where I have my roots, and I find it disfigured,'' said
Chirac, who lives in a chateau in the Correze region when he is not at the
Elysee palace in Paris.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It will be dozens and dozens of years before this landscape recovers its
equilibrium and harmony,'' he said at a devastated forest near the town of
Ussel. ``It is an incomparable loss for the people who live here.''
</P>
<P>
	   The president met with soldiers and electricity teams working to clear trees
and fix power lines damaged in the two storms.
</P>
<P>
	   Fewer than 100,000 French homes were still without power Saturday, the
national electric company EDF said. Most of the affected households were in the
country's central and southwestern regions. Teams from throughout Europe have
helped EDF restore electricity to the 3.4 million French homes that originally
lost power.
</P>
<P>
	   Ninety people in France died in storm-related incidents. The violent weather
also uprooted millions of trees from the nation's forests and parks and damaged
historical monuments such as the Notre Dame cathedral and the royal palace at
Versailles.
</P>
</TEXT>
