<HEADLINE> French Say Seafood Not Contaminated  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BREST, France (AP) -- French authorities said Saturday that seafood already
on the market showed no signs of contamination from an oil slick floating off
France's northwest coast.
</P>
<P>
	   Still, federal food agencies introduced a ban on fishing and oyster
harvesting off the worst-hit shorelines. Many local governments along the
Atlantic had already banned such activities for several days.
</P>
<P>
	   ``So far, the analyses on shellfish and fish at the consumer level have
shown an absence of contamination,'' a statement from several state food
agencies said.
</P>
<P>
	   Thousands of protesters marched Saturday through the streets of the coastal
town of Saint-Nazaire, calling for Franco-Belgian oil company TotalFina to take
more responsibility for the spill, LCI television reported.
</P>
<P>
	   The ``Erika'' tanker, chartered by TotalFina, cracked in half on Dec. 12,
spilling 3 million gallons of heavy oil into the waters off the picturesque
Atlantic coast.
</P>
<P>
	   The company has offered to pay $6 million for a part of the clean up. It was
unclear how much the total bill would cost.
</P>
<P>
	   Oil continued to wash up on land Saturday, and teams were still scraping up
gummy patches from 250 miles of coastline. About 6 million gallons of oil remain
trapped in the two halves of the sunken tanker.
</P>
<P>
	   Earlier this week, a governmental food safety watchdog group proposed
several more precautions, including a ban on the sale of salt and seaweed from
the visibly affected coasts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-08-00 1612 </TRAILER>
