<DOCNO> APW20000108.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 16:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> $10,000 Offered for Malaysia Tribe  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) -- A Swiss activist offered $10,000 to help the
nomadic Penan tribe, but the local government refused the aid, calling it a
publicity stunt, the Malaysian news agency said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   Bruno Manser said he had hoped the money would be used to help improve the
living conditions of the Penans, believed to be the world's last nomadic rain
forest tribe, Bernama reported.
</P>
<P>
	   The Penans, which live in the state of Sarawak on Borneo island, fear they
may die out as a result of the industrial revolution, which is making inroads
into their habitat deep in the lush forests.
</P>
<P>
	   But the Sarawak government brushed aside the aid offer, calling it ``just
another publicity stunt,'' the news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
	   The shy Penans live off palm, bear and boar and then move on to where the
forest has regenerated for thousands of years. The government wants to bring
them into society's mainstream by offering them homes with running water,
schools and work.
</P>
<P>
	   Manser reportedly offered to help the government run a mobile dental clinic
for the Penans and the Kelabits, another nomadic tribe.
</P>
<P>
	   Manser, a self-proclaimed champion of the Penans, lived with them until he
was arrested in 1987 for anti-logging activities.
</P>
<P>
	   After his deportation, Manser re-entered Sarawak clandestinely. He caused a
stir last year by landing solo in a glider at a construction site near the state
capital, Kuching.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-08-00 1613 </TRAILER>
