<DOCNO> APW20000108.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 16:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cleric Charged in US Embassy Threat  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) -- A Muslim cleric from neighboring South Africa has
been charged with threatening to bomb the U.S. Embassy in Harare, a
state-controlled newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   The embassy was closed to the public after Mohammed Yesudas, 28, from the
South African city of Durban, allegedly threatened on Christmas Eve to blow up a
vehicle near the mission in Zimbabwe's capital.
</P>
<P>
	   Security guards told would-be visitors the embassy was closed until Jan. 4
``for security reasons. Embassy officials could not be reached Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   Yesudas was in custody on charges of threatening to commit acts of
terrorism, The Herald reported. If convicted, he faces 10 years' imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
	   He is accused of going to the heavily fortified embassy and telling a
Zimbabwean security company employee he was a commando trained in Afghanistan,
and planned to detonate explosives packed in a vehicle at the diplomatic
mission.
</P>
<P>
	   The security guard alerted police after the bizarre conversation, and police
tracked down and apprehended Yesudas on Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
	   Security at the two-story U.S. Embassy, overlooking gardens about a mile
from the city center, has been fortified since the American embassies in Kenya
and Tanzania were bombed in 1998. The United States suspects Osama bin Laden, a
Saudi who has been hiding out in Afghanistan, masterminded those attacks, in
which 224 people were killed.
</P>
<P>
	   A line of concrete blocks prevents vehicles coming within 10 yards of the
U.S. Embassy's outer wall in Harare. A side road has been closed to the public.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1991, suspected Iraqi agents blew up the foyer of Harare's Sheraton
International Hotel, injuring three people, as a reprisal for Zimbabwe's
pro-U.S. stance during the Persian Gulf War.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
