<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
   By The Associated Press
<TEXT>
<P>
	   Showers spread from the southern Plains across the South and the Ohio Valley
on Saturday, and snow showers rippled through the northern Rockies.
</P>
<P>
	   Moist air flowing out of the Gulf of Mexico combined with low pressure over
Texas to produce clouds and showers across eastern sections of Texas, Oklahoma
and Kansas, plus areas of Louisiana, Arkansas and Missouri.
</P>
<P>
	   During the afternoon, the wet weather moved eastward, with some heavy rain
falling over northern parts of Mississippi and Alabama.
</P>
<P>
	   Light showers were scattered from Illinois through the Ohio and Tennessee
valleys into western sections of Virginia and the Carolinas.
</P>
<P>
	   Across the Northwest, rain was scattered over western Oregon and Washington.
</P>
<P>
	   Farther inland, snow showers were scattered through the Cascades and
Olympics, and through Idaho into western Montana and northern Nevada and Utah.
Some snow showers also developed in the mountains of western Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
	   Brisk wind blew across Montana, with gusts to 40 mph at Cut Bank, Livingston
and Great Falls.
</P>
<P>
	   Light snow showers were possible during the night in the western Dakotas and
Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
	   Elsewhere, a few light, isolated snow showers moved across northern New York
state.
</P>
<P>
	   Saturday's temperatures around the Lower 48 states ranged from a morning low
of 3 below zero at Big Piney, Wyo., and Grand Canyon, Ariz., to a midday reading
of 80 at Hollywood, Fla. The lowest wind chill was 28 below zero at Frenchville,
Maine, and the highest heat index by early afternoon was 83 at Fort Lauderdale,
Fla.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
