<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State police investigator disciplined in politically motivated  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   SCHENECTADY, N.Y. (AP) - The state police has demoted, reassigned and
suspended an investigator who officials said planned a politically motivated
traffic stop days before Election Day.
<P>
	   State police Lt. Jamie Mills said the investigator pleaded guilty to
departmental charges of misconduct and was reassigned to the uniformed road
patrol, transferred from the Albany-area troop to the Hudson Valley, suspended
without pay for a "substantial" period and given a letter of censure, reported
The Daily Gazette of Schenectady.
</P>
<P>
	   Mills wouldn't identify the investigator.
</P>
<P>
	   State police said the investigator received "detailed" information from an
acquaintance outside the state police about George Robertson - a top local
official and ally of Schenectady Mayor Albert Jurczynski who was in the midst of
a bitter reelection campaign. The information, later proved false, claimed
Robertson was driving with a suspended license, Mills said.
</P>
<P>
	   The investigator relayed the incorrect information to a trooper who saw
Robertson driving and pulled him over on Oct. 26, Mills said.
</P>
<P>
	   Robertson was ticketed for driving with a suspended license, having lapsed
insurance and not wearing a seat belt. The first two charges subsequently were
dropped and the seat belt charge is to be dismissed if Robertson stays out of
trouble for six months.
</P>
<P>
	   Mills said the investigator had engineered the stop at the behest of an
acquaintance, who had it in for Robertson. She did not name the acquaintance.
</P>
<P>
	   "It was a personal friendship  1/8the former investigator 3/8 had with
somebody outside the state police," Mills said. "This person had provided him
with information about Mr. Robertson ... It was a personal agenda on the part of
this investigator's friend."
</P>
<P>
	   Robertson said he knew the stop was politically motivated.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think it's unfortunate because I think the police power of the state
should not be used in politics," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Jurczynski, a Republican, said he believes the state police should reveal
the identities of everyone in the incident.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm pleased that the state police took appropriate action to discipline the
officers involved, but whoever it was that approached the state police, I would
like that information to be made public, whoever that may be," said the mayor,
who is closely allied with GOP Gov. George Pataki. "I would call on the state
police in the name of justice to let the public know who was behind this."
</P>
<P>
	   Jurczynski's opponent, Democrat Gary McCarthy denied any knowledge of the
plan. "I had nothing to do with it. It's the first I'm hearing of this," he said
Friday, referring to the discipline.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-08-00 1647 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
