<DOCTYPE> SUBDIVIDED </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 5 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    Saturday, Jan. 8, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore, Bradley Debate Health Care
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   JOHNSTON, Iowa (AP) -- Bill Bradley accused Al Gore of trying to scare Iowa
voters with misrepresentations of his health care proposal today while the vice
president said he is campaigning on "the front lines in the fight for our future
and has "not been hiding in a Washington bunker." The contenders argued about
health care, farm policy, education -- a familiar array after four prior
Democratic presidential campaign debates -- and Gore revived his challenge for
even more debates. He said they should meet twice a week, scrap TV ads, and
debate next in Iowa on agriculture policy.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Confederate Flag Rally Draws 6,000
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- An estimated 6,000 people gathered today under a sea
of red Confederate flags to defend the banner that has flown from the Statehouse
dome for 38 years and thrust the state into the national spotlight. Today's
event was the second day of a three-day rally being staged by supporters of the
flag, who say it stands for defiant defense of freedom and Southern heritage.
The NAACP says the banner is a symbol of slavery. And at the other end of Main
Street, leaders of the state NAACP met but did not decide to widen economic
sanctions against South Carolina beyond a tourism boycott that started a week
ago.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Soldier Pleads Guilty in Killing
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   FORT CAMPBELL, Ky. (AP) -- A soldier pleaded guilty to a reduced charge
today in the killing of a barracks mate, beaten to death in his sleep, who had
been rumored to be gay. Army Spc. Justin R. Fisher, 26, admitted he lied to
military investigators and obstructed the investigation when he wiped blood from
a baseball bat that Pvt. Calvin Glover used to kill Pfc. Barry Winchell. Under a
plea agreement, the Army dropped other charges, including participating as a
principal to premeditated murder and acting as an accessory after the fact.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Cuban-Americans Suspend Protests
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   MIAMI (AP) -- Encouraged by a lawmaker's bid to keep Elian Gonzalez in the
United States, Cuban-American leaders said today they will temporarily halt
protests against plans to return the child to Cuba. The organizers cited a "more
positive course" in the ongoing custody battle over the 6-year-old. That
includes a subpoena issued by Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., to have the boy testify
before a House committee and efforts by Elian's relatives to attain custody of
the child. Committee sources said it is unlikely Elian will actually be asked to
appear.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Cleric Charged in U.S. Embassy Threat
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) -- A Muslim cleric from neighboring South Africa has
been charged with threatening to bomb the U.S. Embassy in Harare, a
state-controlled newspaper reported today. The embassy was closed to the public
after Mohammed Yesudas, 28, from the South African city of Durban, allegedly
threatened on Christmas Eve to blow up a vehicle near the mission in Zimbabwe's
capital. Security at the two-story U.S. Embassy, overlooking gardens about a
mile from the city center, has been fortified since the American embassies in
Kenya and Tanzania were bombed in 1998.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Serb Gen. Threatens Kosovo Return
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- A top Yugoslav Army general threatened today to
return to Kosovo, charging that NATO peacekeepers and U.N. officials have failed
to prevent a genocide against Serbs in the southern Yugoslav province. Serbia's
control over its southern province has been "only temporarily suspended," Gen.
Nebojsa Pavkovic was quoted as saying by the official Tanjug news agency. Also
today, the Yugoslav government accused opposition leader Vuk Draskovic of
conspiring with the French intelligence service to try to topple Milosevic.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Nike Says Shirts Aren't Toxic
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   BERLIN (AP) -- Nike soccer jerseys pulled from store shelves across Germany
after a television report do not contain a dangerous amount of a toxic
anti-bacterial chemical, the company said today. Citing preliminary tests
conducted by a Hamburg laboratory, Nike said the jerseys present no danger to
people. Three German department store chains stopped selling the shirts after a
television program reported tests had turned up amounts of a heavy metal
compound used in anti-barnacle paint for ships.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Titans Get Last-Second Win Over Bills
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Kevin Dyson sped 75 yards down the left sideline
with a lateral on a kickoff for the winning touchdown with three seconds
remaining today, lifting the Tennessee Titans to a 22-16 playoff victory over
the stunned Buffalo Bills. The Titans had to survive a video review. Buffalo
players, meanwhile, lay strewn on the turf, in shock that they allowed Tennessee
to steal the first playoff game of 2000. It was the first touchdown on a kickoff
return for the Titans since 1988, when they were the Houston Oilers, and Dyson's
first kickoff return ever.
</P>
