<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 6 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    Saturday, Jan. 8, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Troops: Russia Understating Deaths
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   SLEPTSOVSKAYA, Russia (AP) -- Russian soldiers said Saturday that the
military is understating casualties in Chechnya, hushing up the deaths of scores
of men to avoid a public backlash against the increasingly bloody war. In a
series of interviews, Russian soldiers in Chechnya and the adjoining region of
Ingushetia claimed their units had suffered numerous casualties that have not
been reported. It was not possible to obtain overall figures, but soldiers in
some units said more than half the men in their detachments had been killed or
wounded in recent weeks.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bradley Hits Gore on Agriculture Issue
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   JOHNSTON, Iowa (AP) -- Bill Bradley got the last words in today's debate
with Vice-President Al Gore, and used them to slap Gore on an issue central in
the farm state that will register the first Democratic decision of the 2000
presidential campaign, in party caucuses Jan. 24. "Al's been hammering me on my
agriculture votes 15 years ago," the former New Jersey senator said. "But I
would simply ask the family farmers of Iowa today, are you better off than you
were seven years ago or do we need a change?" Despite a robust U.S. economy, the
agriculture sector is suffering through its worst downturn in more than a
decade. Net farm income in Iowa is projected at $40.4 billion in 2000, down $7.6
billion from 1999.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mideast Talks Have Slow First Week
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   SHEPHERDSTOWN, W.Va. (AP) -- Mideast peace talks, which recessed for the
Jewish Sabbath and the Muslim feast marking the end of the holy month of
Ramadan, are not expected to start before tomorrow at the earliest, officials
say. The State Department's assessment of the first week of talks basically
indicates that little progress was achieved. During that period, there were only
two face-to-face meetings between Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Syrian
Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa. And that took President Clinton four trips to
this town to arrange.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Forbes Outlines Political Agenda
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   ATLANTA (AP) -- Republican presidential candidate Steve Forbes outlined a
political agenda to the Christian Coalition of Georgia today that he said would
renew faith and redeem the moral principles of the nation. The key lies in life,
liberty and pursuit of happiness, in that order, he said. Forbes made several
references to abortion, telling about 300 supporters at Mount Vernon Baptist
Church his first act as president would be to sign a law banning a form of
late-term abortion. "Life begins at conception and should end only in natural
death," he said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Protests Suspended Over Cuban Boy
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   MIAMI (AP) -- Encouraged by a lawmaker's bid to keep Elian Gonzalez in the
United States, Cuban-American leaders said today they will temporarily halt
protests against plans to return the child to Cuba. The organizers cited a "more
positive course" in the ongoing custody battle over the 6-year-old. That
includes a subpoena issued by Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., to have the boy testify
before a House committee and efforts by Elian's relatives to attain custody of
the child. Committee sources said it is unlikely Elian will actually be asked to
appear.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Thousands Rally for Confederate Flag
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- An estimated 6,000 people gathered today under a sea
of red Confederate flags to defend the banner that has flown from the Statehouse
dome for 38 years and thrust the state into the national spotlight. Today's
event was the second day of a three-day rally being staged by supporters of the
flag, who say it stands for defiant defense of freedom and Southern heritage.
The NAACP says the banner is a symbol of slavery.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Titans Pull Off Last-Second Win
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Kevin Dyson sped 75 yards down the left sideline
with a lateral from Frank Wycheck on a kickoff for the winning touchdown with
three seconds remaining today, lifting the Tennessee Titans to a 22-16 playoff
victory over the stunned Buffalo Bills. The Titans had to survive a video
review. Buffalo players, meanwhile, lay strewn on the turf, in shock that they
allowed Tennessee to steal the first playoff game of 2000.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Suicide Threat Delays Redskins Fans
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Washington Redskins fans heading to their team's first
playoff game since 1993 hit a roadblock when authorities closed a major bridge
to the stadium to respond to a man threatening suicide. Virginia and Maryland
state police closed all eastbound lanes of the Woodrow Wilson Bridge, which
carries the Capital Beltway over the Potomac River, at about 3 p.m. when they
learned the man had one leg over the rail and a brick tied to a rope around his
neck. The man didn't jump and was in custody an hour later, police said. He was
taken to a hospital for evaluation.
</P>
