<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N.H. Publisher Nackey Loeb Dies  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   GOFFSTOWN, N.H. (AP) -- Nackey S. Loeb, the former publisher of The Union
Leader and New Hampshire Sunday News who during the impeachment scandal ran a
headline calling President Clinton ``a disgrace,'' died Saturday at her home,
the papers said. She was 75.
</P>
<P>
	   Mrs. Loeb had been in failing health due in part to complications associated
with her partial paralysis from a 1977 car accident.
</P>
<P>
	   She retired in May but still maintained an interest in the affairs of the
Manchester newspapers and consulted on the recent endorsement of Steve Forbes in
next month's Republican New Hampshire Primary.
</P>
<P>
	   The Union Leader is the largest newspaper in the state and the only
statewide daily, the New Hampshire Sunday News is the largest Sunday paper in
the state.
</P>
<P>
	   Mrs. Loeb and her late husband, William Loeb, bought the newspapers in the
1940s and turned them into two of the nation's most conservative papers. William
Loeb's blunt editorial style and his active involvement in the state's
presidential primaries earned the Union Leader a national reputation that his
wife continued to nurture.
</P>
<P>
	   Mrs. Loeb, born in 1924 to Robert and Margaret Scripps and an heir to the
Scripps Howard publishing fortune, took over as publisher after her husband died
in 1981. During her 18 years at the helm, she pursued a more quiet, but still
forceful approach.
</P>
<P>
	   An editorial signed by Publisher Joseph McQuaid for Sunday's editions said,
``We were lucky to have her because her commitment to maintain an independent
voice caused her to not only hang onto The Union Leader and Sunday News after
William Loeb's death but to invest in their future and to do the hard work of
leading us there.''
</P>
<P>
	   During a visit by Clinton in February, a week after the Senate voted not to
oust him over the Monica Lewinsky scandal, she didn't hesitate to publish a
front-page editorial with the headline: ``Mr. President, you're a disgrace!''
</P>
<P>
	   Republican presidential candidate Patrick Buchanan called her his
``political godmother,'' and credited her endorsement for his 1996 New Hampshire
primary upset of Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
	   Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the front runner in the Republican presidential
race, said that while he and Mrs. Loeb ``did not always agree, her opinions and
influence always helped shape the politics and the independent spirit of the
state of New Hampshire.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``She will always be known as the torch bearer for conservative views,''
said Terrence Williams, publisher of The Telegraph in Nashua. ``She certainly
stayed true to that over the years, and she made quite a name for herself doing
so.''
</P>
<P>
	   Mrs. Loeb also kept the newspapers in step with the changing needs of their
readers. She made the decision to convert the daily newspaper to a morning
publication and was involved in expanding it onto the Internet.
</P>
<P>
	   Details on survivors were not available.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-08-00 1818 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000108.0229 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SEC Accuses Oil Firms of Fraud  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. (AP) -- The Securities and Exchange Commission is accusing
two oil companies and three businesses involved in selling their stock of
deceiving investors in an $8 million oil well scheme.
</P>
<P>
	   Petro Resources Corp. of Scottsdale and its president, Samuel McClintock,
and Austral Oil &AMP; Exploration Inc. of Sulphur, La., and its president, Myron
Palermo, are named in the civil suit accusing the group of securities fraud.
</P>
<P>
	   Also named were ITS Consulting Inc. of Newport Beach, Calif.; Integrity
Financial Group of Montreal; and Tritech Investment Group of Laguna Beach,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
	   According to the complaint, Petro Resources and Austral obtained oil leases
in Oklahoma and Texas and then contracted with ITS Consulting and its president,
Alan B. Baiocchi, to raise money from investors to drill wells.
</P>
<P>
	   Baiocchi and his associates directed the sale of securities "through a
'boiler room' involving unsolicited cold calls and high pressure sales
techniques" and directed similar sales through Integrity and Tritech, the suit
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Investors were promised "fantastic" returns but were not told of the risks
or that most of their money would go to sales commissions, said Don Hoerl,
associate regional director of the SEC office in Denver.
</P>
<P>
	   According to the lawsuit, filed Thursday in federal district court in Orange
County, Calif., about $8 million was raised from about 400 investors nationwide
from January 1996 through July 1997.
</P>
<P>
	   Palermo denied any wrongdoing and said he used about $750,000 to drill two
new wells and re-enter two previously drilled wells. Only one produced oil.
</P>
<P>
	   "I lost a quarter of a million dollars on it, and I can prove that," Palmero
said. "I didn't have anything to do with raising the money. All I did was drill
the wells."
</P>
<P>
	   Officials at the other companies could not be reached for comment Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   A few investors received a small amount of their investment back, but the
majority lost most of their money, Hoerl said.
</P>
<P>
	   "All of the defendants misrepresented . . . facts to investors or
prospective investors," the suit said. It also said none of the securities,
brokers or dealers was registered with the SEC.
</P>
<P>
	   The SEC wants an injunction to prevent further sales, unspecified civil
fines and the return of money to investors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-08-00 1845 </TRAILER>
