<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCain Defends Regulators' Letters  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sen. John McCain said Saturday he only was trying to
protect consumers and prod regulators to act when he wrote letters on behalf of
large donors and other companies in his capacity as Commerce Committee chairman.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I have acted on one fundamental principle, and that is to try to protect
the consumer,'' the GOP presidential contender said while campaigning in South
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain, R-Ariz., said most of the letters he has written to regulators urged
them to act on matters concerning telecommunications and airlines that were
languishing.
</P>
<P>
	   ``An overwhelming majority of these communications are, 'please act, please
act,''' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
	   The senator wrote federal regulators on behalf of more than a dozen
contributors over the past three years, according to hundreds of documents made
public Saturday by his campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain wrote twice in 1998 to William Kennard, chairman of the Federal
Communications Commission, with concerns about a lawsuit by broadcast networks
against satellite television distributors.
</P>
<P>
	   A federal district court had issued a preliminary injunction that would mean
the companies could not distribute programing from local stations.
</P>
<P>
	   The decision would have hurt Echostar Communications Corp., a Littleton,
Col., satellite TV company. The company has donated $18,000 to McCain's
presidential committee, according to campaign officials.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Our concern is that, once deprived of their network programming, consumers
will abandon satellite television service ...'' McCain wrote. He asked the FCC
to look into how many customers would lose network service.
</P>
<P>
	   Officials from Echostar had visited McCain to voice concerns prior to his
writing the letter, aides said.
</P>
<P>
	   But McCain's motivation in writing was because he believed consumers would
be hurt and that the decision would stymie competition, said Senate Commerce
Committee Republican staff director Mark Buse.
</P>
<P>
	   Although it was a life issue at the time, Congress has since passed
legisation allowing satellite services to carry broadcasting by local stations.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain weighed in on behalf of BellSouth, trying to offer long-distance
service; Ameritech, trying to merge with SBC Communications; America West
airlines, trying to offer airline service out of Flagstaff Airport; and other
corporate givers.
</P>
<P>
	   The memos show McCain intervened just as forcefully on behalf of companies
that did not give to his campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   For example, in a July 1999 letter to Kennard, McCain complained about the
delay in transferring a broadcast license for a Texas radio station.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain, an outspoken supporter of campaign finance reform, complained he was
being held to a different standard compared with other members of Congress, most
of whom write federal agencies on behalf of constituents and donors.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Take a look at what other congressmen and senators do,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain said that in keeping most of his letters focused on getting
regulators to act on matter of public interest, he was adhering to a higher
standard than others.
</P>
<P>
	   ``What is the standard and am I acting in higher standard? I think so,'' he
said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain's campaign staff made public over 1,500 pages consisting of letters
to various agencies and responses from 1997 to present. He is also asking
federal agencies to release all correspondence from him dating back to 1983,
when McCain began his career in Washington as a House member.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   Associated Press Writer Leigh Strope in Columbia, S.C., contributed to this
report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-08-00 1846 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
