<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 19:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bus, Truck Crash in N.M., 2 Killed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TINNIE, N.M. (AP) -- A tractor-trailer rig hauling produce slammed into a
church van preparing to enter a cemetery for a funeral Saturday, killing three
people in the van and injuring 10 other people, state police reported.
</P>
<P>
	   The van from the First Baptist Church of Alamogordo was carrying senior
citizens, said Dorothetta Ernest, manager of the Red Cross service center in
nearby Ruidoso.
</P>
<P>
	   ``They were slowing to take a left into the cemetery and they were
rear-ended by the semi,'' said state police Lt. Tim Baughman.
</P>
<P>
	   Baughman said he did not know how many people were in the eastbound van.
</P>
<P>
	   Ten people were taken to hospitals in Ruidoso and Roswell, hospital
representatives said. Three people were in critical condition.
</P>
<P>
	   The truck was hauling produce from San Simone, Ariz., to Ontario, Canada,
Baughman said.
</P>
<P>
	   The truck driver was among the injured, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The collision occurred on two-lane U.S. Highway 70 at Tinnie, a farming and
ranching community in a mountain valley about 200 miles southeast of
Albuquerque. The weather was dry and clear, Baughman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-08-00 1905 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000108.0235 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> With AM-Debate-Highlights, AM-Debate Text-Excerpts, moving on  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   JOHNSTON, Iowa (AP) - Bill Bradley accused Al Gore of trying to scare
Iowa voters with misrepresentations of his health care proposal on Saturday. The
vice president said he has not been hiding in a Washington bunker but
campaigning on "the front lines in the fight for our future."
<P>
	   Bradley got the last words, and used them to slap Gore on an issue central
in the farm state that will register the first Democratic decision of the 2000
presidential campaign, in party caucuses Jan. 24.
</P>
<P>
	   "Al's been hammering me on my agriculture votes 15 years ago," the former
New Jersey senator said. "But I would simply ask the family farmers of Iowa
today, are you better off than you were seven years ago or do we need a change?"
</P>
<P>
	   Despite a robust U.S. economy, the agriculture sector is suffering through
its worse downturn in more than a decade. Net farm income in Iowa is projected
at $40.4 billion in 2000, down $7.6 billion from 1999.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley's "better off" line echoed a theme used by Republican Ronald Reagan
in his winning, 1980 campaign, which Bradley has said he admires for its
concentration on big-issue proposals.
</P>
<P>
	   The contenders argued about health care, farm policy, education - a familiar
array after four prior Democratic presidential campaign debates - and Gore
revived his challenge for even more. He said they should meet twice a week,
scrap TV ads, and debate next in Iowa on agriculture policy.
</P>
<P>
	   "I know that you have said no, but as they say on that millionaire
television show, is that your final answer"?" he asked. Evidently so, because
Bradley ignored the question.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore had opened the debate with a rebuttal to Bradley's claim that he'd been
down in a Washington bunker in an administration trying to survive scandal and
impeachment. He said his seven years as vice president to President Clinton have
been a time of the greatest economic progress in American history.
</P>
<P>
	   "I want to start by telling you what we have been doing in that Washington
bunker," Gore said, saying the administration has delivered on health reform,
job creation and budget surpluses. The vice president said that as president, he
would deliver on those fronts and more. "That's not a bunker," he said, "Those
are the front lines in the fight for our future."
</P>
<P>
	   Gore said repeatedly that Bradley's health care proposal would end Medicaid
and leave the needy in Iowa and elsewhere without the coverage. Bradley said he
would replace it with a better plan.
</P>
<P>
	   That prompted Bradley's sharpest retort in a generally placid debate,
</P>
<P>
	   "What we have here is a scare tactic," he said. "... I reject that kind of
politics."
</P>
<P>
	   The debate was sponsored by the Des Moines Register, with editor Dennis
Ryerson as moderator. Televised nationally by CNN and C-Span, it was set in a
suburban public TV station before an invitation-only audience of 300 - including
some the candidates used to demonstrate points.
</P>
<P>
	   On agriculture, Bradley said family farmers have had no real help, "no
safety net whatsoever," from the current administration. The former New Jersey
senator said he wants policy changes to help small farmers. "You can talk about
the past, but I want to talk about the future," Bradley told Gore.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore said he could understand Bradley's reluctance to talk about the past,
saying his rival had voted against emergency aid to farmers in midwest floods,
and against subsidies for ethanol, a fuel derived from corn.
</P>
<P>
	   Both candidates talked tough on farm policies important in Iowa, demanding
that foreign markets be opened to genetically modified commodities. Europe and
Japan resist those products.
</P>
<P>
	   "We can't let Europe and Japan determine our farm policy," said Gore, who
said "sound science" should govern.
</P>
<P>
	   "The most important thing we can do is use our authority to petition to get
access to markets," said Bradley. "The problem with agriculture in America is
serious, in Iowa it's dead serious."
</P>
<P>
	   The latest Iowa poll showed the challenge facing Bradley; Gore led him by 21
percentage points in a survey for the Des Moines Register among Democrats who
said they intend to vote in the party caucuses two weeks from Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   The numbers: Gore 54 percent; Bradley 33 percent. The margin of error was
4.4 percentage points either way.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley acknowledged the deficit as he courted potential caucus-goers with a
post-debate lunch of meatballs and pasta. "Wouldn't it be great to be a part of
something that creates a big surprise?"
</P>
<P>
	   On the way to the debate, Gore stopped his motorcade outside a Titan Tire
Corp., to shake hands with picketing steel workers. "I want to fight for you as
president," he told them. "I need you to fight for me at the caucuses."
</P>
<P>
	   After the debate, Gore appeared with AFL-CIO Secretary-Treasurer Richard
Trumka before a crowd of 300 cheering union activists along with top officials
of other large unions.
</P>
<P>
	   Despite occasional differences on trade, Gore has the formal backing of
organized labor, an important tool in organization-based Iowa. "I'm keenly aware
of the fact that some of you are supporting me despite the fact that we don't
agree on every single issue," said Gore.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley had an eye on labor supporters, too, making of the point by
mentioning twice in the debate that he'd been at a Teamsters' picket line. The
AFL-CIO has endorsed Gore, but the Teamsters have not.
</P>
<P>
	   The day before, Bradley appeared on WHO-TV in Des Moines, and said he
disagrees with the government decision to return Elian Gonzalez, the 6-year-old
refugee, to Cuba. "I thought that the boy should stay in the United States,"
Bradley said. "... I think the courts should review it. The ideal situation
would be for the boy and his father to be in the United States."
</P>
<P>
	   The father is in Cuba and wants his son back. The controversy over the boy,
whose mother died trying to get to Florida, is a political headache for the
administration. The Immigration and Naturalization Service has ordered the boy
returned, stirring Cuban American demonstrations in Miami and Republican demands
that he stay. Gore says the courts should decide.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-08-00 1908 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
