<DOCNO> APW20000108.0239 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> SUBDIVIDED </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    Saturday, Jan. 8, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bradley, Gore Square Off in Debate
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   JOHNSTON, Iowa (AP) -- Bill Bradley and Al Gore argued about health care,
farm policy and education in their debate today -- themes now familiar after
four prior Democratic presidential campaign debates. Gore revived his challenge
to Bradley to hold even more debates. He said they should meet twice a week,
scrap TV ads, and debate next in Iowa on agriculture policy. "I know that you
have said no, but as they say on that millionaire television show, is that your
final answer"?" Gore asked. Evidently so, because Bradley ignored the question.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
WHO Pushes Tobacco Control Treaty
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- The World Health Organization chief warned that
tobacco could take a ghastly toll in developing countries unless nations act
swiftly to control the substance. Tobacco kills half its consumers, and could
take 10 million lives annually by 2030 with 70 percent from developing
countries, WHO Director General Gro Harlem Brundtland said Friday at a
conference in New Delhi. If countries do not act soon, tobacco will kill more
people in the next 30 years than the combined toll from malaria, tuberculosis
and child diseases, Brundtland warned.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Irish Record Shows 1969 Arms Demand
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) -- Three Northern Ireland legislators appealed to
Ireland for rifles to protect Catholics when sectarian violence erupted in the
British province three decades ago, according to government documents released
Saturday. Legislators turned up at the foreign ministry in Dublin on the night
of Aug. 30, 1969, to ask for smuggled arms, saying "a few hundred rifles" from
the Irish Army could "easily be lost and would not be missed," the records
showed. The three were members of a Northern Ireland assembly which was
dismantled by Britain because of the unrest.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Displaced Syrians Hope To Return
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) -- Syrian refugees displaced from the Israeli-occupied
Golan Heights celebrated the end of Ramadan on Saturday, visiting relatives and
taking their children for rides on a mini Ferris wheel set up in an empty lot. A
year from now, they hope, they'll be celebrating the same rituals to end the
Muslim month of fasting but in a different place-- on the land they fled after
Israel captured it during the 1967 Arab-Israeli War. The Middle East peace talks
in West Virginia have stirred their expectations. "I will leave soon and leave
everything behind," Ahmed Mustafa Diab said in Wafideen, a camp for displaced
people 11 miles east of Damascus.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Poll: Gore, Bush Lead in Iowa
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore has shored up his lead over
former Sen. Bill Bradley among Iowans planning to vote in the Democratic Party
caucuses this month, a new poll indicates. Among Republicans, it found George W.
Bush holding to his solid lead over five other candidates. The Des Moines
Register's poll of registered voters -- 500 Republicans and 501 Democrats --
found Gore with support of 54 percent, Bradley of 33 percent. Thirteen percent
said they were unsure or uncommitted.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Russian Troops Say Deaths Underreported
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   SLEPTSOVSKAYA, Russia (AP) -- In an effort to avoid public backlash against
its military actions in Chechnya, Russia is understating the number of its
soldiers killed in combat, soldiers claimed Saturday. In a series of interviews,
Russian soldiers in Chechnya and the adjoining region of Ingushetia claimed
their units had suffered numerous casualties that have not been reported. It was
not possible to obtain overall figures, but soldiers in some units said more
than half the men in their detachments had been killed or wounded in recent
weeks.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Cuban-Americans Halt Protests
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   MIAMI (AP) -- Cuban-American leaders, encouraged by a lawmaker's bid to keep
6-year-old Elian Gonzalez in the United States while a judge considers his case,
said today they would temporarily halt protests against plans to return the
child to Cuba. "We have called for a cautious, temporary hold of the civil
disobedience campaign," said Ramon Saul Sanchez, head of Democracy Movement.
About 100 protesters have been arrested since Thursday, and another protest had
been planned Monday to block access to Miami International Airport.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Redskins Beat Lions 27-13
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   LANDOVER, Md. (AP) -- Stephen Davis ran for 119 yards and two touchdowns to
lead the Washington Redskins to victory in their first playoff game in seven
years. Davis, playing despite a sore ankle, suffered a sprained knee five
minutes into the second quarter that put him out of the game. By then, the
Redskins already had a 17-point lead on the way to a 27-13 rout of the
mistake-prone Detroit Lions in an NFC wild-card game.
</P>
