<BODY>
<HEADLINE> War Crimes Suspect Denies Atrocities  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- A suspected Nazi war criminal on Sunday told an
Australian radio station that he did not participate in mass killings in Latvia
during World War II.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Never, never, I have done nothing of the kind, I have never participated
in anything like that,'' Konrad Kalejs told Australia's Special Broadcasting
Service.
</P>
<P>
	   Latvian-born Kalejs, 86, arrived in Australia on Friday. He fled Britain,
where he had been living, after authorities launched proceedings to deport him
for alleged wartime atrocities.
</P>
<P>
	   Kalejs is accused of belonging to the Arajs Kommando squad responsible for
the death of 30,000 people, mostly Jews, in Latvia during World War II. He has
denied the allegations and described his accusers as ``liars and storytellers.''
</P>
<P>
	   Kalejs told SBS radio he had been a student and a Latvian officer during the
war but had never been where civilians were murdered.
</P>
<P>
	   Federal Justice Minister Amanda Vanstone said Saturday the Australian
government would examine evidence against Kalejs supplied by the British
government.
</P>
<P>
	   Jewish organizations have urged the Australian government to reopen
investigations into Kalejs, despite previous probes that failed to turn up
enough evidence to send him to trial.
</P>
<P>
	   Kalejs said he commanded a skiing platoon in 1942 and that he became a
student in 1944 after he was released from military duty because of stomach
ulcers.
</P>
<P>
	   Kalejs migrated to Australia after World War II and was granted citizenship
in 1957.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-08-00 2014 </TRAILER>
