<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ecuador Military Denies Coup Rumor  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUITO, Ecuador (AP) -- Ecuador's armed forces said Saturday it had no
intention of seizing power, despite rumors that the military planned a coup to
put an end to the political and economic chaos.
</P>
<P>
	   The military high command issued a statement expressing support for
Ecuador's democratically elected government after a seven-hour meeting.
</P>
<P>
	   Radio stations speculated throughout the day that military commanders were
meeting to decide whether to forcibly remove President Jamil Mahuad from office
or join in an alliance with him to shut down Congress, which has blocked many of
his attempted reforms.
</P>
<P>
	   The armed forces ``reject any attempt to violate constitutional order,'' the
military statement said, without elaborating.
</P>
<P>
	   The show of support came a day after President Clinton phoned the embattled
Mahuad to voice confidence in his ability to resolve the nation's worst economic
crisis since the 1920s. The nation's economy shrank 7 percent and inflation
topped 60 percent last year as Ecuador's currency, the sucre, plummeted.
</P>
<P>
	   Roman Catholic Church leaders on Friday also expressed support for the
government and rejected calls from leftist leaders for Mahuad to step down and
be replaced by a transitional government of church and labor leaders.
</P>
<P>
	   The military called on ``the powers of state, political parties and society
in general to seek solutions to the crisis within the constitutional and
democratic system.''
</P>
<P>
	   Over the last six months, the Harvard-educated Mahuad, a political centrist,
has faced growing calls to resign from political rivals and business and labor
leaders, who accuse him of incompetence in handling Ecuador's economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
	   Mahuad met all day with his Cabinet, awaiting the results of the military
meeting, aides said.
</P>
<P>
	   The president, who took office in August 1998, has said repeatedly that he
plans to serve out his term, which ends in January 2003.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-08-00 2022 </TRAILER>
