during World War II. "Never, never, I have done nothing of the kind, I have
never participated in anything like that," Konrad Kalejs told Australia's
Special Broadcasting Service. Latvian-born Kalejs, 86, arrived in Australia on
Friday. He fled Britain, where he had been living, after authorities launched
proceedings to deport him for alleged wartime atrocities. Kalejs is accused of
belonging to the Arajs Kommando squad responsible for the death of 30,000
people, mostly Jews, in Latvia during World War II.
</P>
