<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentine Officers Said Kidnappers  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- A group of retired Argentine naval officers
have been arrested for allegedly kidnapping children born to political prisoners
during the 1976-83 dictatorship, local reports said.
</P>
<P>
	   Argentine news agency Diarios y Noticias said six officers were arrested
late Friday in the coastal city of Mar del Plata, 250 miles south of Buenos
Aires, while a report in the daily Pagina/12 newspaper said nine former officers
had been detained. The arrests were first made public Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   Both reports said the arrests followed a Thursday raid on a naval base in
Mar del Plata, where the military had set up one of several detention centers
during the dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
	   Federal Judge Maria Servini ordered the arrests.
</P>
<P>
	   The former officers are suspected of taking 12 babies from political
prisoners held at the base, the reports said. Several officers are accused of
illegally adopting several of the babies.
</P>
<P>
	   Federal judges in Argentina are investigating whether there was a systematic
plan for the illicit adoption of more than 200 children born to dissidents held
captive during the military's campaign against leftists and political opponents.
</P>
<P>
	   The children's mothers are among at least 9,000 Argentines who vanished
during the ``dirty war.'' Human rights groups say the figure is closer to
30,000.
</P>
<P>
	   The investigation was prompted by a report from the Grandmothers of the
Plaza de Mayo, a human rights group that has identified some 60 children born to
dissidents who disappeared during the military regime.
</P>
<P>
	   Nine of the regime's top leaders are being held in the case, including
former Gen. Jorge Videla, the regime's first president, and former navy Chief
Adm. Emilio Massera, both leaders of the military junta that overthrew President
Isabel Peron in 1976 and ruled until 1983.
</P>
<P>
	   Many of the senior members of the dictatorship were sentenced to life in
prison in 1985 for human rights abuses. But President Carlos Menem pardoned the
imprisoned leaders, along with all middle- and senior-ranking officers, five
years later.
</P>
<P>
	   The move outraged human rights groups, who have since searched for ways to
bring the former military officials to justice. Charges of child kidnapping are
not covered by the presidential pardon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-08-00 2207 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000108.0248 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Buddhist Leader Visits Dalai Lama  </HEADLINE>
   By DEEPAK SHARMA Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DHARMSALA, India (AP) -- Still recuperating from an eight-day trek across
the Himalayas to escape Chinese-ruled Tibet, a teen-age Buddhist leader was all
smiles Saturday after a visit with the Dalai Lama.
</P>
<P>
	   The 17th Karmapa, wearing a dark brown monk's robe and light orange scarf,
grinned as he walked easily from the gate of the Dalai Lama's house to a yellow
car.
</P>
<P>
	   The teen-ager, who arrived unexpectedly at a hotel in this Indian city on
Wednesday, had been described by sources close to the Dalai Lama's
administration as exhausted and suffering from blistered feet and scratched
hands after his journey. He appeared well during the brief moments journalists
saw him Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   He left the Dalai Lama's headquarters before dawn on Sunday. His destination
was not immediately known.
</P>
<P>
	   His defection and that of five followers, including his 24-year-old sister,
a Buddhist nun, cheered Tibetan exiles, embarrassed Beijing and surprised the
Indian government. It is the most significant exodus since the Dalai Lama and
tens of thousands of Tibetans departed their homeland after a failed 1959
uprising against Chinese rule.
</P>
<P>
	   The Dalai Lama's administration-in-exile made its first public comment about
the defection Saturday. It has been quiet on the subject for fear of reprisals
in Tibet and out of consideration for India, which fought a war with China in
1962 but has recently enjoyed progress in trade relations.
</P>
<P>
	   ``He is 14 years old and he has undertaken a long and difficult journey. He
is not talking properly. He is very tired and very restless,'' said Kalong Tashi
Wangdi, minister for religion and culture in the Dalai Lama's administration.
</P>
<P>
	   Also Saturday, monks lined up to present the teen with mustard-yellow wool
shawls, mushrooms and other gifts while the Dalai Lama's guard service and
Indian state police watched closely.
</P>
<P>
	   The Karmapa, head of the Karma Kagyu religious order, escaped to India by
crossing Nepal on a route followed by most Tibetan refugees, said sources close
to the case who asked not to be named.
</P>
<P>
	   The Karmapa eluded his guards at the 800-year-old Tsurphu monastery in
central Tibet by saying he was going on retreat, the sources said. He and a few
followers set out across the mountains on Dec. 28, hiking along rocky paths
lined with thorny bushes.
</P>
<P>
	   Those close to the Dalai Lama's administration said the teen was frustrated
at not being allowed to meet with his teachers. Chinese authorities had
repeatedly denied a visa to his principle teacher, Tai Situ Rinpoche, who has a
monastery near Dharmsala.
</P>
<P>
	   The escape could prod the Chinese communist leadership to intensify an
already stern four-year campaign to purge Tibetan monasteries of Dalai Lama
supporters.
</P>
<P>
	   Tibetan officials said they would talk with the Karmapa next week to discuss
his plans for the future. The only outsider to have met him is a mid-ranking
official from India's foreign ministry, officials in the Dalai Lama's exile
government said.
</P>
<P>
	   The Karmapa's Kagyupa sect, known as the ``Black Hats,'' was once Tibet's
most politically powerful but was supplanted by the Gelugpa school of the Dalai
Lamas 350 years ago. Leaders of the Tibetan sects are revered as the
reincarnations of their predecessors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-08-00 2210 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000108.0249 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Triplets Born to Grandmother of 15  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   YAKIMA, Wash. (AP) -- A 54-year-old mother of eight who has 15 grandchildren
gave birth Saturday to triplets.
</P>
<P>
	   Arcelia Garcia gave birth by Caesarean section to three healthy girls at
about 5 p.m. at Yakima Valley Memorial Hospital.
</P>
<P>
	   The triplets, who weigh about 4 or 5 pounds each, were born within about
five minutes of each other.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It went very smoothly. Everything went as planned,'' said Francisco
Garcia, 34, one of Mrs. Garcia's sons.
</P>
<P>
	   All of Arcelia Garcia's eight children arrived in the hospital to be with
their mother.
</P>
<P>
	   Mrs. Garcia plans to return to work as a farmworker as soon as her health
and the babies allow, she said before the births.
</P>
<P>
	   Originally from Michoacan, Mexico, Mrs. Garcia and her family moved in 1976
to Sunnyside, a town about 30 miles southeast of Yakima, and she has been a U.S.
citizen since 1996.
</P>
<P>
	   A woman in her 50s pregnant with triplets is extremely rare, especially
without the aid of fertility drugs, said Tom Easterling, a maternal and fetal
medicine specialist at the University of Washington Medical Center. Garcia's
pregnancy was natural.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-08-00 2236 </TRAILER>
