<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 23:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Conner Guilty of Illegal Rudder Use  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   AUCKLAND, New Zealand (AP) -- Dennis Conner's Stars and Stripes won on the
water but lost in the committee room Sunday after having been found guilty of
using an illegal rudder in one of its previous America's Cup semifinals.
</P>
<P>
	The decision means Stars and Stripes, now in second place in the six-team
semifinals, could have points stripped from its total. That would harm its
chances of being one of the two teams to sail off for the right to face Team New
Zealand for the America's Cup.
</P>
<P>
	AmericaOne, which leads the standings, beat Le Defi Francais by 1 minute, 16
seconds, the identical time by which Prada beat America True, while Stars and
Stripes had a close encounter with Nippon, winning by only 10 seconds.
</P>
<P>
	An Australian-built rudder was used on Stars and Stripes in the first race of
the semifinals against Nippon, but was replaced that night and has not been used
since.
</P>
<P>
	The America's Cup arbitration panel ruled Sunday the use of a rudder built in
Australia breached article 19 of the cup protocol, the regulations governing cup
racing.
</P>
<P>
	Those rules require appendages to be built either in the home country -- the
United States for Stars and Stripes -- or the host country, New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
	Team Dennis Conner had argued the wording of the protocol was loose, and
allowed the challenge to use a rudder built anywhere.
</P>
<P>
	Technically, breaching the protocol also means Stars and Stripes cannot comply
with a requirement that the syndicate challenging for the America's Cup must
sign, declaring it has complied with all the rules for racing.
</P>
<P>
	That means Team Dennis Conner's challenge could be declared invalid, ending
their cup campaign. However, it is widely expected that Conner will be allowed
to stay in the race.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-08-00 2345 </TRAILER>
