<DOCTYPE> SUBDIVIDED </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    Saturday, Jan. 8, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Elian Gonzalez Protests Suspended
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   MIAMI (AP) -- Cuban-American leaders, encouraged by a lawmaker's bid to keep
6-year-old Elian Gonzalez in the United States while a judge considers his case,
said Saturday they would temporarily halt protests against plans to return the
child to Cuba. "We have called for a cautious, temporary hold of the civil
disobedience campaign," said Ramon Saul Sanchez, head of Democracy Movement.
About 100 protesters have been arrested since Thursday, and another protest had
been planned Monday to block access to Miami International Airport.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Urges Family Planning Funds
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal spending for contraception and other family
planning services in the United States would rise by $35 million, the largest
increase in two decades, under a proposal Saturday by President Clinton. The
president said the program will promote strong children, healthy families and
make abortion less frequent at home and abroad. In his weekly radio address,
Clinton said his 2001 budget proposal will include $35 million more for such
services in the United States. The White House said the money will not pay for
abortions.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Escaped Buddhist Leader Visits Dalai Lama
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   DHARMSALA, India (AP) -- Still recuperating from an eight-day trek across
the Himalayas to escape Chinese-ruled Tibet, a teen-age Buddhist leader was all
smiles Saturday after a visit with the Dalai Lama. The 17th Karmapa, wearing a
dark brown monk's robe and light orange scarf, grinned as he walked easily from
the gate of the Dalai Lama's house to a yellow car. The teen-ager, who arrived
unexpectedly at a hotel in this Indian city on Wednesday, had been described by
sources close to the Dalai Lama's administration as exhausted and suffering from
blistered feet and scratched hands after his journey. He appeared well during
the brief moments journalists saw him Saturday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ex-Argentine Officers Arrested As Kidnappers
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- A group of retired Argentine naval officers
have been arrested for allegedly kidnapping children born to political prisoners
during the 1976-83 dictatorship, local reports said. Argentine news agency
Diarios y Noticias said six officers were arrested late Friday in the coastal
city of Mar del Plata, 250 miles south of Buenos Aires, while a report in the
daily Pagina/12 newspaper said nine former officers had been detained. The
arrests were first made public Saturday. Both reports said the arrests followed
a Thursday raid on a naval base in Mar del Plata, where the military had set up
one of several detention centers during the dictatorship.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Arafat Calls for Advancement of Talks
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   GAZA CITY, Gaza Strip (AP) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat on Saturday
called on President Clinton, currently mediating Israeli-Syrian peace talks, to
push Israeli-Palestinian negotiations forward. Arafat made the request after
receiving holiday telephone calls from Clinton and Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak, who were in Sheperdstown, W.Va., for the talks with Syria. During their
phone conversation, Barak and Arafat agreed to meet after the Palestinian leader
returns from a meeting with Clinton in Washington on Jan. 20, Arafat aide Nabil
Abourdeneh told the Palestinian News Agency WAFA.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
FBI Allegedly Misled Spy Suspect
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal investigators questioning fired nuclear physicist
Wen Ho Lee told him that he'd failed a lie-detector test that he'd actually
fared very well on, The Washington Post reported today. During a long
interrogation, FBI agents pressed Lee to confess passing nuclear weapons secrets
to China. Lee, however, denied that and insisted he was telling the truth and
was never told by his interrogators that polygraph operators had in fact given
him a very high score for honesty. The Post obtained a transcript of the March 7
interrogation, which was recorded by the FBI.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Libya-Bound Arms Seized in U.K.
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   LONDON (AP) -- Components of Scud missiles capable of carrying chemical or
biological warheads were illegally smuggled into Britain and seized before their
shipment to Libya, a British customs official said Saturday. A Customs and
Excise official said crates carrying the missile components were found at
Gatwick Airport, south of London, and were bound for Tripoli. The official, who
spoke on condition of anonymity, said an investigation was being conducted and
that no further details were being immediately released.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Spurs Beat Magic 127-92
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- Tim Duncan scored 22 points as the San Antonio Spurs
routed the Orlando Magic 127-92 on Saturday night. The NBA champion Spurs put
the Magic away early, using a 24-0 run to take a 27-4 lead before the Magic made
a field goal. Orlando, coached by former Spurs player Doc Rivers, missed its
first nine shots from the field and had six turnovers before Monty Williams made
a layup with 3:39 left in the first period.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Els, Woods Tied in Mercedes Tourney
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   KAPALUA, Hawaii (AP) -- Two days ago, Ernie Els wasn't even sure if he was
in the same league as Tiger Woods -- he proved today he was up to the challenge.
In a near flawless round of golf against the No. 1 player in the world, the
South African known as the "Big Easy" got down to business with a 6-under 67
that erased a four-stroke deficit and left him tied with Woods after three
rounds in the Mercedes Championship.
</P>
</TEXT>
